{"title_page": "Catholic University of Leuven (1834\u20131968)", "text_new": "{{Other uses|University of Leuven (disambiguation)}}\n[[File:Gregory XVI.jpg|thumb|Pope [[Gregory XVI]], co-founder of the [[Catholic University of Malines]], which would later become the Catholic University of Leuven]]\nThe '''Catholic University of Leuven''' was founded in 1834 in [[Mechelen]] as the [[Catholic University of Belgium]], and moved its seat to the town of [[Leuven]] in 1835, changing its name to Catholic University of Leuven.<ref>''Encyclop\u00e9die th\u00e9ologique'', tome 54, ''Dictionnaire de l'histoire universelle de l'\u00c9glise'', Paris : \u00e9d. J.P. Migne, 1863, ''sub verbo'' ''Gr\u00e9goire XVI'', col. 1131 : \"Apr\u00e8s sa s\u00e9paration de la Hollande en 1830, la Belgique lib\u00e9rale a vu son \u00c9glise jouir d'une v\u00e9ritable ind\u00e9pendance. Les \u00e9v\u00eaques s'assemblent en conciles, communiquent avec le Saint-Si\u00e8ge en toute libert\u00e9. Sur l'article fondamental des \u00e9tudes, ils ont fond\u00e9 l'universit\u00e9 catholique de Louvain, o\u00f9 les jeunes Belges vont en foule puiser aux sources les plus pures toutes les richesses de la science\". And : Edward van Even, ''Louvain dans le pass\u00e9 et dans le pr\u00e9sent'', Louvain, 1895, p. 606 : \"''Par lettre collective du 14 novembre 1833, le corps \u00e9piscopal s'adressa \u00e0 Gr\u00e9goire XVI, \u00e0 l'effet d'obtenir l'autorisation n\u00e9cessaire pour ouvrir l'\u00e9cole. Cette autorisation fut octroy\u00e9e par un bref du 13 d\u00e9cembre suivant. Une circulaire \u00e9piscopale, dat\u00e9e du 20 f\u00e9vrier 1834, annon\u00e7a aux fid\u00e8les la fondation d'une Universit\u00e9 catholique''\".</ref>\n\n== History ==\n[[File:Pierre de Ram 1836.png|thumb|250 px|[[Pierre de Ram]], first rector of the new [[Catholic University of Belgium]]]]\n[[File:Castle Arenberg, Katholieke Universiteit Leuven adj.jpg|thumb|Castle Arenberg, part of the University]]\nAn earlier [[Old University of Leuven|University of Leuven]] was founded in 1425 by [[John IV, Duke of Brabant]] and [[University charter|chartered]] by a [[papal bull]] of [[Pope Martin V]].<ref>{{cite web|title=About K.U.Leuven |url=http://www.kuleuven.be/about/history.html |publisher=[[Katholieke Universiteit Leuven]] |date=September 21, 2009 |accessdate=July 18, 2010 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110705023027/http://www.kuleuven.be/about/history.html |archivedate=July 5, 2011 }}</ref> It flourished for hundreds of years as the most prominent university in what would become Belgium, and one of the more prominent in Europe. Once formally integrated into the [[French First Republic|French Republic]], the law of 15 September 1793 had decreed the suppression of all the colleges and universities in France and it was abolished by Decree of the Departement of the Dijle on 25 October 1797.<ref>[[Jan Roegiers]] et al., ''Leuven University'', Leuven, Leuven University Press, 1990, p. 31: \"''With the Law of 3 Brumaire of Year IV, which reorganized higher education in the French Republic, there was no place for the University of Louvain, and it was abolished by Decree of the Departement of the Dijle on 25 october'' (1797)\".</ref>\n\nA new institution, the [[State University of Louvain]], was established in the city in 1816, but closed in 1835. With the closing of the State University, the Catholic University of Mechelen moved its seat to Leuven, adjusted its name and declared itself as a \"re-founding\" of the 1425 University of Leuven. This claim to continuity with the older institution was challenged in the courts, with [[Court of Cassation (Belgium)|Belgium's highest court]] issuing rulings (in 1844, 1855 and 1861) that the Catholic University of Leuven was a different institution created under a different charter.<ref>Several rulings of the Belgian Courts, of Cassation and Appel, forbid the identification of the Catholic University with the Old University: \"''L'universit\u00e9 catholique de Louvain ne peut \u00eatre consid\u00e9r\u00e9e comme continuant l'ancienne universit\u00e9 de Louvain; et lorsqu'un acte de fondation a d\u00e9sign\u00e9 pour collateur un professeur de cette ancienne universit\u00e9, il y a lieu d'y pourvoir par le gouvernement''\", (''Table g\u00e9n\u00e9rale alphab\u00e9tique et chronologique de la Pasicrisie Belge contenant la jurisprudence du Royaume de 1814 \u00e0 1850'', Bruxelles, 1855, p. 585, colonne 1, alinea 2. Voir \u00e9galement: ''Bulletin Usuel des Lois et Arr\u00eat\u00e9s'', 1861, p.166.)\n\nSee also the ruling of the ''Cour d'Appel'' of 1844: ''La Belgique Judiciaire'', 28 july 1844 n\u00b0 69, p. 1 : \"''Cour d\u2019Appel de Bruxelles. Deuxi\u00e8me chambre. L'universit\u00e9 libre de Louvain ne repr\u00e9sente pas l\u00e9galement l\u2019antique universit\u00e9 de cette ville. Attendu que cette universit\u00e9 (l\u2019ancienne Universit\u00e9 de Louvain), institu\u00e9e par une bulle papale, de concert avec l'autorit\u00e9 souveraine, formait un corps reconnu dans l'\u00c9tat, ayant diff\u00e9rentes attributions, dont plusieurs m\u00eame lui \u00e9taient d\u00e9l\u00e9gu\u00e9es par le pouvoir civil; Attendu que ce corps a \u00e9t\u00e9 supprim\u00e9 par les lois de la r\u00e9publique fran\u00e7aise; Attendu que l'universit\u00e9 existant actuellement \u00e0 Louvain ne peut \u00eatre consid\u00e9r\u00e9e comme continuant celle qui existait en 1457, ces deux \u00e9tablissemens ayant un caract\u00e8re bien distinct, puisque l'universit\u00e9 actuelle, non reconnue comme personne civile, n'est qu'un \u00e9tablissement tout-\u00e0-fait priv\u00e9, r\u00e9sultat de la libert\u00e9 d'enseignement, en dehors de toute action du pouvoir et sans autorit\u00e9 dans l'\u00c9tat...''\".</ref>  Nonetheless, the Catholic University of Leuven is very frequently identified as a continuation of the older institution.<ref name=CE/>\n\nIn 1968, the Catholic University of Leuven split to form two institutions:\n* [[Katholieke Universiteit Leuven]], Dutch-speaking, situated primarily in [[Leuven]]; and\n* [[Universit\u00e9 catholique de Louvain]], French-speaking, situated primarily in nearby [[Louvain-la-Neuve]].\n\nThis entry deals with the three historic university/universities established in the town of Leuven, 1425\u20131797, 1817\u20131835 and 1834\u20131968. For the current successor institutions and their separate development since 1968, see the individual articles linked above.\n\n==Timeline==\n\n===The Old University (1425\u20131797)===\n{{Main|Old University of Leuven}}\nIn the 15th century the city of Leuven, with the support of [[John IV, Duke of Brabant]], made a formal request to the [[Holy See]] for a university.<ref name=CE>{{CathEncy|wstitle=University of Louvain}}</ref> [[Pope Martin V]] issued a [[papal bull]] dated 9 December 1425 founding the University in Leuven as a ''Studium Generale''. In its early years, the university was modelled on those of [[Paris]], [[Cologne]] and [[Vienna]].  The university flourished in the 16th century due to the presence of famous scholars and professors, such as Adriaan Florenszoon Boeyens ([[Pope Adrian VI]]), [[Desiderius Erasmus]], [[Johannes Molanus]], [[Joan Llu\u00eds Vives]], [[Andreas Vesalius]], [[Ferdinand Verbiest]] and [[Gerardus Mercator]].\n\nIn the time of the [[French Directory|Directory]], by the [[Treaty of Campo Formio]], this region was ceded to the [[French Republic]] by [[Austria]] in exchange for the [[Republic of Venice]].<ref>Jules Delhaize, ''La domination fran\u00e7aise en Belgique'', Bruxelles, 1909, tome III, p. 171 : \"'' Les articles 3 et 4 du trait\u00e9 de Campo-Formio consacr\u00e8rent enfin, au point de vue international, la r\u00e9union de la Belgique \u00e0 la France. Voici ces articles. Art. 3 - Sa Majest\u00e9 l'Empereur, Roi de Hongrie et de Boh\u00eame, renonce pour elle et ses successeurs en faveur de la R\u00e9publique fran\u00e7aise, \u00e0 tous ses droits et titres sur les ci-devant provinces belgiques, connues sous le nom de Pays-Bas autrichiens. La R\u00e9publique fran\u00e7aise poss\u00e9dera ces pays \u00e0 perp\u00e9tuit\u00e9, en toute souverainet\u00e9 et propri\u00e9t\u00e9, et avec tous les biens territoriaux qui en d\u00e9pendent'\".</ref> Once formally integrated into the French Republic, a law from 1793 which mandated that all universities in France be closed came into effect. The University of Leuven was abolished by decree of the [[Dyle (department)|D\u00e9partement of Dijle]] on October 25, 1797.<ref>[[Jan Roegiers]] et al., ''Leuven University'', Leuven, Leuven University Press, 1990, p. 31: \"''With the Law of 3 Brumaire of Year IV, which reorganized higher education in the French Republic, there was no place for the University of Louvain, and it was abolished by Decree of the Departement of the Dijle on 25 octobre'' (1797)\".</ref>\n\n===The State University (1816\u20131835)===\n{{Main|State University of Leuven}}\n\nThe region next became part of the [[United Kingdom of the Netherlands]] (1815\u20131830), and [[William I of the Netherlands]] founded a new university in 1816 in Leuven as a state university ({{lang-nl|Rijksuniversiteit}}).\n\n===Catholic University (1834\u20131968)===\n* In 1830, Belgium was formed as a new nation out of the Southern Provinces of the Netherlands.\n* The 8 November 1834, after an official [[Papal brief]] on 13 December 1833 of Pope [[Gregory XVI]],<ref>Edward van Even, ''Louvain dans le pass\u00e9 et dans le pr\u00e9sent'', Louvain, 1895, p. 606 : \"Par lettre collective du 14 novembre 1833, le corps \u00e9piscopal s'adressa \u00e0 Gr\u00e9goire XVI, \u00e0 l'effet d'obtenir l'autorisation n\u00e9cessaire pour ouvrir l'\u00e9cole. Cette autorisation fut octroy\u00e9e par un bref du 13 d\u00e9cembre suivant. Une circulaire \u00e9piscopale, dat\u00e9e du 20 f\u00e9vrier 1834, annon\u00e7a aux fid\u00e8les la fondation d'une Universit\u00e9 catholique\".</ref> the Belgian bishops founded a new [[Roman Catholic]] [[Catholic University of Mechelen|university]] at [[Mechelen]]. The announcement of the bishops' founding of the University in Mechelen provoked serious riots in the cities of [[Ghent]], [[Leuven]] and [[Li\u00e8ge|Liege]].<ref>John Bartier, Guy Cambier, ''Lib\u00e9ralisme et socialisme au XIXe si\u00e8cle'', Universit\u00e9 libre de Bruxelles, Institut d'histoire du christianisme, 1981, p. 17. And Emiel Lamberts and [[Jan Roegiers]], Leuven University, Louvain, 1990, p. 194 : \"There were demonstrations in protest, especially at Ghent and Louvain\" (...) \" and the Liberals responded by setting up a parallel university in Brussels\".</ref> <br />The first rector was [[Pierre de Ram]].<ref>P\u00e8re V. De Buck S.J., ''Mgr de Ram, recteur magnifique de l'universit\u00e9 catholique de Louvain'', Paris : Ch. Douniol, 1865 : \"Naturellement, on songea \u00e0 lui pour lui confier une charge dans l'universit\u00e9 catholique dont on projetait la fondation. On n'a pas \u00e9crit jusqu'ici et nous ne rechercherons pas qui, le premier, osa concevoir cette id\u00e9e, une des plus hardies qui aient jamais \u00e9t\u00e9 mises \u00e0 ex\u00e9cution. Le pays est petit, et il poss\u00e9dait d\u00e9j\u00e0 trois universit\u00e9s soutenues par l'autorit\u00e9 et l'argent du gouvernement (\u2026.)et de faire appr\u00e9cier les \u00e9normes difficult\u00e9s qui s'attachaient \u00e0 la fondation de l'universit\u00e9 catholique\".</ref>\n*In 1835 the recently founded [[Catholic University of Mechlin]] moved to Leuven, and changed its name to Catholic University of Leuven, where the State University had been closed. This is nowadays generally seen as a refounding of the old University of Leuven,<ref name=CE/>{{failed verification|reason=Does not support e claim that it \"is nowadays generally seen as a refounding of the old University of Leuven\"|date=August 2019}} although the Belgian [[Court of Cassation (Belgium)|Court of Cassation]] has ruled that the two entities are legally distinct,<ref>''Table g\u00e9n\u00e9rale alphab\u00e9tique et chronologique de la Pasicrisie Belge contenant la jurisprudence du Royaume de 1814 \u00e0 1850'', Brussels, 1855, p. 585, column 1, alinea 2. See also: ''Bulletin Usuel des Lois et Arr\u00eat\u00e9s'', 1861, p.166</ref> and at the time, Liberals protested the attempts of the new Catholic university to usurp the heritage<ref>''Discussion de la loi sur l'enseignement sup\u00e9rieur du 27 septembre 1835, et de la loi sur le jury d'examen du 8 avril 1844 : pr\u00e9c\u00e9d\u00e9e d'un aper\u00e7u historique sur l'organisation universitaire en Belgique'', Bruxelles : Th. Lesigne, 1844, p.1143 : \u00ab M. d'ELHOUGNE (d\u00e9put\u00e9) : Messieurs, permettez-moi de r\u00e9tablir la v\u00e9rit\u00e9 des faits. Entre l'ancienne Universit\u00e9 de Louvain, dont la gloire appartient \u00e0 toute la Belgique, et l'universit\u00e9 catholique, la filiation me para\u00eet quelque peu douteuse. Il y a plus d'une solution de continuit\u00e9 dans la g\u00e9n\u00e9alogie. Ce n'est pas comme h\u00e9riti\u00e8re l\u00e9gitime que l'universit\u00e9 catholique a recueilli la succession de l'universit\u00e9 de Louvain, elle s'est empar\u00e9e d'une succession en desh\u00e9rence \u00bb [https://books.google.fr/books?id=16ZEAAAAcAAJ&printsec=frontcover&hl=fr#v=onepage&q&f=false Lire en ligne].</ref> and identity of the historical University of Leuven.<ref>{{in lang|fr}} [[Maurice Voituron]], ''Le parti lib\u00e9ral jou\u00e9 par le parti catholique dans la question de l'enseignement sup\u00e9rieur'', Brussels, 1850: \"''et alors aurait paru plus \u00e9vidente encore aux yeux du pays l'intention du parti catholique de tuer l'enseignement de l'\u00c9tat, afin de ne laisser debout que l'Universit\u00e9 catholique de Malines, qui allait prendre le titre d'Universit\u00e9 de Louvain, pour y usurper la renomm\u00e9e de l'ancienne, ainsi que ses fondations de bourses. Cependant, malgr\u00e9 lui, le parti catholique laissa \u00e9chapper cet espoir par la bouche de son rapporteur [[Adolphe Dechamps|M. Dechamps]], lorsqu'il disait: \"la confiance entourera de telle fa\u00e7on les \u00e9tablissements priv\u00e9s que les Universit\u00e9s de l'\u00c9tat, par exemple, deviendront \u00e0 peu pr\u00e8s d\u00e9sertes''\"</ref>\n* Thursday, November 3, 1859, the Catholic University celebrated 25 years of existence.<ref>''Souvenir du XXVe anniversaire de la fondation de l'Universit\u00e9 catholique: Novembre 1859'', Louvain, typographie Vanlinthout et Cie, 1860 : \"Inaugur\u00e9e \u00e0 Malines, le 4 novembre 1834, l'Universit\u00e9 catholique a c\u00e9l\u00e9br\u00e9 \u00e0 Louvain, le jeudi 3 novembre 1859, sa vingt-cinqui\u00e8me ann\u00e9e d'existence\"</ref> A banquet with more than five hundred guests offered by the students to the Rector and the faculty, took place the 23 November 1859 in the great festival hall of the Music Academy of Louvain.<ref>''Souvenir du XXVe anniversaire de la fondation de l'Universit\u00e9 catholique: Novembre 1859'', p. 24 : \"Banquet offert par les \u00e9tudiants au Recteur et au Corps professoral le 23 novembre\" ; and : Emiel Lamberts, [[Jan Roegiers]], ''et alii'', ''Leuven University'', \"The Catholic University\", Leuven, 1990, p. 199 (illustration 11)</ref>\n* In the year 1884 the Catholic University of Louvain celebrated solemnly its 50th anniversary.<ref>E. Descamps, in : ''Universit\u00e9 catholique de Louvain : Liber Memorialis : 1834\u20131884'', Louvain : Peeters, 1887, p. V : \"''les f\u00eates du cinquanti\u00e8me anniversaire de l'Universit\u00e9 catholique de Louvain ont eu un brillant \u00e9clat et un immense retentissement''\".</ref>\n* In 1909, the Catholic University celebrated its 75th anniversary, and struck a medal where for the first time it officially used the French word \"r\u00e9installation\" (ressetlement), and the Dutch word \"herstelling\" (restoration) beginning of a new \"official\" history.\n* In 1914, during [[World War I]], Leuven [[Rape of Belgium|was looted]] by German troops. They set fire to a large part of the city, effectively destroying about half of it. The library was lost, as well as about 300,000 books, about 1000 [[incunable|incunabula]];<ref>[http://www.unesco.org/webworld/mdm/administ/pdf/LOSTMEMO.PDF Lost Memory - Libraries and Archives Destroyed in the Twentieth Century] ( {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120905105742/http://www.unesco.org/webworld/mdm/administ/pdf/LOSTMEMO.PDF |date=5 September 2012 }})</ref> and a huge collection of [[manuscripts]], such as the [[Easter Island]] tablet bearing [[Rongorongo text E]] or [[cz:Bible leskovecko-dr\u00e1\u017e\u010fansk\u00e1|the oldest Czech Bible]] In the early stages of the war, Allied propaganda capitalized on the German destruction as a reflection on German ''Kultur''.\n\n====The split (1962\u20131970)====\n{{Unreferenced section|date=November 2010}}\n{{main|Split of the Catholic University of Leuven}}\nFrom its beginning in 1834, the Catholic University of Louvain provided lectures only in [[French language|French]]. Latin was sometimes used in the theology faculty, but it was essentially a French-language institution. Lectures in [[Dutch language|Dutch]], the other [[official language]] of Belgium and the language spoken in Leuven, began to be provided in 1930.\n\nIn 1962, in line with constitutional reforms governing official language use, the French and Dutch sections of the university became autonomous within a common governing structure. [[Flemish Movement|Flemish nationalists]] continued to demand a division of the university, and Dutch speakers expressed resentment at privileges given to French-speaking academic staff and the perceived disdain by the local French-speaking community for their Dutch-speaking neighbours. At the time, Brussels and Leuven were both part of the officially bilingual and now defunct [[Province of Brabant]]; but [[Francization of Brussels|unlike Brussels]], Leuven had retained its Dutch-speaking character. Tensions rose when a French-speaking [[Social geography|social geographer]] suggested in a televised lecture that the city of Leuven should be incorporated into an enlarged [[bilingual]] 'Greater-Brussels' region. Mainstream Flemish politicians and students began demonstrating under the slogan 'Leuven Vlaams \u2013 Walen Buiten' (\"Leuven [is] Flemish \u2013 [[Walloons]] out\"). Student demonstrations escalated into violence throughout the mid-1960s. Student unrest fueled by the [[Language legislation in Belgium|history of discrimination against Flemings]] eventually brought down the Belgian government in February 1968.\n\nThe dispute was resolved in June 1968 by turning the [[Dutch-language]] section of the university into the independent [[Katholieke Universiteit Leuven]], which remained in Leuven. The French-speaking university, called the [[Universit\u00e9 catholique de Louvain]], was moved to a [[Greenfield land|greenfield]] campus called [[Louvain-la-Neuve]] (\"New Leuven\"), farther south in the French-speaking part of the Province of Brabant. Acrimony about the split was long-lasting. Nowadays, however, research collaborations and student exchanges between the two \"sister universities\" take place with increasing frequency.\n\n==Library==\n[[File:Louvain Library WWI.jpg|thumb|The ruins of the library of the Catholic University of Leuven after the library was burned by the German army in 1914.]]\n\nThe holdings of the modern Catholic University of Leuven date back to 1834. Its main collections were held in a building on Naamsestraat dating back to the 17th century. It was only the collections of the university since its founding in 1834 that were lost. The manuscripts and most valuable works of the pre-revolutionary Old University, were transported<ref>''Leuven University'', p. 31: \"The university colleges were closed on 9 november 1797, and all items of use, with all the books, were requisitioned for the new \u00c9cole Centrale, in Brussels\"</ref> to the National Library in Paris, while the bulk of the holdings (at least officially) was transferred to the [[Central School of Brussels]], the official legal successor of the [[Old University of Leuven]]. The library of the Central School of Brussels had about 80,000 volumes, which then became part of the library of Brussels, and then the future [[Royal Library of Belgium]] where they are still found. The extensive archives of the Old University are now part of the State Archives in Belgium.<ref>[http://www.arch.be/ arch.be]{{Clarify|date=August 2013}}</ref>\n\n[[Image:Leuven-University-Library.jpg|thumb|The library building designed by [[Whitney Warren]] and built from 1921\u20131928, now the KUL's central library.]]\nFollowing the destruction of the library, a new library building was constructed on the [[Ladeuzeplein|Mgr. Ladeuzeplein]]. It was designed by the American architect [[Whitney Warren]] in a neo-Flemish-Renaissance style, and built between 1921 and 1928.<ref name=\"Impe2012\">{{cite book|author=Jan van Impe|title=De Leuvense universiteitsbibliotheek / druk 2: historische wandelgids|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=9WL5uPw3HiwC&pg=PT26|accessdate=29 June 2013|date=20 November 2012|publisher=Leuven University Press|isbn=978-90-5867-920-8|page=26}}</ref> Its monumental size is a reflection of the Allied victory against [[Germany]], and it is one of the largest university buildings in the city. The library's collections were rebuilt with donations from all around the world, outraged by the barbaric act which it had suffered. In 1940, during the second German invasion of Leuven, the building largely burnt down, including its 900,000 manuscripts and books. The building was rebuilt after the war in accordance with Warren's design.\n\nThe library's collections were again restored after the war, and by the fission in 1968 had approximately four million books.\nThe split of the university into separate French-language and Dutch-language institutions in 1968 entailed a division of the central library holdings.  This was done on the basis of alternate shelfmarks (except in cases where a work clearly belonged to one section or the other, e.g. was written by a member of faculty or bequeathed by an alumnus whose linguistic allegiance was clear). This gave rise to the [[factoid]] that encyclopedias and runs of periodicals were divided by volume between the two universities, but actually such series bear single shelfmarks.\n\nThe building on the Mgr. Ladeuzeplein is now the central library of the Katholieke Universiteit Leuven.\n\n==Notable alumni==\n* [[Theodor Schwann]] (1810\u20131882), developer of [[cell theory]] and discoverer of [[Schwann cells]] (professor)\n* [[Louis Defr\u00e9]] (aka Maurice Voituron) (1816\u20131880), lawyer and burgomaster of [[Uccle]]\n* [[Charles-Louis-Joseph-Xavier de la Vall\u00e9e-Poussin]] (1827\u20131903), a [[mineralogist]] and [[geologist]]\n* [[Auguste Marie Fran\u00e7ois Beernaert]] (1829\u20131912), [[Prime Minister of Belgium]] and winner of the [[Nobel Peace Prize]]\n* [[Patrick Francis Healy]] (1830\u20131910), president of [[Georgetown University]], first [[Jesuit]] priest of [[African American]] ancestry, first American of acknowledged African-American ancestry to earn PhD\n* [[Antanas Baranauskas]] (1835\u20131902), Lithuanian [[poet]].\n* [[Arthur Vierendeel]] (1852\u20131940) civil engineer.\n* [[E. J. Dillon|Emile Joseph Dillon]] (1854\u20131933), [[linguist]], author and journalist.\n* [[Albrecht Rodenbach]] (1856\u20131880), poet.\n* [[Albin van Hoonacker]] (1857\u20131933), Catholic [[theologian]] and Biblical scholar\n* [[Charles Jean de la Vall\u00e9e-Poussin]] (1866\u20131962), mathematician who proved the [[prime number theorem]].\n* [[Charles Terlinden]] (1878\u20141972), historian\n* [[Edgar Sengier]] (1879\u20131963), director of the [[Union Mini\u00e8re du Haut Katanga]].\n* [[Frans Van Cauwelaert]] (1880\u20131961), politician.\n* [[Jean-Baptiste Janssens]], S.J. (1889\u20131964), twenty-seventh Superior General of the [[Society of Jesus]].\n* [[Weng Wenhao]] (1889\u20131971), founder of modern Chinese [[geography]].\n* [[Georges Lema\u00eetre]] (1894\u20131966), [[astronomer]], priest and proposer of the [[Big Bang]] theory.\n* [[Fulton J. Sheen]] (1895\u20131979), American archbishop, television personality, and writer.\n* [[August De Boodt]] (1895\u20131986), politician.\n* [[Jerome D'Souza]], S.J. (1897\u20131977), educationist, member of Indian Constituent assembly, & four times Indian Delegate to the UNO.\n* [[Albert Claude]] (1899\u20131983), medical doctor and cell biologist, winner of [[Nobel Prize in Physiology or Medicine]]\n* [[Peter McKevitt]] (1900\u20131976), Irish priest, author and sociologist\n* [[Rafael \u00c1ngel Calder\u00f3n Guardia]] (1900\u20131970), physician, social reformer, president of [[Costa Rica]] 1940\u20131944\n* [[Alberto Hurtado]], (1901\u20131952), Chilean Jesuit priest, [[social worker]] and writer. Canonized in 2005.\n* [[Victor Delhez]], (1902\u20131985), engraver and artist.\n* [[Hendrik Elias]], (1902\u20131973), Flemish Nationalist, [[quisling]].\n* [[Maurice Anthony Biot]] (1905\u20131985), Belgian\u2013American [[physicist]] and the founder of the theory of poroelasticity.\n* [[L\u00e9on Degrelle]], (1906\u20131994), founder of [[Rexism]], [[quisling]].\n* [[Jean Charles Snoy et d'Oppuers]] (1907\u20131991), law, diplomat, businessman.\n* [[Dominique Pire]] (1910\u20131969), won [[Nobel Peace Prize]] for helping refugees in post-World War II Europe \n* [[Herman Van Breda]] (1911\u20131974), founder of the [[Husserl Archives]].\n* [[Andr\u00e9 Molitor]] (1911\u20132005), law, private secretary of [[Baudouin I of Belgium]].\n* [[Otto von Habsburg]] (1912\u20132011), heir to the thrones of [[Austria-Hungary]]; politician and writer.\n* [[Qian Xiuling]] (1912\u20132008), saved nearly 100 lives during World War II.\n* [[Tang Yuhan]], (1912\u20132014), Chinese [[oncologist]].\n* [[Pieter De Somer]] (1917\u20131985), first [[Rector (academia)|rector]] of the [[Katholieke Universiteit Leuven]].\n* [[Christian de Duve]] (1917\u20132013), [[Nobel Prize in Physiology or Medicine|Nobel Prize in Medicine]] 1974, for his discoveries concerning the structural and functional organization of the [[cell (biology)|cell]].\n* [[Anton van Wilderode]] (1919\u20131998), Flemish activist and writer.\n* [[Frans Van Coetsem]] (1919\u20132002), linguist.\n* [[Lode Van Den Bergh|Aster Berkhof]], (born 1920), Flemish writer.\n* [[Charles Mertens de Wilmars]] (1921\u20131994), psychiatrist, professor at [[Harvard Medical School]]\n* [[Malachi Martin]] (1921\u20131999), Irish writer.\n* [[Antoon Vergote]], also known as Antoine Vergote (1921\u20132013), Catholic priest, theologian, philosopher, [[psychologist]] and [[psychoanalyst]].\n* [[Tom\u00e1s \u00d3 Fiaich]] (1923\u20131990), Archbishop of Armagh.\n* [[Jan Zaprudnik]] (born 1926), Belarusian\u2013American [[historian]] and poet.\n* [[Geza Vermes]] (1924\u20132013), religious historian and [[translation|translator]] into English of the [[Dead Sea Scrolls]].\n* [[H. Narayan Murthy]] (1924\u20132011), Indian Psychologist, Philosopher and Scholar known for Behavioural Therapy.\n* [[Jos\u00e9 J. Fripiat]], a chemist, and laureate of the 1967 [[Francqui Prize]]\n* [[Gustavo Guti\u00e9rrez]] (born 1928), [[Peru]]vian [[Dominican Order|Dominican]] theologian, founder of [[Liberation Theology]].\n* [[Michael Hurley (Jesuit)|Michael Hurley]] (1923\u20132011), Irish Jesuit, co-founder of the [[Irish School of Ecumenics]]<ref name=rte>{{cite news |first=|last=|title=Father Michael Hurley dies aged 87 |url=http://www.rte.ie/news/2011/0415/hurleym.html |work=[[RT\u00c9 News and Current Affairs]] |publisher=|date=2011-04-16 |accessdate=2011-05-14}}</ref>\n* [[Adolphe Gesch\u00e9]] (1928\u20132003), theologian\n* [[Jacques Taminiaux]] (1928\u20132019), philosopher, 1977 laureate of the [[Francqui Prize]]\n* [[Camilo Torres Restrepo|Camilo Torres]] (1929\u20131966), Colombian priest and guerillero.\n* [[Jan Vansina]] (1929\u20132017), historian of Africa\n* [[Luce Irigaray]] (born 1930), French [[philosopher]], [[linguist]], [[psycholinguist]], [[psychoanalyst]], [[cultural theorist]], [[feminist]]. Graduated in 1954.\n* [[Marcel Lihau]] (1931\u20131999), first Congolese to receive a law degree, constitutionalist\n* [[Father Robert S. Smith]] (1932\u20132010), American Catholic priest, author, and educator.\n* [[Herman Van Den Berghe]] (born 1933), founder of the Centrum voor Menselijke Erfelijkheid (Belgian Centre for Human Heredity).\n* [[Thomas Kanza]] (1933\u20132004), one of the first Congolese university graduates, Congolese ambassador to the [[United Nations]].\n* [[Pierre Laconte]] (born 1934), a Belgian urbanist.\n* [[Abdul Qadeer Khan]] (born 1936), Pakistani [[metallurgist]] considered to be the father of Pakistan's nuclear weapons program.\n* [[Jacques van Ypersele de Strihou]] (born 1936), Minister of state, former Chief Cabinet of Albert II and Baudouin.\n* [[Renato Prada Oropeza]] (1937\u20132011), Mexican writer and [[Semiotics|semiotician]].\n* [[Jean Nguza Karl-i-Bond|Nguza Karl-i-Bond]] (1938\u20132003), notable [[Zaire|Zairian]] politician.<ref>Jeffrey M. Elliot and Mervyn M. Dymally, eds., ''Voices of Zaire: Rhetoric or Reality'', p. 53</ref>\n* [[Piet Van Waeyenberge]] (born 1938), economics, President of [[De Warande (Club)|De Warande]].\n* [[Robert Sokolowski]] (born 1939), American Catholic priest, and Professor of Philosophy at [[The Catholic University of America]].\n* [[Erik De Clercq]] (born 1941), [[physician]] and [[biologist]].\n* [[Bernard Lietaer]] (born 1942), economist and author.\n* [[Arthur Ulens]] (born 1946), chemistry and economics, businessman.\n* [[Herman Van Rompuy]] (born 1947), Belgian statesman and Prime Minister of Belgium. Appointed as the first [[President of the European Council]] in November 2009.\n\n==See also==\n{{Portal|Belgium|Catholicism}}\n* [[Academic libraries in Leuven]]\n* [[Catholic University of Mechlin]]\n* [[Collegium Trilingue]]\n* [[Katholieke Universiteit Leuven]]\n* [[Leuven Database of Ancient Books]]\n* [[Old University of Leuven]]\n* [[State University of Leuven]]\n* [[Universit\u00e9 catholique de Louvain]]\n* [[Universities in Leuven]]\n* [[Lovanium University]]\n\n== References ==\n{{reflist}}\n\n== Further reading ==\n* 1860: ''Souvenir du XXVe anniversaire de la fondation de l'Universit\u00e9 catholique: Novembre 1859'', Louvain, typographie Vanlinthout et Cie, 1860 [https://books.google.be/books?id=brlLAAAAcAAJ&printsec=frontcover&hl=fr#v=onepage&q&f=false ''Souvenir du XXVe anniversaire de la fondation de l'Universit\u00e9 catholique: Novembre 1859''].\n* 1887: ''Universit\u00e9 Catholique de Louvain : Liber Memorialis : 1834\u20131884'', Louvain : Peeters, 1887.\n* 1975: R. Mathes, ''L\u00f6wen und Rom. Zur Gr\u00fcndung der Katholischen Universit\u00e4t L\u00f6wen unter besonderer Ber\u00fccksichtigung der Kirchen-und Bildungspolitik Papst Gregors XVI'', Essen, 1975.\n* 2006: abb\u00e9 Andr\u00e9 Tihon: Article ''L\u00f6wen''. In: ''Lexikon f\u00fcr Theologie und Kirche'', vol. 6. Herder, Fribourg, B\u00e2le, Vienne, 3e \u00e9d., 2006, {{p.|1070\u20131073}}.\n* 2011: Pieter Dhondt, ''Un double compromis. Enjeux et d\u00e9bats relatifs \u00e0 l'enseignement universitaire en Belgique au XIXe si\u00e8cle'', Gand : Academia Press, 2011.\n\n{{Universities of Louvain}}\n{{Belgian universities}}\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{coord|50|40|11|N|4|36|44|E|source:kolossus-nlwiki|display=title}}\n[[Category:1834 establishments in Belgium]]\n[[Category:1968 disestablishments in Belgium]]\n[[Category:Catholic University of Leuven]]\n[[Category:Catholic University of Leuven before 1968| ]]\n[[Category:Catholic universities and colleges in Belgium|Leuven, Catholic University]]\n[[Category:Education in Leuven]]\n[[Category:Educational institutions established in the 15th century|Leuven, Catholic University]]\n[[Category:Educational institutions established in 1834|Leuven, Catholic University]]\n[[Category:Educational institutions established in 1968|Leuven, Catholic University]]\n[[Category:History of Leuven]]\n[[Category:Pontifical universities|Leuven, Catholic University of]]\n[[Category:Universities in Belgium|Leuven]]\n", "text_old": "{{Other uses|University of Leuven (disambiguation)}}\n[[File:Gregory XVI.jpg|thumb|Pope [[Gregory XVI]], co-founder of the [[Catholic University of Malines]], which would later become the Catholic University of Leuven]]\nThe '''Catholic University of Leuven''' was founded in 1834 in [[Mechelen]] as the [[Catholic University of Belgium]], and moved its seat to the town of [[Leuven]] in 1835, changing its name to Catholic University of Leuven.<ref>''Encyclop\u00e9die th\u00e9ologique'', tome 54, ''Dictionnaire de l'histoire universelle de l'\u00c9glise'', Paris : \u00e9d. J.P. Migne, 1863, ''sub verbo'' ''Gr\u00e9goire XVI'', col. 1131 : \"Apr\u00e8s sa s\u00e9paration de la Hollande en 1830, la Belgique lib\u00e9rale a vu son \u00c9glise jouir d'une v\u00e9ritable ind\u00e9pendance. Les \u00e9v\u00eaques s'assemblent en conciles, communiquent avec le Saint-Si\u00e8ge en toute libert\u00e9. Sur l'article fondamental des \u00e9tudes, ils ont fond\u00e9 l'universit\u00e9 catholique de Louvain, o\u00f9 les jeunes Belges vont en foule puiser aux sources les plus pures toutes les richesses de la science\". And : Edward van Even, ''Louvain dans le pass\u00e9 et dans le pr\u00e9sent'', Louvain, 1895, p. 606 : \"''Par lettre collective du 14 novembre 1833, le corps \u00e9piscopal s'adressa \u00e0 Gr\u00e9goire XVI, \u00e0 l'effet d'obtenir l'autorisation n\u00e9cessaire pour ouvrir l'\u00e9cole. Cette autorisation fut octroy\u00e9e par un bref du 13 d\u00e9cembre suivant. Une circulaire \u00e9piscopale, dat\u00e9e du 20 f\u00e9vrier 1834, annon\u00e7a aux fid\u00e8les la fondation d'une Universit\u00e9 catholique''\".</ref>\n\n== History ==\n[[File:Pierre de Ram 1836.png|thumb|250 px|[[Pierre de Ram]], first rector of the new [[Catholic University of Belgium]]]]\n[[File:Castle Arenberg, Katholieke Universiteit Leuven adj.jpg|thumb|Castle Arenberg, part of the University]]\nAn earlier [[Old University of Leuven|University of Leuven]] was founded in 1425 by [[John IV, Duke of Brabant]] and [[University charter|chartered]] by a [[papal bull]] of [[Pope Martin V]].<ref>{{cite web|title=About K.U.Leuven |url=http://www.kuleuven.be/about/history.html |publisher=[[Katholieke Universiteit Leuven]] |date=September 21, 2009 |accessdate=July 18, 2010 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110705023027/http://www.kuleuven.be/about/history.html |archivedate=July 5, 2011 }}</ref> It flourished for hundreds of years as the most prominent university in what would become Belgium, and one of the more prominent in Europe. Once formally integrated into the [[French First Republic|French Republic]], the law of 15 September 1793 had decreed the suppression of all the colleges and universities in France and it was abolished by Decree of the Departement of the Dijle on 25 octobre 1797.<ref>[[Jan Roegiers]] et al., ''Leuven University'', Leuven, Leuven University Press, 1990, p. 31: \"''With the Law of 3 Brumaire of Year IV, which reorganized higher education in the French Republic, there was no place for the University of Louvain, and it was abolished by Decree of the Departement of the Dijle on 25 october'' (1797)\".</ref>\n\nA new institution, the [[State University of Louvain]], was established in the city in 1816, but closed in 1835. With the closing of the State University, the Catholic University of Mechelen moved its seat to Leuven, adjusted its name and declared itself as a \"re-founding\" of the 1425 University of Leuven. This claim to continuity with the older institution was challenged in the courts, with [[Court of Cassation (Belgium)|Belgium's highest court]] issuing rulings (in 1844, 1855 and 1861) that the Catholic University of Leuven was a different institution created under a different charter.<ref>Several rulings of the Belgian Courts, of Cassation and Appel, forbid the identification of the Catholic University with the Old University: \"''L'universit\u00e9 catholique de Louvain ne peut \u00eatre consid\u00e9r\u00e9e comme continuant l'ancienne universit\u00e9 de Louvain; et lorsqu'un acte de fondation a d\u00e9sign\u00e9 pour collateur un professeur de cette ancienne universit\u00e9, il y a lieu d'y pourvoir par le gouvernement''\", (''Table g\u00e9n\u00e9rale alphab\u00e9tique et chronologique de la Pasicrisie Belge contenant la jurisprudence du Royaume de 1814 \u00e0 1850'', Bruxelles, 1855, p. 585, colonne 1, alinea 2. Voir \u00e9galement: ''Bulletin Usuel des Lois et Arr\u00eat\u00e9s'', 1861, p.166.)\n\nSee also the ruling of the ''Cour d'Appel'' of 1844: ''La Belgique Judiciaire'', 28 july 1844 n\u00b0 69, p. 1 : \"''Cour d\u2019Appel de Bruxelles. Deuxi\u00e8me chambre. L'universit\u00e9 libre de Louvain ne repr\u00e9sente pas l\u00e9galement l\u2019antique universit\u00e9 de cette ville. Attendu que cette universit\u00e9 (l\u2019ancienne Universit\u00e9 de Louvain), institu\u00e9e par une bulle papale, de concert avec l'autorit\u00e9 souveraine, formait un corps reconnu dans l'\u00c9tat, ayant diff\u00e9rentes attributions, dont plusieurs m\u00eame lui \u00e9taient d\u00e9l\u00e9gu\u00e9es par le pouvoir civil; Attendu que ce corps a \u00e9t\u00e9 supprim\u00e9 par les lois de la r\u00e9publique fran\u00e7aise; Attendu que l'universit\u00e9 existant actuellement \u00e0 Louvain ne peut \u00eatre consid\u00e9r\u00e9e comme continuant celle qui existait en 1457, ces deux \u00e9tablissemens ayant un caract\u00e8re bien distinct, puisque l'universit\u00e9 actuelle, non reconnue comme personne civile, n'est qu'un \u00e9tablissement tout-\u00e0-fait priv\u00e9, r\u00e9sultat de la libert\u00e9 d'enseignement, en dehors de toute action du pouvoir et sans autorit\u00e9 dans l'\u00c9tat...''\".</ref>  Nonetheless, the Catholic University of Leuven is very frequently identified as a continuation of the older institution.<ref name=CE/>\n\nIn 1968, the Catholic University of Leuven split to form two institutions:\n* [[Katholieke Universiteit Leuven]], Dutch-speaking, situated primarily in [[Leuven]]; and\n* [[Universit\u00e9 catholique de Louvain]], French-speaking, situated primarily in nearby [[Louvain-la-Neuve]].\n\nThis entry deals with the three historic university/universities established in the town of Leuven, 1425\u20131797, 1817-1835 and 1834\u20131968. For the current successor institutions and their separate development since 1968, see the individual articles linked above.\n\n==Timeline==\n\n===The Old University (1425\u20131797)===\n{{Main|Old University of Leuven}}\nIn the 15th century the city of Leuven, with the support of [[John IV, Duke of Brabant]], made a formal request to the [[Holy See]] for a university.<ref name=CE>{{CathEncy|wstitle=University of Louvain}}</ref> [[Pope Martin V]] issued a [[papal bull]] dated 9 December 1425 founding the University in Leuven as a ''Studium Generale''. In its early years, the university was modelled on those of [[Paris]], [[Cologne]] and [[Vienna]].  The university flourished in the 16th century due to the presence of famous scholars and professors, such as Adriaan Florenszoon Boeyens ([[Pope Adrian VI]]), [[Desiderius Erasmus]], [[Johannes Molanus]], [[Joan Llu\u00eds Vives]], [[Andreas Vesalius]], [[Ferdinand Verbiest]] and [[Gerardus Mercator]].\n\nIn the time of the [[French Directory|Directory]], by the [[Treaty of Campo Formio]], this region was ceded to the [[French Republic]] by [[Austria]] in exchange for the [[Republic of Venice]].<ref>Jules Delhaize, ''La domination fran\u00e7aise en Belgique'', Bruxelles, 1909, tome III, p. 171 : \"'' Les articles 3 et 4 du trait\u00e9 de Campo-Formio consacr\u00e8rent enfin, au point de vue international, la r\u00e9union de la Belgique \u00e0 la France. Voici ces articles. Art. 3 - Sa Majest\u00e9 l'Empereur, Roi de Hongrie et de Boh\u00eame, renonce pour elle et ses successeurs en faveur de la R\u00e9publique fran\u00e7aise, \u00e0 tous ses droits et titres sur les ci-devant provinces belgiques, connues sous le nom de Pays-Bas autrichiens. La R\u00e9publique fran\u00e7aise poss\u00e9dera ces pays \u00e0 perp\u00e9tuit\u00e9, en toute souverainet\u00e9 et propri\u00e9t\u00e9, et avec tous les biens territoriaux qui en d\u00e9pendent'\".</ref> Once formally integrated into the French Republic, a law from 1793 which mandated that all universities in France be closed came into effect. The University of Leuven was abolished by decree of the [[Dyle (department)|D\u00e9partement of Dijle]] on October 25, 1797.<ref>[[Jan Roegiers]] et al., ''Leuven University'', Leuven, Leuven University Press, 1990, p. 31: \"''With the Law of 3 Brumaire of Year IV, which reorganized higher education in the French Republic, there was no place for the University of Louvain, and it was abolished by Decree of the Departement of the Dijle on 25 octobre'' (1797)\".</ref>\n\n===The State University (1816\u20131835)===\n{{Main|State University of Leuven}}\n\nThe region next became part of the [[United Kingdom of the Netherlands]] (1815\u20131830), and [[William I of the Netherlands]] founded a new university in 1816 in Leuven as a state university ({{lang-nl|Rijksuniversiteit}}).\n\n===Catholic University (1834\u20131968)===\n* In 1830, Belgium was formed as a new nation out of the Southern Provinces of the Netherlands.\n* The 8 November 1834, after an official [[Papal brief]] on 13 December 1833 of Pope [[Gregory XVI]],<ref>Edward van Even, ''Louvain dans le pass\u00e9 et dans le pr\u00e9sent'', Louvain, 1895, p. 606 : \"Par lettre collective du 14 novembre 1833, le corps \u00e9piscopal s'adressa \u00e0 Gr\u00e9goire XVI, \u00e0 l'effet d'obtenir l'autorisation n\u00e9cessaire pour ouvrir l'\u00e9cole. Cette autorisation fut octroy\u00e9e par un bref du 13 d\u00e9cembre suivant. Une circulaire \u00e9piscopale, dat\u00e9e du 20 f\u00e9vrier 1834, annon\u00e7a aux fid\u00e8les la fondation d'une Universit\u00e9 catholique\".</ref> the Belgian bishops founded a new [[Roman Catholic]] [[Catholic University of Mechelen|university]] at [[Mechelen]]. The announcement of the bishops' founding of the University in Mechelen provoked serious riots in the cities of [[Ghent]], [[Leuven]] and [[Li\u00e8ge|Liege]].<ref>John Bartier, Guy Cambier, ''Lib\u00e9ralisme et socialisme au XIXe si\u00e8cle'', Universit\u00e9 libre de Bruxelles, Institut d'histoire du christianisme, 1981, p. 17. And Emiel Lamberts and [[Jan Roegiers]], Leuven University, Louvain, 1990, p. 194 : \"There were demonstrations in protest, especially at Ghent and Louvain\" (...) \" and the Liberals responded by setting up a parallel university in Brussels\".</ref> <br />The first rector was [[Pierre de Ram]].<ref>P\u00e8re V. De Buck S.J., ''Mgr de Ram, recteur magnifique de l'universit\u00e9 catholique de Louvain'', Paris : Ch. Douniol, 1865 : \"Naturellement, on songea \u00e0 lui pour lui confier une charge dans l'universit\u00e9 catholique dont on projetait la fondation. On n'a pas \u00e9crit jusqu'ici et nous ne rechercherons pas qui, le premier, osa concevoir cette id\u00e9e, une des plus hardies qui aient jamais \u00e9t\u00e9 mises \u00e0 ex\u00e9cution. Le pays est petit, et il poss\u00e9dait d\u00e9j\u00e0 trois universit\u00e9s soutenues par l'autorit\u00e9 et l'argent du gouvernement (\u2026.)et de faire appr\u00e9cier les \u00e9normes difficult\u00e9s qui s'attachaient \u00e0 la fondation de l'universit\u00e9 catholique\".</ref>\n*In 1835 the recently founded [[Catholic University of Mechlin]] moved to Leuven, and changed its name to Catholic University of Leuven, where the State University had been closed. This is nowadays generally seen as a refounding of the old University of Leuven,<ref name=CE/>{{failed verification|reason=Does not support e claim that it \"is nowadays generally seen as a refounding of the old University of Leuven\"|date=August 2019}} although the Belgian [[Court of Cassation (Belgium)|Court of Cassation]] has ruled that the two entities are legally distinct,<ref>''Table g\u00e9n\u00e9rale alphab\u00e9tique et chronologique de la Pasicrisie Belge contenant la jurisprudence du Royaume de 1814 \u00e0 1850'', Brussels, 1855, p. 585, column 1, alinea 2. See also: ''Bulletin Usuel des Lois et Arr\u00eat\u00e9s'', 1861, p.166</ref> and at the time, Liberals protested the attempts of the new Catholic university to usurp the heritage<ref>''Discussion de la loi sur l'enseignement sup\u00e9rieur du 27 septembre 1835, et de la loi sur le jury d'examen du 8 avril 1844 : pr\u00e9c\u00e9d\u00e9e d'un aper\u00e7u historique sur l'organisation universitaire en Belgique'', Bruxelles : Th. Lesigne, 1844, p.1143 : \u00ab M. d'ELHOUGNE (d\u00e9put\u00e9) : Messieurs, permettez-moi de r\u00e9tablir la v\u00e9rit\u00e9 des faits. Entre l'ancienne Universit\u00e9 de Louvain, dont la gloire appartient \u00e0 toute la Belgique, et l'universit\u00e9 catholique, la filiation me para\u00eet quelque peu douteuse. Il y a plus d'une solution de continuit\u00e9 dans la g\u00e9n\u00e9alogie. Ce n'est pas comme h\u00e9riti\u00e8re l\u00e9gitime que l'universit\u00e9 catholique a recueilli la succession de l'universit\u00e9 de Louvain, elle s'est empar\u00e9e d'une succession en desh\u00e9rence \u00bb [https://books.google.fr/books?id=16ZEAAAAcAAJ&printsec=frontcover&hl=fr#v=onepage&q&f=false Lire en ligne].</ref> and identity of the historical University of Leuven.<ref>{{in lang|fr}} [[Maurice Voituron]], ''Le parti lib\u00e9ral jou\u00e9 par le parti catholique dans la question de l'enseignement sup\u00e9rieur'', Brussels, 1850: \"''et alors aurait paru plus \u00e9vidente encore aux yeux du pays l'intention du parti catholique de tuer l'enseignement de l'\u00c9tat, afin de ne laisser debout que l'Universit\u00e9 catholique de Malines, qui allait prendre le titre d'Universit\u00e9 de Louvain, pour y usurper la renomm\u00e9e de l'ancienne, ainsi que ses fondations de bourses. Cependant, malgr\u00e9 lui, le parti catholique laissa \u00e9chapper cet espoir par la bouche de son rapporteur [[Adolphe Dechamps|M. Dechamps]], lorsqu'il disait: \"la confiance entourera de telle fa\u00e7on les \u00e9tablissements priv\u00e9s que les Universit\u00e9s de l'\u00c9tat, par exemple, deviendront \u00e0 peu pr\u00e8s d\u00e9sertes''\"</ref>\n* Thursday, November 3, 1859, the Catholic University celebrated 25 years of existence.<ref>''Souvenir du XXVe anniversaire de la fondation de l'Universit\u00e9 catholique: Novembre 1859'', Louvain, typographie Vanlinthout et Cie, 1860 : \"Inaugur\u00e9e \u00e0 Malines, le 4 novembre 1834, l'Universit\u00e9 catholique a c\u00e9l\u00e9br\u00e9 \u00e0 Louvain, le jeudi 3 novembre 1859, sa vingt-cinqui\u00e8me ann\u00e9e d'existence\"</ref> A banquet with more than five hundred guests offered by the students to the Rector and the faculty, took place the 23 November 1859 in the great festival hall of the Music Academy of Louvain.<ref>''Souvenir du XXVe anniversaire de la fondation de l'Universit\u00e9 catholique: Novembre 1859'', p. 24 : \"Banquet offert par les \u00e9tudiants au Recteur et au Corps professoral le 23 novembre\" ; and : Emiel Lamberts, [[Jan Roegiers]], ''et alii'', ''Leuven University'', \"The Catholic University\", Leuven, 1990, p. 199 (illustration 11)</ref>\n* In the year 1884 the Catholic University of Louvain celebrated solemnly its 50th anniversary.<ref>E. Descamps, in : ''Universit\u00e9 catholique de Louvain : Liber Memorialis : 1834\u20131884'', Louvain : Peeters, 1887, p. V : \"''les f\u00eates du cinquanti\u00e8me anniversaire de l'Universit\u00e9 catholique de Louvain ont eu un brillant \u00e9clat et un immense retentissement''\".</ref>\n* In 1909, the Catholic University celebrated its 75th anniversary, and struck a medal where for the first time it officially used the French word \"r\u00e9installation\" (ressetlement), and the Dutch word \"herstelling\" (restoration) beginning of a new \"official\" history.\n* In 1914, during [[World War I]], Leuven [[Rape of Belgium|was looted]] by German troops. They set fire to a large part of the city, effectively destroying about half of it. The library was lost, as well as about 300,000 books, about 1000 [[incunable|incunabula]];<ref>[http://www.unesco.org/webworld/mdm/administ/pdf/LOSTMEMO.PDF Lost Memory - Libraries and Archives Destroyed in the Twentieth Century] ( {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120905105742/http://www.unesco.org/webworld/mdm/administ/pdf/LOSTMEMO.PDF |date=5 September 2012 }})</ref> and a huge collection of [[manuscripts]], such as the [[Easter Island]] tablet bearing [[Rongorongo text E]] or [[cz:Bible leskovecko-dr\u00e1\u017e\u010fansk\u00e1|the oldest Czech Bible]] In the early stages of the war, Allied propaganda capitalized on the German destruction as a reflection on German ''Kultur''.\n\n====The split (1962\u20131970)====\n{{Unreferenced section|date=November 2010}}\n{{main|Split of the Catholic University of Leuven}}\nFrom its beginning in 1834, the Catholic University of Louvain provided lectures only in [[French language|French]]. Latin was sometimes used in the theology faculty, but it was essentially a French-language institution. Lectures in [[Dutch language|Dutch]], the other [[official language]] of Belgium and the language spoken in Leuven, began to be provided in 1930.\n\nIn 1962, in line with constitutional reforms governing official language use, the French and Dutch sections of the university became autonomous within a common governing structure. [[Flemish Movement|Flemish nationalists]] continued to demand a division of the university, and Dutch speakers expressed resentment at privileges given to French-speaking academic staff and the perceived disdain by the local French-speaking community for their Dutch-speaking neighbours. At the time, Brussels and Leuven were both part of the officially bilingual and now defunct [[Province of Brabant]]; but [[Francization of Brussels|unlike Brussels]], Leuven had retained its Dutch-speaking character. Tensions rose when a French-speaking [[Social geography|social geographer]] suggested in a televised lecture that the city of Leuven should be incorporated into an enlarged [[bilingual]] 'Greater-Brussels' region. Mainstream Flemish politicians and students began demonstrating under the slogan 'Leuven Vlaams \u2013 Walen Buiten' (\"Leuven [is] Flemish \u2013 [[Walloons]] out\"). Student demonstrations escalated into violence throughout the mid-1960s. Student unrest fueled by the [[Language legislation in Belgium|history of discrimination against Flemings]] eventually brought down the Belgian government in February 1968.\n\nThe dispute was resolved in June 1968 by turning the [[Dutch-language]] section of the university into the independent [[Katholieke Universiteit Leuven]], which remained in Leuven. The French-speaking university, called the [[Universit\u00e9 catholique de Louvain]], was moved to a [[Greenfield land|greenfield]] campus called [[Louvain-la-Neuve]] (\"New Leuven\"), farther south in the French-speaking part of the Province of Brabant. Acrimony about the split was long-lasting. Nowadays, however, research collaborations and student exchanges between the two \"sister universities\" take place with increasing frequency.\n\n==Library==\n[[File:Louvain Library WWI.jpg|thumb|The ruins of the library of the Catholic University of Leuven after the library was burned by the German army in 1914.]]\n\nThe holdings of the modern Catholic University of Leuven date back to 1834. Its main collections were held in a building on Naamsestraat dating back to the 17th century. It was only the collections of the university since its founding in 1834 that were lost. The manuscripts and most valuable works of the pre-revolutionary Old University, were transported<ref>''Leuven University'', p. 31: \"The university colleges were closed on 9 november 1797, and all items of use, with all the books, were requisitioned for the new \u00c9cole Centrale, in Brussels\"</ref> to the National Library in Paris, while the bulk of the holdings (at least officially) was transferred to the [[Central School of Brussels]], the official legal successor of the [[Old University of Leuven]]. The library of the Central School of Brussels had about 80,000 volumes, which then became part of the library of Brussels, and then the future [[Royal Library of Belgium]] where they are still found. The extensive archives of the Old University are now part of the State Archives in Belgium.<ref>[http://www.arch.be/ arch.be]{{Clarify|date=August 2013}}</ref>\n\n[[Image:Leuven-University-Library.jpg|thumb|The library building designed by [[Whitney Warren]] and built from 1921\u20131928, now the KUL's central library.]]\nFollowing the destruction of the library, a new library building was constructed on the [[Ladeuzeplein|Mgr. Ladeuzeplein]]. It was designed by the American architect [[Whitney Warren]] in a neo-Flemish-Renaissance style, and built between 1921 and 1928.<ref name=\"Impe2012\">{{cite book|author=Jan van Impe|title=De Leuvense universiteitsbibliotheek / druk 2: historische wandelgids|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=9WL5uPw3HiwC&pg=PT26|accessdate=29 June 2013|date=20 November 2012|publisher=Leuven University Press|isbn=978-90-5867-920-8|page=26}}</ref> Its monumental size is a reflection of the Allied victory against [[Germany]], and it is one of the largest university buildings in the city. The library's collections were rebuilt with donations from all around the world, outraged by the barbaric act which it had suffered. In 1940, during the second German invasion of Leuven, the building largely burnt down, including its 900,000 manuscripts and books. The building was rebuilt after the war in accordance with Warren's design.\n\nThe library's collections were again restored after the war, and by the fission in 1968 had approximately four million books.\nThe split of the university into separate French-language and Dutch-language institutions in 1968 entailed a division of the central library holdings.  This was done on the basis of alternate shelfmarks (except in cases where a work clearly belonged to one section or the other, e.g. was written by a member of faculty or bequeathed by an alumnus whose linguistic allegiance was clear). This gave rise to the [[factoid]] that encyclopedias and runs of periodicals were divided by volume between the two universities, but actually such series bear single shelfmarks.\n\nThe building on the Mgr. Ladeuzeplein is now the central library of the Katholieke Universiteit Leuven.\n\n==Notable alumni==\n* [[Theodor Schwann]] (1810\u20131882), developer of [[cell theory]] and discoverer of [[Schwann cells]] (professor)\n* [[Louis Defr\u00e9]] (aka Maurice Voituron) (1816\u20131880), lawyer and burgomaster of [[Uccle]]\n* [[Charles-Louis-Joseph-Xavier de la Vall\u00e9e-Poussin]] (1827\u20131903), a [[mineralogist]] and [[geologist]]\n* [[Auguste Marie Fran\u00e7ois Beernaert]] (1829\u20131912), [[Prime Minister of Belgium]] and winner of the [[Nobel Peace Prize]]\n* [[Patrick Francis Healy]] (1830\u20131910), president of [[Georgetown University]], first [[Jesuit]] priest of [[African American]] ancestry, first American of acknowledged African-American ancestry to earn PhD\n* [[Antanas Baranauskas]] (1835\u20131902), Lithuanian [[poet]].\n* [[Arthur Vierendeel]] (1852\u20131940) civil engineer.\n* [[E. J. Dillon|Emile Joseph Dillon]] (1854\u20131933), [[linguist]], author and journalist.\n* [[Albrecht Rodenbach]] (1856\u20131880), poet.\n* [[Albin van Hoonacker]] (1857\u20131933), Catholic [[theologian]] and Biblical scholar\n* [[Charles Jean de la Vall\u00e9e-Poussin]] (1866\u20131962), mathematician who proved the [[prime number theorem]].\n* [[Charles Terlinden]] (1878\u20141972), historian\n* [[Edgar Sengier]] (1879\u20131963), director of the [[Union Mini\u00e8re du Haut Katanga]].\n* [[Frans Van Cauwelaert]] (1880\u20131961), politician.\n* [[Jean-Baptiste Janssens]], S.J. (1889\u20131964), twenty-seventh Superior General of the [[Society of Jesus]].\n* [[Weng Wenhao]] (1889\u20131971), founder of modern Chinese [[geography]].\n* [[Georges Lema\u00eetre]] (1894\u20131966), [[astronomer]], priest and proposer of the [[Big Bang]] theory.\n* [[Fulton J. Sheen]] (1895\u20131979), American archbishop, television personality, and writer.\n* [[August De Boodt]] (1895\u20131986), politician.\n* [[Jerome D'Souza]], S.J. (1897\u20131977), educationist, member of Indian Constituent assembly, & four times Indian Delegate to the UNO.\n* [[Albert Claude]] (1899\u20131983), medical doctor and cell biologist, winner of [[Nobel Prize in Physiology or Medicine]]\n* [[Peter McKevitt]] (1900\u20131976), Irish priest, author and sociologist\n* [[Rafael \u00c1ngel Calder\u00f3n Guardia]] (1900\u20131970), physician, social reformer, president of [[Costa Rica]] 1940\u20131944\n* [[Alberto Hurtado]], (1901\u20131952), Chilean Jesuit priest, [[social worker]] and writer. Canonized in 2005.\n* [[Victor Delhez]], (1902\u20131985), engraver and artist.\n* [[Hendrik Elias]], (1902\u20131973), Flemish Nationalist, [[quisling]].\n* [[Maurice Anthony Biot]] (1905\u20131985), Belgian\u2013American [[physicist]] and the founder of the theory of poroelasticity.\n* [[L\u00e9on Degrelle]], (1906\u20131994), founder of [[Rexism]], [[quisling]].\n* [[Jean Charles Snoy et d'Oppuers]] (1907\u20131991), law, diplomat, businessman.\n* [[Dominique Pire]] (1910\u20131969), won [[Nobel Peace Prize]] for helping refugees in post-World War II Europe \n* [[Herman Van Breda]] (1911\u20131974), founder of the [[Husserl Archives]].\n* [[Andr\u00e9 Molitor]] (1911\u20132005), law, private secretary of [[Baudouin I of Belgium]].\n* [[Otto von Habsburg]] (1912\u20132011), heir to the thrones of [[Austria-Hungary]]; politician and writer.\n* [[Qian Xiuling]] (1912\u20132008), saved nearly 100 lives during World War II.\n* [[Tang Yuhan]], (1912\u20132014), Chinese [[oncologist]].\n* [[Pieter De Somer]] (1917\u20131985), first [[Rector (academia)|rector]] of the [[Katholieke Universiteit Leuven]].\n* [[Christian de Duve]] (1917\u20132013), [[Nobel Prize in Physiology or Medicine|Nobel Prize in Medicine]] 1974, for his discoveries concerning the structural and functional organization of the [[cell (biology)|cell]].\n* [[Anton van Wilderode]] (1919\u20131998), Flemish activist and writer.\n* [[Frans Van Coetsem]] (1919\u20132002), linguist.\n* [[Lode Van Den Bergh|Aster Berkhof]], (born 1920), Flemish writer.\n* [[Charles Mertens de Wilmars]] (1921\u20131994), psychiatrist, professor at [[Harvard Medical School]]\n* [[Malachi Martin]] (1921\u20131999), Irish writer.\n* [[Antoon Vergote]], also known as Antoine Vergote (1921\u20132013), Catholic priest, theologian, philosopher, [[psychologist]] and [[psychoanalyst]].\n* [[Tom\u00e1s \u00d3 Fiaich]] (1923\u20131990), Archbishop of Armagh.\n* [[Jan Zaprudnik]] (born 1926), Belarusian\u2013American [[historian]] and poet.\n* [[Geza Vermes]] (1924\u20132013), religious historian and [[translation|translator]] into English of the [[Dead Sea Scrolls]].\n* [[H. Narayan Murthy]] (1924\u20132011), Indian Psychologist, Philosopher and Scholar known for Behavioural Therapy.\n* [[Jos\u00e9 J. Fripiat]], a chemist, and laureate of the 1967 [[Francqui Prize]]\n* [[Gustavo Guti\u00e9rrez]] (born 1928), [[Peru]]vian [[Dominican Order|Dominican]] theologian, founder of [[Liberation Theology]].\n* [[Michael Hurley (Jesuit)|Michael Hurley]] (1923\u20132011), Irish Jesuit, co-founder of the [[Irish School of Ecumenics]]<ref name=rte>{{cite news |first=|last=|title=Father Michael Hurley dies aged 87 |url=http://www.rte.ie/news/2011/0415/hurleym.html |work=[[RT\u00c9 News and Current Affairs]] |publisher=|date=2011-04-16 |accessdate=2011-05-14}}</ref>\n* [[Adolphe Gesch\u00e9]] (1928\u20132003), theologian\n* [[Jacques Taminiaux]] (1928\u20132019), philosopher, 1977 laureate of the [[Francqui Prize]]\n* [[Camilo Torres Restrepo|Camilo Torres]] (1929\u20131966), Colombian priest and guerillero.\n* [[Jan Vansina]] (1929\u20132017), historian of Africa\n* [[Luce Irigaray]] (born 1930), French [[philosopher]], [[linguist]], [[psycholinguist]], [[psychoanalyst]], [[cultural theorist]], [[feminist]]. Graduated in 1954.\n* [[Marcel Lihau]] (1931\u20131999), first Congolese to receive a law degree, constitutionalist\n* [[Father Robert S. Smith]] (1932\u20132010), American Catholic priest, author, and educator.\n* [[Herman Van Den Berghe]] (born 1933), founder of the Centrum voor Menselijke Erfelijkheid (Belgian Centre for Human Heredity).\n* [[Thomas Kanza]] (1933\u20132004), one of the first Congolese university graduates, Congolese ambassador to the [[United Nations]].\n* [[Pierre Laconte]] (born 1934), a Belgian urbanist.\n* [[Abdul Qadeer Khan]] (born 1936), Pakistani [[metallurgist]] considered to be the father of Pakistan's nuclear weapons program.\n* [[Jacques van Ypersele de Strihou]] (born 1936), Minister of state, former Chief Cabinet of Albert II and Baudouin.\n* [[Renato Prada Oropeza]] (1937\u20132011), Mexican writer and [[Semiotics|semiotician]].\n* [[Jean Nguza Karl-i-Bond|Nguza Karl-i-Bond]] (1938\u20132003), notable [[Zaire|Zairian]] politician.<ref>Jeffrey M. Elliot and Mervyn M. Dymally, eds., ''Voices of Zaire: Rhetoric or Reality'', p. 53</ref>\n* [[Piet Van Waeyenberge]] (born 1938), economics, President of [[De Warande (Club)|De Warande]].\n* [[Robert Sokolowski]] (born 1939), American Catholic priest, and Professor of Philosophy at [[The Catholic University of America]].\n* [[Erik De Clercq]] (born 1941), [[physician]] and [[biologist]].\n* [[Bernard Lietaer]] (born 1942), economist and author.\n* [[Arthur Ulens]] (born 1946), chemistry and economics, businessman.\n* [[Herman Van Rompuy]] (born 1947), Belgian statesman and Prime Minister of Belgium. Appointed as the first [[President of the European Council]] in November 2009.\n\n==See also==\n{{Portal|Belgium|Catholicism}}\n* [[Academic libraries in Leuven]]\n* [[Catholic University of Mechlin]]\n* [[Collegium Trilingue]]\n* [[Katholieke Universiteit Leuven]]\n* [[Leuven Database of Ancient Books]]\n* [[Old University of Leuven]]\n* [[State University of Leuven]]\n* [[Universit\u00e9 catholique de Louvain]]\n* [[Universities in Leuven]]\n* [[Lovanium University]]\n\n== References ==\n{{reflist}}\n\n== Further reading ==\n* 1860: ''Souvenir du XXVe anniversaire de la fondation de l'Universit\u00e9 catholique: Novembre 1859'', Louvain, typographie Vanlinthout et Cie, 1860 [https://books.google.be/books?id=brlLAAAAcAAJ&printsec=frontcover&hl=fr#v=onepage&q&f=false ''Souvenir du XXVe anniversaire de la fondation de l'Universit\u00e9 catholique: Novembre 1859''].\n* 1887: ''Universit\u00e9 Catholique de Louvain : Liber Memorialis : 1834\u20131884'', Louvain : Peeters, 1887.\n* 1975: R. Mathes, ''L\u00f6wen und Rom. Zur Gr\u00fcndung der Katholischen Universit\u00e4t L\u00f6wen unter besonderer Ber\u00fccksichtigung der Kirchen-und Bildungspolitik Papst Gregors XVI'', Essen, 1975.\n* 2006: abb\u00e9 Andr\u00e9 Tihon: Article ''L\u00f6wen''. In: ''Lexikon f\u00fcr Theologie und Kirche'', vol. 6. Herder, Fribourg, B\u00e2le, Vienne, 3e \u00e9d., 2006, {{p.|1070\u20131073}}.\n* 2011: Pieter Dhondt, ''Un double compromis. Enjeux et d\u00e9bats relatifs \u00e0 l'enseignement universitaire en Belgique au XIXe si\u00e8cle'', Gand : Academia Press, 2011.\n\n{{Universities of Louvain}}\n{{Belgian universities}}\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{coord|50|40|11|N|4|36|44|E|source:kolossus-nlwiki|display=title}}\n[[Category:1834 establishments in Belgium]]\n[[Category:1968 disestablishments in Belgium]]\n[[Category:Catholic University of Leuven]]\n[[Category:Catholic University of Leuven before 1968| ]]\n[[Category:Catholic universities and colleges in Belgium|Leuven, Catholic University]]\n[[Category:Education in Leuven]]\n[[Category:Educational institutions established in the 15th century|Leuven, Catholic University]]\n[[Category:Educational institutions established in 1834|Leuven, Catholic University]]\n[[Category:Educational institutions established in 1968|Leuven, Catholic University]]\n[[Category:History of Leuven]]\n[[Category:Pontifical universities|Leuven, Catholic University of]]\n[[Category:Universities in Belgium|Leuven]]\n", "name_user": "RisingStar", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eHistory", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Catholic_University_of_Leuven_(1834%E2%80%931968)"}
{"title_page": "Black Mirror", "text_new": "{{other uses}}\n{{short description|British science fiction anthology television series}}\n{{Use British English|date=February 2018}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=February 2018}}\n{{Infobox television\n |show_name            = Black Mirror\n |image                = BlackMirrorTitleCard.jpg\n |caption              =\n |show_name_2          =\n |genre                = {{Plainlist|\n* [[Science fiction]]\n* [[Satire]]\n* [[Psychological thriller]]\n* [[Dystopia]]\n* [[Anthology series|Anthology]]\n* [[Dramedy]]\n* [[Horror film|Horror]]\n* [[Horror comedy]]\n* [[Black comedy]]\n* [[Romance film|Romance]]\n* [[Mundane science fiction]]\n* [[Speculative fiction]]\n* [[Quality television]]\n* [[Psychological drama]]\n}}\n |creator              = [[Charlie Brooker]]\n |developer            =\n |writer               = {{Plainlist|\n* Charlie Brooker\n* [[Konnie Huq]]\n* [[Jesse Armstrong]]\n* [[Rashida Jones]]\n* [[Michael Schur]]\n* William Bridges\n}}\n |starring             =\n |voices               =\n |narrated             =\n |theme_music_composer =\n |opentheme            =\n |endtheme             =\n |composer             =\n |country              = United Kingdom\n |language             = English\n |num_series           = 5\n |num_episodes         = 22\n |list_episodes        = List of Black Mirror episodes\n |producer             =\n |executive_producer   = {{Plainlist|\n* [[Annabel Jones]]\n* Charlie Brooker\n}}\n |editor               =\n |location             =\n |cinematography       =\n |camera               =\n |runtime              = 41\u201389 minutes\n |company              = {{Plainlist|\n* Zeppotron (2011\u20132013)\n* [[Endemol UK|House of Tomorrow]] (2014\u2013present)\n}}\n |distributor          = [[Endemol Shine UK]]\n |network              = {{Plainlist|\n* [[Channel 4]] (2011\u20132014)\n* [[Netflix]] (2016\u2013present)\n}}\n |picture_format       = {{Plainlist|\n* [[High-definition television|HDTV]] [[1080i]] (2011\u20132014)\n* [[Ultra-high-definition television|4K UHD]] [[2160p]] (2016\u2013present)\n}}\n |audio_format         = [[Dolby Digital]] 2.0\n |first_run            =\n |first_aired          = {{Start date|df=yes|2011|12|4}}\n |last_aired           = {{End date|df=yes|present}}\n |preceded_by          =\n |followed_by          =\n |related              =\n |website              = https://www.netflix.com/gb/title/70264888\n |production_website   =\n}}\n\n'''''Black Mirror''''' is a British<!-- the series is produced in England and was originally broadcast on Channel 4, a British TV station --> [[dystopia]]n [[science fiction]] [[comedy-drama]] [[Anthology series|anthology]] television series created by [[Charlie Brooker]]. He and [[Annabel Jones]] are the programme's [[showrunner]]s. It examines modern society, particularly with regard to the unanticipated consequences of [[Post-industrial society|new technologies]]. Episodes are standalone, usually set in an [[alternative history|alternative present]] or the near future, often with a dark and satirical tone, although some are more experimental and lighter.\n\n''Black Mirror'' was inspired by older anthology series, such as ''[[The Twilight Zone]]'', which Brooker felt were able to deal with controversial, contemporary topics with less fear of censorship than other more realistic programmes. Brooker developed ''Black Mirror'' to highlight topics related to humanity's relationship with technology, creating stories that feature \"the way we live now&nbsp;\u2013 and the way we might be living in 10 minutes' time if we're clumsy.\"<ref name=\"guardian_a\"/>\n\nThe series premiered for two series on [[Channel 4]] in December 2011 and February 2013. After its addition to the catalogue in December 2014, [[Netflix]] purchased the programme in September 2015. It commissioned a series of 12 episodes later divided into the third and fourth series, each comprising six episodes; the former was released on 21 October 2016 and the latter on 29 December 2017. A standalone [[interactive film]] titled ''[[Black Mirror: Bandersnatch]]'' was released on 28 December 2018. A fifth series, comprising three episodes, was released on 5 June 2019.<ref name=\"S5ReleaseDate\" />\n\nThe series has garnered positive reception from critics, received many [[List of awards and nominations received by Black Mirror|awards and nominations]], and seen an increase in interest internationally, particularly in the United States after its addition to Netflix. The show has won eight [[Emmy Awards]] for \"[[San Junipero]]\", \"[[USS Callister]]\" and ''Bandersnatch'', including three consecutive wins in the [[Primetime Emmy Award for Outstanding Television Movie|Outstanding Television Movie]] category.\n\n== Episodes ==\n{{Main|List of Black Mirror episodes}}\nThe series was originally commissioned by [[Channel 4]] in the United Kingdom and premiered in December 2011. A second series ran during February 2013. In September 2015, [[Netflix]] purchased the programme, commissioning a series of 12 episodes later divided into two series of six episodes.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://media.netflix.com/en/press-releases/netflix-will-bring-viewers-twelve-new-episodes-of-the-critically-acclaimed-black-mirror-migration-1 |title=Netflix will bring viewers twelve new episodes of the critically-acclaimed Black Mirror |website=[[Netflix]] |date=24 September 2015 |access-date=8 November 2016 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180621194414/https://media.netflix.com/en/press-releases/netflix-will-bring-viewers-twelve-new-episodes-of-the-critically-acclaimed-black-mirror-migration-1 |archive-date=21 June 2018 |url-status=dead }}</ref> The first of these series was released on Netflix worldwide as the overall third series on 21 October 2016. The fourth series was released on 29 December 2017.<ref name=\"Series4Release\">{{cite web |url=https://variety.com/2017/tv/news/black-mirror-season-4-release-date-trailer-1202628880/ |title=Netflix Announces 'Black Mirror' Season 4 Release Date (Watch) |last=Turchiano |first=Danielle |website=Variety |date=6 December 2017 |accessdate=6 December 2017 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20171207013407/https://variety.com/2017/tv/news/black-mirror-season-4-release-date-trailer-1202628880/ |archive-date=7 December 2017 |url-status=live }}</ref> A fifth series consisting of three episodes was released on 5 June 2019.<ref name=\"S5ReleaseDate\" />\n{{:List of Black Mirror episodes}}\n\n== Production ==\n=== Conception and style ===\nCharlie Brooker had completed production of ''[[Dead Set]]'', a zombie-based drama series, and while working on ''[[Newswipe with Charlie Brooker|Newswipe]]'' and other programmes, had decided that he wanted to make another drama series, in an [[anthology series|anthology style]] like ''[[The Twilight Zone]]'', ''[[Tales of the Unexpected (TV series)|Tales of the Unexpected]]'', and ''[[Hammer House of Horror]]''.<ref name=\"denofgeek interview\">{{cite web |url=https://www.denofgeek.com/tv/21083/charlie-brooker-interview-black-mirror-videogames-gameswipe-and-a-touch-of-cloth |title=Charlie Brooker interview: Black Mirror, videogames, Gameswipe and A Touch Of Cloth |first=Ryan |last=Lamble |date=12 February 2012 |accessdate=7 December 2017 |website=[[Den of Geek]] |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20171208005054/http://www.denofgeek.com/tv/21083/charlie-brooker-interview-black-mirror-videogames-gameswipe-and-a-touch-of-cloth |archive-date=8 December 2017 |url-status=live }}</ref><ref name=\"guardian_a\">{{cite news |title=Charlie Brooker: the dark side of our gadget addiction |url=https://www.theguardian.com/technology/2011/dec/01/charlie-brooker-dark-side-gadget-addiction-black-mirror |accessdate=17 December 2011 |newspaper=The Guardian |date=1 December 2011 |location=London |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20131005141925/http://www.theguardian.com/technology/2011/dec/01/charlie-brooker-dark-side-gadget-addiction-black-mirror |archive-date=5 October 2013 |url-status=live }}</ref>  Brooker recognised that [[Rod Serling]] had written episodes of ''The Twilight Zone'' using contemporary issues, often controversial ones such as racism, but placed them in fictional settings so as to get around television censors at the time.<ref name=\"guardian_a\" /> Brooker realised he could do similar commentary on modern issues, specifically focusing on mankind's dependency on technology, something he encountered while producing the series ''[[How TV Ruined Your Life]]''.<ref name=\"guardian_a\" /> Brooker pulled the series' title from this approach:\n{{quote|If technology is a drug&nbsp;\u2013 and it does feel like a drug&nbsp;\u2013 then what, precisely, are the side effects? This area&nbsp;\u2013 between delight and discomfort&nbsp;\u2013 is where ''Black Mirror'', my new drama series, is set. The 'black mirror' of the title is the one you'll find on every wall, on every desk, in the palm of every hand: the cold, shiny screen of a [[Television|TV]], a monitor, a [[smartphone]].<ref name=\"guardian_a\" />}}\n\nBrooker wanted to keep the anthology approach, using new stories, settings, characters, and actors for each episode, as he felt this approach was a key element of enjoying series like ''The Twilight Zone''; he said, \"There was a signature tone to the stories, the same dark chocolate coating&nbsp;\u2013 but the filling was always a surprise.\"<ref name=\"guardian_a\" /> This approach would allow ''Black Mirror'' to contrast with current dramas and serials that had a standard recurring cast.<ref name=\"guardian_a\" /> According to Brooker, the production team considered giving the series a linking theme or presenter, but ultimately decided not to: \"There were discussions. Do we set them all in the same street? Do we have some characters who appear in each episode, a bit ''[[Three Colours trilogy|Three Colours: Blue/White/Red]]'' style? We did think about having a character who introduces them, ''[[Tales from the Crypt (TV series)|Tales from the Crypt]]'' style, or like Rod Serling or [[Alfred Hitchcock]] or [[Roald Dahl]], because most anthology shows did have that... but the more we thought about it, we thought it was a bit weird.\"<ref name=\"SFX_Magazine\">{{cite news |title=Charlie Brooker Talks The Twilight Zone And Technology |url=http://www.sfx.co.uk/2013/02/01/charlie-brooker-talks-the-twilight-zone-and-technology/ |accessdate=4 February 2013 |magazine=SFX |date=1 February 2013 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20130205075847/http://www.sfx.co.uk/2013/02/01/charlie-brooker-talks-the-twilight-zone-and-technology/ |archive-date=5 February 2013 |url-status=live }}</ref>\n\nWhile the production does not use linking elements, the series has included allusions and [[Easter egg (media)|Easter eggs]] from previous episodes into later ones. For example, \"[[Hated in the Nation]]\" in the third series calls back to the events of both the first series episode \"[[The National Anthem (Black Mirror)|The National Anthem]]\" and the second series episode \"[[White Bear (Black Mirror)|White Bear]]\",<ref name=\"hwr s4\" /> while the final episode of the fourth series \"[[Black Museum (Black Mirror)|Black Museum]]\" includes references to each prior episode of the series.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://variety.com/2017/tv/news/black-mirror-season-4-black-museum-colm-mccarthy-directing-interview-1202640505/ |title='Black Mirror' Director on 'Black Museum': 'I Think There's Something Quite Spiritual About It' |first=Danielle |last=Turchiano |date=29 December 2017 |accessdate=31 December 2017 |website=[[Variety (magazine)|Variety]] |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180111102248/http://variety.com/2017/tv/news/black-mirror-season-4-black-museum-colm-mccarthy-directing-interview-1202640505/ |archive-date=11 January 2018 |url-status=live }}</ref> Some of these are for the ease of reusing a name developed in a prior episode; for example, they created the fictional \"UKN\" broadcast network for handling news reports that drive stories,<ref name=\"thrillest s3 easter eggs\" /> while the pizza delivery company used in \"[[USS Callister]]\" was used again for a company running automated pizza trucks in \"[[Crocodile (Black Mirror)|Crocodile]]\".<ref name=\"ew s4 interview\">{{cite web |url=https://ew.com/tv/2018/01/02/black-mirror-season-4-interviews/ |title=Black Mirror season 4, your burning questions answered |first=James |last=Hibbard |date=2 January 2018 |accessdate=2 January 2018 |website=[[Entertainment Weekly]] |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180102200542/http://ew.com/tv/2018/01/02/black-mirror-season-4-interviews/ |archive-date=2 January 2018 |url-status=live }}</ref> Other Easter eggs were added as they knew viewers would be intensely dissecting the episodes, and the team provided these as gags. However, over time the use of Easter eggs became more purposeful, as to establish a [[canon (fiction)|canon]] of the \"dream universe\" that the episodes take place in.<ref name=\"hwr s4\">{{cite web |url=https://www.hollywoodreporter.com/live-feed/black-mirror-season-4-episodes-charlie-brooker-annabel-jones-interview-spoilers-1033807 |title='Black Mirror' Bosses on \"San Junipero\" Sequel and an Unpredictable Season 4 |first=Jackie |last=Strause |date=7 September 2017 |accessdate=14 December 2017 |website=[[The Hollywood Reporter]] |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20171215053422/https://www.hollywoodreporter.com/live-feed/black-mirror-season-4-episodes-charlie-brooker-annabel-jones-interview-spoilers-1033807 |archive-date=15 December 2017 |url-status=live }}</ref> Brooker noted that when they opted to reuse a cover of [[Irma Thomas]]' \"[[Anyone Who Knows What Love Is (Will Understand) |Anyone Who Knows What Love Is]]\", first introduced in \"[[Fifteen Million Merits]]\", for \"[[White Christmas (Black Mirror)|White Christmas]]\", as \"it does sort of nest the whole thing together in some kind of artistic universe\".<ref name=\"thrillest s3 easter eggs\">{{cite web |url=https://www.thrillist.com/entertainment/nation/black-mirror-netflix-season-3-charlie-brooker-interview |title='Black Mirror' Creator Charlie Brooker Explains Season 3 and Reveals Easter Eggs |first=Sean |last=Fitz-Gerald |date=23 October 2016 |accessdate=11 January 2018 |website=[[Thrillist]] |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20171230223739/https://www.thrillist.com/entertainment/nation/black-mirror-netflix-season-3-charlie-brooker-interview |archive-date=30 December 2017 |url-status=live }}</ref> In describing the nature of Easter eggs in the standalone film ''[[Black Mirror: Bandersnatch]]'', Brooker alluded to dialogue said by character Colin Ritman that spoke towards alternate realities, and suggested that their use of Easter eggs to previous episodes helps to connect all these stories, but not necessarily within the same reality or timeline. However, Brooker asserted that the Easter eggs in ''Black Mirror'' are only there \"as an extra bit of texture for fans of the show\", and not meant to fully construct an atlas of ''Black Mirror'' episodes that becomes essential for understanding any episode.<ref>{{cite news| url = https://www.hollywoodreporter.com/live-feed/bandersnatch-tuckersoft-black-mirror-universe-1172028 | title = How 'Bandersnatch' Fits Into the 'Black Mirror' Universe | first = Jackie | last = Strause | date = 31 December 2018 | accessdate = 2 January 2019 | work = [[The Hollywood Reporter]] | archive-url = https://web.archive.org/web/20190102053516/https://www.hollywoodreporter.com/live-feed/bandersnatch-tuckersoft-black-mirror-universe-1172028 | archive-date = 2 January 2019 | url-status=live }}</ref>\n\nGiles Harvey comments in a profile of Brooker for ''[[The New Yorker]]'' that each episode \"establishes the background of normality against which a decisive tweak will stand out all the more starkly\". Harvey notes that the series' diverse range of genres show that it is \"manifestly the work of someone who has clocked up many hours of screen time\". He further comments that Brooker is \"scrupulous\", as \"the believability of each episode depends on maintaining the complex internal logic of its dystopic world\". Brooker is involved during the filming and editing processes, pointing out any inconsistencies that arise, and is \"determined to make the devices and screens and interfaces used in 'Black Mirror' seem authentic\". As examples of Brooker's \"meticulous attention to detail\", Harvey reports that Brooker carefully considered whether a falling wine bottle would shatter in the nested virtual realities of \"[[Playtest (Black Mirror)|Playtest]]\", and whether it would rain in the eponymous location in \"[[San Junipero]]\". An instance of realistic technology is the email system in \"[[Be Right Back]]\", which contrasts with \"histrionic computers\" found in Hollywood; an email is sent to the main character with the heading \"Martha, people in your position bought the following\", containing various books on the topic of grief-counseling.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.newyorker.com/magazine/2016/11/28/the-speculative-dread-of-black-mirror |title=The Speculative Dread of \"Black Mirror\" |last=Harvey |first=Giles |website=[[The New Yorker]] |date=28 November 2016 |accessdate=16 December 2017 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20171222050640/https://www.newyorker.com/magazine/2016/11/28/the-speculative-dread-of-black-mirror |archive-date=22 December 2017 |url-status=live }}</ref> Knowing that fans of the series have dissected some of these details by watching the episodes frame-by-frame, Brooker and his team have included humorous jabs at these fans through printed messages on various props, such as a paragraph in a news article held up by a character directed to fans of the series on [[Reddit]] in \"[[Crocodile (Black Mirror) |Crocodile]]\".<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.thewrap.com/black-mirror-charlie-brooker-reddit-fans-easter-egg-crocodile/ |title='Black Mirror' Trolls Eagle-Eyed Reddit Users With Insane Season 4 Easter Egg |first=Jennifer |last=Maas |date=1 January 2018 |accessdate=2 January 2018 |website=[[The Wrap]] |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180102033759/https://www.thewrap.com/black-mirror-charlie-brooker-reddit-fans-easter-egg-crocodile/ |archive-date=2 January 2018 |url-status=live }}</ref>\n\n=== Series 1 ===\nThe series' inception was in 2010. Charlie Brooker and Annabel Jones served as executive producers; the two had begun to work together on ''[[Charlie Brooker's Screenwipe]]'', a television review programme which aired from 2006 to 2008. The first pitch, to the head of comedy at Channel 4, was for eight half-hour episodes written by different people. Technology was a lesser focus, and the worlds were larger and more detailed, which Jones said was not possible to execute properly in the short runtime. The series was then commissioned for three hour-long episodes. The first script was \"[[Fifteen Million Merits]]\", which was written by Brooker and his wife [[Konnie Huq]]. The second script was \"Inbound\", which episode was never produced; it was about war and contained concepts which were later repurposed for the series 3 episode \"[[Men Against Fire]]\". The following script pitched became \"[[The National Anthem (Black Mirror)|The National Anthem]]\", the first episode to air. The third episode is \"[[The Entire History of You]]\".<ref name=\"ibm\">{{cite book | title=  Inside Black Mirror | date = November 2018 | first1 = Charlie | last1 = Brooker | first2 = Annabel | last2 = Jones | first3 = Jason | last3 = Arnopp | isbn = 9781984823489 | publisher =  [[Crown Publishing Group]] | place = New York City }}</ref>{{rp|6\u201313}}\n\nThe programme was produced by Brooker's production company Zeppotron, for [[Endemol]]. Joel Collins served as production designer, with his company Painting Practice working on visual effects.<ref name=\"ibm\"/>{{rp|18}} An Endemol press release described the series as \"a hybrid of ''The Twilight Zone'' and ''Tales of the Unexpected'' which taps into our contemporary unease about our modern world\", with the stories having a \"techno-paranoia\" feel.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.endemoluk.com/news/black-mirror-a-new-drama-from-charlie-brooker |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110515185448/http://www.endemoluk.com/news/black-mirror-a-new-drama-from-charlie-brooker |url-status=dead |archive-date=15 May 2011 |title=Black Mirror&nbsp;\u2013 A new drama from Charlie Brooker |website=Endemol UK |date=11 May 2011 |accessdate=15 November 2011}}</ref> [[Channel 4]] described the first episode, \"The National Anthem\", as \"a twisted parable for the [[Twitter]] age\".<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.channel4.com/info/press/programme-information/black-mirror/allpi |title=Black Mirror |website=Channel 4 |date=7 November 2011 |accessdate=6 December 2011 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20111127030814/http://www.channel4.com/info/press/programme-information/black-mirror/allpi |archive-date=27 November 2011 |url-status=live }}</ref> ''Black Mirror'' series 1 had a limited DVD release for PAL / Region 2 on 27 February 2012.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.tuppencemagazine.co.uk/black-mirror-dvd.html |title=Black Mirror DVD |magazine=Tuppence Magazine |date=7 November 2011 |accessdate=18 December 2011 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120229014619/http://www.tuppencemagazine.co.uk/black-mirror-dvd.html |archivedate=29 February 2012 |df=dmy-all }}</ref>\n\nIn 2013, [[Robert Downey Jr.]] [[Option (filmmaking)|optioned]] the episode \"[[The Entire History of You]]\" (written by [[Jesse Armstrong]]) to potentially be made into a film by [[Warner Bros.]] and his own production company, [[Team Downey]].<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.theguardian.com/film/2013/feb/12/robert-downey-jr-black-mirror |title=Robert Downey Jr to turn episode of Charlie Brooker's Black Mirror into film |date=12 February 2013 |newspaper=[[The Guardian]] |first=Ben |last=Child |location=London |access-date=11 December 2016 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20151103220854/http://www.theguardian.com/film/2013/feb/12/robert-downey-jr-black-mirror |archive-date=3 November 2015 |url-status=live }}</ref> The series was available in the U.S. from November 2013 via [[DirecTV]], where episodes aired on [[Audience (TV network)|Audience]] and were also available online to subscribers.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://grantland.com/hollywood-prospectus/black-mirror-episode-1-the-national-anthem-pig-bang-theory/|title=Black Mirror Episode 1, 'The National Anthem': Pig Bang Theory|work=[[Grantland]]|last=Yoshida|first=Emily|date=14 November 2013|accessdate=20 March 2020}}</ref> It was made available in the U.S. on Netflix from late 2014 onwards.<ref name=\"Netflix vs 4\" />\n\nIn the early stages of ''Black Mirror'', Jones was keen to avoid casting comedy actors, as Brooker was previously a comedy writer, and they wanted the series to not feel like comedy.<ref name=\"ibm\"/>{{rp|16}} \"The National Anthem\" stars [[Rory Kinnear]] as Prime Minister Michael Callow, with [[Lindsay Duncan]] playing Home Secretary Alex Cairns. \"Fifteen Million Merits\" features [[Daniel Kaluuya]] as Bing, [[Jessica Brown Findlay]] as Abi and [[Rupert Everett]], [[Julia Davis]], [[Bashy|Ashley Thomas]] as Judges Hope, Charity, and Wraith. In \"The Entire History of You\", [[Toby Kebbell]] and [[Jodie Whittaker]] star as married couple Liam and Ffion.\n\nThe first series was popular and critically well received, although viewing figures decreased throughout the series. The series was expensive for Channel 4, as the anthology format meant there were no [[economies of scale]], but it was commissioned for a second series.<ref name=\"ibm\"/>{{rp|59}}\n\n=== Series 2 ===\nSeries 2 consists of three episodes. Brooker described it as \"more epic in scale, but more intimate in scope\". The episodes are more \"understated\" in their technologies. Brooker commented that the second series mirrors the first: the first series has topics of (in order) \"warped political satire\", \"dystopian hellscape\", and \"relationship torn apart by technology\", while the second series presents episodes of these forms in reverse.<ref name=\"ibm\"/>{{rp|60}} Each episode in the first series had a male protagonist, so Brooker deliberately wrote female protagonists for series 2 episodes \"[[Be Right Back]]\" and \"[[White Bear (Black Mirror)|White Bear]]\".<ref name=\"ibm\"/>{{rp|64}}\n\nA trailer for the second series was made by [[Moving Picture Company]] and featured three interspersed storylines: \"a dream sequence, the repetitive factory setting and the huge dust cloud that sweeps through the street at the ad's climactic end.\" Aired from 22 January 2013, the advertisement was shown on Channel 4 and in cinemas.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.digitalartsonline.co.uk/news/motion-graphics/mpc-creates-darkly-compelling-ads-for-charlie-brookers-black-mirror/ |title=MPC creates darkly compelling ads for Charlie Brooker's Black Mirror |website=Digital Arts |date=29 January 2013 |accessdate=16 December 2017 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20171222050737/https://www.digitalartsonline.co.uk/news/motion-graphics/mpc-creates-darkly-compelling-ads-for-charlie-brookers-black-mirror/ |archive-date=22 December 2017 |url-status=live }}</ref>\n\n\"Be Right Back\" stars [[Hayley Atwell]] as Martha and [[Domhnall Gleeson]] as Ash, both in human and robot form. In \"White Bear\", [[Lenora Crichlow]] plays Victoria Skillane and [[Michael Smiley]] and [[Tuppence Middleton]] play Baxter and Jem. \"[[The Waldo Moment]]\" features [[Daniel Rigby]] as Jamie Salter, [[Chloe Pirrie]] as Gwendolyn Harris and [[Jason Flemyng]] as Jack Napier.\n\n=== \"White Christmas\" ===\nAccording to Brooker, the series was still taking its budget from the comedy department of Channel 4, and there was discussion of whether it should fall under the drama department instead. Shane Allen, head of comedy for Channel 4 at the time, stated in 2018 that someone had been taken aback by the budget for ''Black Mirror'', which was well above the standard for a comedy, and became involved in the editorial process. A new head of comedy had been hired, who did not have a relationship with Brooker and Jones.<ref name=\"ibm\"/>{{rp|101\u2013103}}\n\nBrooker reported in 2018 that Channel 4 agreed on a third series of four episodes, but requested detailed synopses of the episodes in advance. Brooker came up with an episode \"Angel of the Morning\", which would later become a story in \"[[White Christmas (Black Mirror)|White Christmas]]\". He also conceived of an episode based on the earlier script \"Inbound\" which would have been similar to a later series 3 episode, \"Men Against Fire\". Another episode was named \"Crocodile\", which overlapped in parts with the series 4 episode of the same name. After a lengthy wait, Brooker and Jones were told that the ideas \"weren't very ''Black Mirror''\". Though Channel 4 may have suggested doing a one-off special, Jones said that \"we felt there wasn't any clarity from the channel\".<ref name=\"ibm\"/>{{rp|101\u2013103}}\n\nJones and Brooker worked on other projects for the next year, such as the comedy procedural ''[[A Touch of Cloth]]''. After bumping into a Channel 4 staff member, Brooker emailed the channel to ask about how to continue with ''Black Mirror''. Channel 4 had the budget for an hour-long Christmas special, but Jones and Brooker pushed for a 90-minute episode.<ref name=\"ibm\"/>{{rp|101\u2013103}}\n\n\"White Christmas\" was a portmanteau of three stories, inspired by works such as the 1983 science fiction film ''[[Twilight Zone: The Movie]]''.<ref name=\"ibm\"/>{{rp|101\u2013103}} It starred [[Jon Hamm]] as Matt and [[Rafe Spall]] as Joe throughout. Actors in the individual stories include: [[Rasmus Hardiker]] as Harry, [[Natalia Tena]] as Jennifer, [[Oona Chaplin]] as Greta, [[Janet Montgomery]] as Beth, and Ken Drury as Beth's father. The episode aired on 16 December 2014.\n\n=== Move to Netflix ===\nOn the day of the press screening for \"White Christmas\", Brooker and Jones had a meeting with Channel 4 executives, who told them that they wanted to continue the series but due to budget constraints, it would need to be a co-production. The pair had travelled to Los Angeles a few months prior to try to get co-production money but were unsuccessful. The channel also suggested that Brooker could write an episode of ''[[Electric Dreams (2017 TV series)|Electric Dreams]]'', a 2017 adaptation of short stories by [[Philip K. Dick]].<ref name=\"ibm\"/>{{rp|123\u2013124}}\n\nIn December 2014, the first two series of the programme were released on [[Netflix]] in the United States after they bought exclusive streaming rights, leading to increased attention for the programme.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://variety.com/2014/tv/news/netflix-run-brings-u-k-s-black-mirror-into-light-for-u-s-auds-1201380236/|title=Netflix Run Brings U.K.'s 'Black Mirror' Into Light for U.S. Auds|work=[[Variety (magazine)|Variety]]|last=Spangler|first=Todd|date=18 December 2014|accessdate=26 December 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20181227040808/https://variety.com/2014/tv/news/netflix-run-brings-u-k-s-black-mirror-into-light-for-u-s-auds-1201380236/|archive-date=27 December 2018|url-status=live}}</ref> In a bidding war between channels, which included several American networks, Netflix led with a commitment of two series of ten episodes each. Brooker and Jones reported in 2018 that although they and Netflix were both keen to have Channel 4 as equal partners, they could not get a meeting with Channel 4. They eventually got a meeting without discussion of a co-production with Netflix, where the channel suggested a renewal for three episodes. The channel later offered six episodes if full treatments could be given in advance, but Brooker and Jones were concerned due to past rejection of ideas. They had a limited time to reply to U.S. offers and chose to make a deal with Netflix.<ref name=\"ibm\"/>{{rp|125\u2013126}}\n\nIn September 2015, Netflix officially commissioned 12 episodes of ''Black Mirror''.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://variety.com/2015/digital/news/netflix-black-mirror-new-episodes-1201602037/ |title='Black Mirror' Lands at Netflix |first=Debra |last=Birnbaum |work=[[Variety (magazine)|Variety]] |date=25 September 2015 |accessdate=26 December 2018 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180612162641/https://variety.com/2015/digital/news/netflix-black-mirror-new-episodes-1201602037/ |archive-date=12 June 2018 |url-status=live }}</ref> In March 2016, it outbid Channel 4 for the rights to distributing the third series in the UK, with a bid of {{US$|40&nbsp;million}}.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.theguardian.com/media/2016/mar/29/netflix-channel-4-charlie-brooker-black-mirror |title=Netflix deals Channel 4 knockout blow over Charlie Brooker's Black Mirror |first=John |last=Plunkett |date=29 March 2016 |newspaper=The Guardian |access-date=11 December 2016 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20171230021155/https://www.theguardian.com/media/2016/mar/29/netflix-channel-4-charlie-brooker-black-mirror |archive-date=30 December 2017 |url-status=live }}</ref> Endemol released a statement saying that Channel 4 had \"had the opportunity to recommission [''Black Mirror''] since 2013 and passed on this and subsequent co-production offers put to them. [...] Further efforts were made to try to reach a settlement regarding a U.K. window for Channel 4, but these were also sadly to no avail\". In a press release, Channel 4 say that they \"offered to recommission ''Black Mirror''\". This marked the first time that an online streaming service had gained the rights to a series when the original network had wished to renew it.<ref name=\"Netflix vs 4\">{{cite web |url=https://www.hollywoodreporter.com/news/miptv-why-black-mirror-deal-881421 |title=MIPTV: Why the 'Black Mirror' Deal Marks a Turning Point for Netflix |website=[[The Hollywood Reporter]] |last=Ritman |first=Alex |last2=Roxborough |first2=Scott |date=7 April 2016 |accessdate=12 December 2017 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20171213013130/https://www.hollywoodreporter.com/news/miptv-why-black-mirror-deal-881421 |archive-date=13 December 2017 |url-status=live }}</ref>\n\n=== Series 3 ===\nIn developing the third series' stories, Brooker had looked back to the first two series and the Christmas special and recognised that all the stories were about characters becoming trapped in a situation that they could not escape from. Coupled with the anthology format that asked for viewers to get immersed within the stories to understand the nature of each, this created a sense of darkness and horror, which could make it difficult to watch successive episodes without becoming uncomfortable. With the third series, Brooker wanted to explore different formats, still having a few \"trap\" episodes but adding more conventional stories like a romance and police procedural, making the new series more digestible for the viewer.<ref>{{cite journal |url=https://www.wired.com/2016/10/black-mirror-traps/ |title=What Happens When Black Mirror Moves Beyond Traps? It Gets Even Better |first=Joesph |last=Bien-Kahn |date=21 October 2016 |accessdate=15 December 2017 |journal=[[Wired (magazine)|Wired]] |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20171216034602/https://www.wired.com/2016/10/black-mirror-traps/ |archive-date=16 December 2017 |url-status=live }}</ref> Producer Lucy Dyke commented that Netflix had an expectation that the series would become \"bigger and better\" and \"more international\", while production designer Joel Collins said that Netflix was happy to support ideas on the same scale or on a larger scale than previous episodes. The first episode that Brooker wrote for the series was \"[[San Junipero]]\", and it was an intentional departure from previous episodes as well as a \"deliberate raspberry-blow\" at fans who were concerned at the series' Americanisation.<ref name=\"ibm\"/>{{rp|126\u2013127}}\n\nThe titles of the six episodes that make up series 3 were announced in July 2016, along with the release date.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://nerdist.com/black-mirrors-new-episodes-will-hit-us-in-october/ |title=Black Mirror's New Episodes Will Hit Us In October |website=Nerdist|publisher=[[Nerdist Industries]] |last=Lutes |first=Alicia |date=27 July 2016 |accessdate=12 December 2017 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20171213010958/https://nerdist.com/black-mirrors-new-episodes-will-hit-us-in-october/ |archive-date=13 December 2017 |url-status=dead }}</ref> A trailer for the third series was released in October 2016.<ref name=trailer>{{cite web|title='Black Mirror' Season 3 Trailer: 'No One Is This Happy' |url=https://deadline.com/2016/10/black-mirror-season-3-trailer-netflix-bryce-dallas-howard-alice-eve-james-norton-1201832611/ |accessdate=7 October 2016 |website=Deadline |date=7 October 2016 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20161008153241/http://deadline.com/2016/10/black-mirror-season-3-trailer-netflix-bryce-dallas-howard-alice-eve-james-norton-1201832611/ |archive-date=8 October 2016 |url-status=live }}</ref> It was released on Netflix worldwide on 21 October 2016.<ref>{{cite journal |url=https://variety.com/2016/tv/news/black-mirror-netflix-premiere-date-gilmore-girls-the-ranch-1201824702/ |title=Netflix Original Series Premiere Dates: 'Black Mirror,' 'Gilmore Girls' and More to Drop in 2016 |first=Oriana |last=Schwindt |date=27 July 2016 |journal=Variety |access-date=11 December 2017 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20171213010751/https://variety.com/2016/tv/news/black-mirror-netflix-premiere-date-gilmore-girls-the-ranch-1201824702/ |archive-date=13 December 2017 |url-status=live }}</ref>\n\n\"[[Nosedive (Black Mirror)|Nosedive]]\" is an episode about social media written by [[Michael Schur]] and [[Rashida Jones]], and starring [[Bryce Dallas Howard]] as Lacie. \"[[Playtest (Black Mirror)|Playtest]]\" is a horror story starring [[Wyatt Russell]] as Cooper. \"[[Shut Up and Dance (Black Mirror)|Shut Up and Dance]]\" is about a blackmailed teenager, starring [[Alex Lawther]] as Kenny and [[Jerome Flynn]] as Hector, and written by Brooker and William Bridges. \"San Junipero\" is a science fiction love story starring [[Gugu Mbatha-Raw]] as Kelly and [[Mackenzie Davis]] as Yorkie. \"Men Against Fire\" is an episode about war, starring [[Malachi Kirby]] as Stripe. \"[[Hated in the Nation]]\" is a police procedural with [[Kelly Macdonald]] as Karin Parke and [[Faye Marsay]] as Blue Coulson.\n\n=== Series 4 ===\nAccording to Brooker, the fourth series has even more variety in the episodes than in previous series.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/on-demand/0/black-mirror-season-4-netflix-plus-charlie-brooker-hints-jodie/ |title=Black Mirror season 4: when is it on Netflix? Plus, Charlie Brooker hints about Jodie Foster's episode |newspaper=The Telegraph |date=20 February 2017 |access-date=3 April 2018 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180503102350/https://www.telegraph.co.uk/on-demand/0/black-mirror-season-4-netflix-plus-charlie-brooker-hints-jodie/ |archive-date=3 May 2018 |url-status=live }}</ref> Brooker says that there is \"some more hope\" in the series, crediting this to the fact that writing began in July 2016 and continued throughout the [[2016 United States presidential election]], and \"I genuinely thought, I don't know what state the world's going to be in by the time these [episodes] appear, and I don't know how much appetite there will be for nothing but bleak nihilism.\"<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.digitalspy.com/tv/black-mirror/news/a845347/black-mirror-season-4-charlie-brooker/ |title=Charlie Brooker: Black Mirror is more hopeful now because the world is more depressing |website=[[Digital Spy]] |last=Jeffery |first=Morgan |date=13 December 2017 |access-date=14 December 2017 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20171215055418/http://www.digitalspy.com/tv/black-mirror/news/a845347/black-mirror-season-4-charlie-brooker/ |archive-date=15 December 2017 |url-status=live }}</ref>\n\nIn May 2017, a [[Reddit]] post unofficially announced the names and directors of the six episodes in series 4 of ''Black Mirror''.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.independent.co.uk/arts-entertainment/tv/news/black-mirror-season-4-episode-titles-directors-charlie-brooker-netflix-jodie-foster-john-hillcoat-a7758786.html |title=Black Mirror season 4 episode titles and directors revealed |website=[[The Independent]] |last=Stolworthy |first=Jacob |date=27 May 2017 |accessdate=10 December 2017 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20171207154218/http://www.independent.co.uk/arts-entertainment/tv/news/black-mirror-season-4-episode-titles-directors-charlie-brooker-netflix-jodie-foster-john-hillcoat-a7758786.html |archive-date=7 December 2017 |url-status=live }}</ref> Filming for the fourth series concluded in June 2017.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.bleedingcool.com/2017/12/06/black-mirror-season-4-finally-gets-a-release-date/ |title=Black Mirror Season 4: Finally Gets a Release Date... in 2017 |last=Wickline |first=Dan |website=[[Bleeding Cool]] |date=6 December 2017 |accessdate=12 December 2017 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20171213012445/https://www.bleedingcool.com/2017/12/06/black-mirror-season-4-finally-gets-a-release-date/ |archive-date=13 December 2017 |url-status=live }}</ref> The first trailer for the series was released by Netflix on 25 August 2017, and contained the six episode titles.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.thewrap.com/black-mirror-season-4-teaser-trailer-episode-titles-directors-stars-drop-video/ |title='Black Mirror' Season 4: Teaser Trailer, Episode Titles, Directors and Stars Revealed (Video) |last=Donnelly |first=Matt |website=[[TheWrap]] |date=25 August 2017 |accessdate=10 December 2017 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20171210071818/https://www.thewrap.com/black-mirror-season-4-teaser-trailer-episode-titles-directors-stars-drop-video/ |archive-date=10 December 2017 |url-status=live }}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.independent.co.uk/arts-entertainment/tv/news/black-mirror-season-4-netflix-teaser-trailer-youtube-episode-titles-a7912416.html |title=Black Mirror season 4 Netflix trailer teases all six episodes and their titles |website=[[The Independent]] |last=Hooton |first=Christopher |date=25 August 2017 |accessdate=10 December 2017 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20171210074738/http://www.independent.co.uk/arts-entertainment/tv/news/black-mirror-season-4-netflix-teaser-trailer-youtube-episode-titles-a7912416.html |archive-date=10 December 2017 |url-status=live }}</ref> In September 2017, two photos from the fourth series were released.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.thewrap.com/black-mirror-season-4-photos/ |title=New 'Black Mirror' Season 4 Images Tease 'USS Callister's' Retro Goodness (Photos) |website=[[TheWrap]] |last=Velocci |first=Carli |date=7 September 2017 |accessdate=10 December 2017 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20171210123549/https://www.thewrap.com/black-mirror-season-4-photos/ |archive-date=10 December 2017 |url-status=live }}</ref> Beginning on 24 November 2017, Netflix published a series of posters and trailers for each episode in the fourth series of the program, referred to as the \"13 Days of ''Black Mirror''\",<ref name=\"THR cast\">{{cite web |url=https://www.hollywoodreporter.com/live-feed/black-mirror-season-4-guide-premiere-date-trailer-cast-episode-titles-1061669 |title='Black Mirror': All the Season 4 Details |website=[[The Hollywood Reporter]] |last=Strause |first=Jackie |date=27 November 2017 |accessdate=10 December 2017 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20171210072203/https://www.hollywoodreporter.com/live-feed/black-mirror-season-4-guide-premiere-date-trailer-cast-episode-titles-1061669 |archive-date=10 December 2017 |url-status=live }}</ref> concluding on 6 December 2017 with the announcement of the release date.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://decider.com/2017/12/06/black-mirror-season-4-trailer/ |title=Netflix Reveals 'Black Mirror' Season 4 Release Date In New Trailer |website=Decider.com |publisher=[[New York Post]] |last=White |first=Peter |date=6 December 2017 |accessdate=10 December 2017 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20171210072211/https://decider.com/2017/12/06/black-mirror-season-4-trailer/ |archive-date=10 December 2017 |url-status=live }}</ref> All six episodes were released to Netflix on 29 December 2017.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.theguardian.com/tv-and-radio/2017/dec/29/black-mirror-review-netflix-series-back-darker-charlie-brooker |title=Black Mirror review: the Netflix series is back&nbsp;\u2013 and darker than ever |first=Rebecca |last=Nicholson |date=29 December 2017 |accessdate=29 December 2017 |website=[[The Guardian]] |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20171229125055/https://www.theguardian.com/tv-and-radio/2017/dec/29/black-mirror-review-netflix-series-back-darker-charlie-brooker |archive-date=29 December 2017 |url-status=live }}</ref>\n\n\"[[USS Callister]]\" is a space epic starring [[Jesse Plemons]] as Robert Daly and [[Cristin Milioti]] as Nanette Cole. \"[[Arkangel (Black Mirror)|Arkangel]]\" is an episode about motherhood starring [[Rosemarie DeWitt]] as Marie and [[Brenna Harding]] as Sara. \"[[Crocodile (Black Mirror)|Crocodile]]\" is about the consequences of a [[hit-and-run]], starring [[Andrea Riseborough]] as Mia. \"[[Hang the DJ]]\" is a love story between Amy, played by [[Georgina Campbell]], and Frank, played by [[Joe Cole (actor)|Joe Cole]]. \"[[Metalhead (Black Mirror)|Metalhead]]\" is a black-and-white apocalypse episode starring [[Maxine Peake]] as Bella and directed by [[David Slade]]. \"[[Black Museum (Black Mirror)|Black Museum]]\" is an anthology of three stories, one of which was written by magician [[Penn Jillette]], starring [[Douglas Hodge]] as Rolo Haynes and [[Letitia Wright]] as Nish.\n\nThe first episode made for series 4 was \"Arkangel\", which was directed by [[Jodie Foster]] and filmed in Canada. The Netflix budget allowed them to set and film \"Crocodile\" in Iceland and make the special effects-intensive episode \"Metalhead\".<ref name=\"ibm\"/>{{rp|221}}\n\nAccording to ''[[Engadget]]'' and ''[[Gizmodo]]'', as a means of [[viral marketing]] Netflix sent private messages to users of the Turkish website [[Ek\u015fi S\u00f6zl\u00fck]]. The messages were sent from the account \"iamwaldo\" and read, \"We know what you're up to. Watch and see what we will do.\" Although the advertising was met with positive reception from some users, others were critical of distress that the messages may have caused.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.engadget.com/2017/12/29/maybe-private-black-mirror-messages-werent-a-good-idea-netfl/|title=Maybe private 'Black Mirror' messages weren't a good idea, Netflix|website=[[Engadget]]|last=Fingas|first=Jon|date=29 December 2017|accessdate=8 September 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180909000208/https://www.engadget.com/2017/12/29/maybe-private-black-mirror-messages-werent-a-good-idea-netfl/|archive-date=9 September 2018|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://gizmodo.com/netflix-freaks-out-users-with-creepy-black-mirror-marke-1821649915|title=Netflix Freaks Out Users with Creepy ''Black Mirror'' Marketing Stunt|website=[[Gizmodo]]|last=Jones|first=Rhett|date=29 December 2017|accessdate=8 September 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180909000444/https://gizmodo.com/netflix-freaks-out-users-with-creepy-black-mirror-marke-1821649915|archive-date=9 September 2018|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://metro.co.uk/2017/12/31/black-mirrors-strange-advert-in-the-middle-of-the-night-freaked-a-lot-of-turkish-netflix-viewers-out-it-is-not-cool-7193885/|title=Black Mirror's 'strange advert in the middle of the night' freaked a lot of Netflix viewers out: 'It is not cool'|website=[[Metro (British newspaper)|Metro]]|last=Gamp|first=Joe|date=31 December 2017|accessdate=8 September 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180909000428/https://metro.co.uk/2017/12/31/black-mirrors-strange-advert-in-the-middle-of-the-night-freaked-a-lot-of-turkish-netflix-viewers-out-it-is-not-cool-7193885/|archive-date=9 September 2018|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\n=== ''Bandersnatch'' ===\n{{main|Black Mirror: Bandersnatch}}\n\nThe first ''Black Mirror'' full-length film ''[[Black Mirror: Bandersnatch|Bandersnatch]]'' was released on Netflix on 28 December 2018, after being formally announced the day prior. Set in 1984, the film follows Stefan, portrayed by [[Fionn Whitehead]], a young programmer who begins to question reality as he adapts a sprawling fantasy novel into a video game and soon faces a mind-mangling challenge.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://deadline.com/2018/12/black-mirror-bandersnatch-trailer-netflix-film-release-date-1202526400/|title='Black Mirror: Bandersnatch' Trailer: Netflix Teases Event Film, Confirms Date|work=[[Deadline Hollywood]]|last=Tartaglione|first=Nancy|date=27 December 2018|accessdate=27 December 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20181227134141/https://deadline.com/2018/12/black-mirror-bandersnatch-trailer-netflix-film-release-date-1202526400/|archive-date=27 December 2018|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://tvline.com/2018/12/27/black-mirror-bandersnatch-movie-trailer-premiere-date-netflix-video/|title=Black Mirror: Bandersnatch Movie to Be Released on Friday \u2014 Watch Trailer|website=[[TVLine]]|last=Schwartz|first=Ryan|date=27 December 2018|accessdate=27 December 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20181227135951/https://tvline.com/2018/12/27/black-mirror-bandersnatch-movie-trailer-premiere-date-netflix-video/|archive-date=27 December 2018|url-status=live}}</ref> ''Bandersnatch'' is an [[interactive movie|interactive film]], prompting the viewer at times to select one of two choices on screen that affect how the work is shown; there are over one trillion potential paths to view the work and five distinct endings. The film also features [[Will Poulter]], [[Craig Parkinson]], [[Alice Lowe]], and [[Asim Chaudhry]].<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.hollywoodreporter.com/live-feed/black-mirror-film-bandersnatch-trailer-release-date-1165830|title=Netflix Drops Trailer, Date for 'Black Mirror' Stand-Alone Film|work=[[The Hollywood Reporter]]|last=Strause|first=Jackie|date=27 December 2018|accessdate=27 December 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20181227151926/https://www.hollywoodreporter.com/live-feed/black-mirror-film-bandersnatch-trailer-release-date-1165830|archive-date=27 December 2018|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\n=== Series 5 ===\nIn December 2017, when Brooker and executive producer Annabel Jones were asked about possibly creating a fifth series of ''Black Mirror'', they said, \"We would love to do it.\"<ref>{{cite web |url=http://metro.co.uk/2017/12/29/black-mirrors-charlie-brooker-teases-possibility-season-5-love-7191498/?ito=cbshare |title=Black Mirror's Charlie Brooker teases possibility of season 5: 'We would love to do it' |last=Starkey |first=Adam |date=29 December 2017 |website=Metro News |access-date= |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180109235546/http://metro.co.uk/2017/12/29/black-mirrors-charlie-brooker-teases-possibility-season-5-love-7191498/?ito=cbshare |archive-date=9 January 2018 |url-status=live }}</ref> Netflix announced the fifth series via social media on 5 March 2018, although they did not announce its release date or episode count.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://deadline.com/2018/03/black-mirror-renewed-for-season-5-by-netflix-1202308826/ |title='Black Mirror' Renewed For Season 5 By Netflix |last1=Andreeva |first1=Nellie |last2=Petski |first2=Denise |date=5 March 2018 |website=Deadline |access-date=5 March 2018 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180305190649/http://deadline.com/2018/03/black-mirror-renewed-for-season-5-by-netflix-1202308826/ |archive-date=5 March 2018 |url-status=live }}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=https://ew.com/tv/2018/03/05/black-mirror-season-5/ |title=''Black Mirror'' renewed for season 5 by Netflix |website=[[Entertainment Weekly]] |last=Hibberd |first=James |date=5 March 2018 |accessdate=5 March 2018 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180305224752/http://ew.com/tv/2018/03/05/black-mirror-season-5/ |archive-date=5 March 2018 |url-status=live }}</ref> On 20 March 2018, at the 2018 [[Royal Television Society]] Awards, Brooker confirmed that the fifth series had begun filming.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://screenrant.com/black-mirror-season-5-filming/ |title=Black Mirror Season 5 Has Already Begun Filming |last=Chapman |first=Tom |date=22 March 2018 |website=ScreenRant |access-date= |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180407182729/https://screenrant.com/black-mirror-season-5-filming/ |archive-date=7 April 2018 |url-status=live }}</ref> The complexity of ''Bandersnatch'', which Brooker had originally envisioned to be part of series 5, delayed remaining production of the fifth season, although Netflix still committed to release in 2019.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2018/12/28/arts/television/black-mirror-netflix-interactive.html |title='Black Mirror' Gives Power to the People |first=David |last=Streitfield |date=28 December 2018 |accessdate=28 December 2018 |work=[[The New York Times]] |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20181228101808/https://www.nytimes.com/2018/12/28/arts/television/black-mirror-netflix-interactive.html |archive-date=28 December 2018 |url-status=live }}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=https://arstechnica.com/gaming/2018/12/not-bander-snatched-black-mirror-confirms-fifth-season-plans/ |title=Not Bander-snatched: Black Mirror confirms fifth season plans |first=Sam |last=Makekovech |date=28 December 2018 |accessdate=28 December 2018 |website=[[Ars Technica]] |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20181228200230/https://arstechnica.com/gaming/2018/12/not-bander-snatched-black-mirror-confirms-fifth-season-plans/ |archive-date=28 December 2018 |url-status=live }}</ref><ref name=\"thr endings\">{{cite news|url=https://www.hollywoodreporter.com/live-feed/black-mirror-bandersnatch-charlie-brooker-talks-interactive-movie-1171496 |title='Black Mirror's' Interactive Film: How to Navigate 'Bandersnatch' |first=Jackie |last=Strause |date=29 December 2018 |accessdate=29 December 2018 |work=[[The Hollywood Reporter]] |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20181229192502/https://www.hollywoodreporter.com/live-feed/black-mirror-bandersnatch-charlie-brooker-talks-interactive-movie-1171496 |archive-date=29 December 2018 |url-status=live }}</ref><ref name=\"thr may2019\">{{cite news| url = https://www.hollywoodreporter.com/live-feed/black-mirror-team-complexity-bandersnatch-netflix-data-1213270 | title = 'Black Mirror' Duo on the Challenges of Netflix's First Interactive Movie \u2014 and Why They Would Do It Again | first = Jackie | last = Strause | date = 24 May 2019 | accessdate = 24 May 2019 | work = [[The Hollywood Reporter]] | archive-url = https://web.archive.org/web/20190524182742/https://www.hollywoodreporter.com/live-feed/black-mirror-team-complexity-bandersnatch-netflix-data-1213270 | archive-date = 24 May 2019 | url-status=live }}</ref> On 15 May 2019, a trailer for the fifth series was released, indicating it would comprise 3 episodes.<ref name=\"S5ReleaseDate\">{{cite news|url=https://www.hollywoodreporter.com/live-feed/black-mirror-season-5-cast-premiere-date-trailer-1210653 |title='Black Mirror' Reveals Cast, Premiere Date for Season 5 |first=Jackie |last=Strause |date=15 May 2019 |accessdate=15 May 2019 |work=[[The Hollywood Reporter]] |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190515125227/https://www.hollywoodreporter.com/live-feed/black-mirror-season-5-cast-premiere-date-trailer-1210653 |archive-date=15 May 2019 |url-status=live }}</ref> On 5 June 2019, all three series 5 episodes were released.\n\nThe fifth series cast includes [[Anthony Mackie]], [[Miley Cyrus]], [[Yahya Abdul-Mateen II]], [[Topher Grace]], [[Damson Idris]], [[Andrew Scott (actor)|Andrew Scott]], [[Nicole Beharie]], [[Pom Klementieff]], [[Angourie Rice]], [[Madison Davenport]], and [[Ludi Lin]].<ref name=\"S5Cast\">{{cite news|url=https://variety.com/2019/music/news/black-mirror-season-5-premiere-date-trailer-netflix-1203214490/ |title='Black Mirror' Drops Season 5 Trailer Starring Miley Cyrus; Release Date Announced |first=Danielle |last=Turchiano |date=15 May 2019 |accessdate=15 May 2019 |work=[[Variety (magazine)|Variety]] |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190515120800/https://variety.com/2019/music/news/black-mirror-season-5-premiere-date-trailer-netflix-1203214490/ |archive-date=15 May 2019 |url-status=live }}</ref>\n\n=== Future of the series ===\nIn October 2016, Brooker said that he had ideas of where sequels to both \"[[White Bear (Black Mirror)|White Bear]]\" and \"[[Be Right Back]]\" would go, but it was unlikely that either would be made.<ref name=recurring>{{cite news |url=https://www.independent.co.uk/arts-entertainment/tv/features/black-mirror-season-3-charlie-brooker-interview-release-date-joe-wright-nosedive-shut-up-and-dance-a7372841.html |title=Black Mirror's Charlie Brooker interview: 'I'm loathe to say this is the worst year ever because the next is coming' |date=21 October 2016 |newspaper=The Independent |accessdate=21 October 2016 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20161022025945/http://www.independent.co.uk/arts-entertainment/tv/features/black-mirror-season-3-charlie-brooker-interview-release-date-joe-wright-nosedive-shut-up-and-dance-a7372841.html |archive-date=22 October 2016 |url-status=live }}</ref> Brooker also stated that there were some characters in the series 3 episode \"[[Hated in the Nation]]\" who could potentially recur.<ref name=recurring /> Previously, actors have appeared in multiple ''Black Mirror'' episodes but for unrelated roles, such as [[Hannah John-Kamen]] (\"[[Fifteen Million Merits]]\" and \"[[Playtest (Black Mirror)|Playtest]]\"),<ref name=recurring /> [[Michaela Coel]] (\"[[Nosedive (Black Mirror)|Nosedive]]\" and \"[[USS Callister]]\"),<ref>{{cite web|url=https://nerdist.com/black-mirror-uss-callister-star-trek-trailer/|title=Black Mirror's \"U.S.S Callister\" Trailers Gives Us An Uneasy Star Trek Adventure|website=Nerdist|publisher=[[Nerdist Industries]]|last=Lutes|first=Alicia|date=5 December 2017|accessdate=10 December 2017|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20171210072002/https://nerdist.com/black-mirror-uss-callister-star-trek-trailer/|archive-date=10 December 2017|url-status=dead}}</ref> and [[Daniel Lapaine]] (\"[[The Entire History of You]]\" and \"[[Black Museum (Black Mirror)|Black Museum\"]]).<ref>{{cite web|url=http://heavy.com/entertainment/2017/12/black-museum-cast-characters-black-mirror/|title=Black Museum: Meet the Cast from the Black Mirror Episode|website=[[Heavy.com|Heavy]]|last=Dwilson|first=Stephanie Dube|date=29 December 2017|accessdate=31 December 2017|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20171231103500/http://heavy.com/entertainment/2017/12/black-museum-cast-characters-black-mirror/|archive-date=31 December 2017|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nWhen asked in interviews, Brooker has repeatedly stated that there are no plans for a sequel episode to \"San Junipero\". He told ''[[Los Angeles Times]]'' that they \"want to keep [Kelly and Yorkie] happy there\".<ref name=\"LATimes\">{{cite web |url=https://www.latimes.com/entertainment/envelope/la-en-st-0817-black-mirror-20170816-story.html |title='Black Mirror's' rare glimpse of technology as a means to joy earns an Emmy nod |website=[[Los Angeles Times]] |publisher=[[Tronc]] |last=Press |first=Joy |date=17 August 2017 |accessdate=13 September 2017 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170912125638/http://www.latimes.com/entertainment/envelope/la-en-st-0817-black-mirror-20170816-story.html |archive-date=12 September 2017 |url-status=live }}</ref> However, Brooker has said that the series \"may be referring to San Junipero again\" in [[Easter egg (media)|Easter eggs]], which the series has used before.<ref name=\"NME sequel\">{{cite web |url=https://www.nme.com/news/tv/charlie-brooker-black-mirror-san-junipero-sequel-2133848 |title=Charlie Brooker talks prospect of 'San Junipero' sequel episode on 'Black Mirror' |website=[[NME]] |last=Moore |first=Sam |date=3 September 2017 |access-date=12 December 2017 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180726040949/https://www.nme.com/news/tv/charlie-brooker-black-mirror-san-junipero-sequel-2133848 |archive-date=26 July 2018 |url-status=live }}</ref> Brooker has also raised the idea of doing a sequel to the episode in \"a completely different form\", such as a [[graphic novel]] or \"an experience\".<ref name=\"Hollywood interview\">{{cite web |url=https://www.hollywoodreporter.com/live-feed/black-mirror-season-4-episodes-charlie-brooker-annabel-jones-interview-spoilers-1033807 |title='Black Mirror' Bosses on \"San Junipero\" Sequel and an Unpredictable Season 4 |website=[[The Hollywood Reporter]] |last=Strause |first=Jackie |date=3 September 2017 |accessdate=13 September 2017 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170913234649/http://www.hollywoodreporter.com/live-feed/black-mirror-season-4-episodes-charlie-brooker-annabel-jones-interview-spoilers-1033807 |archive-date=13 September 2017 |url-status=live }}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.nme.com/news/tv/charlie-brooker-rules-out-direct-sequel-to-san-junipero-but-teases-a-graphic-novel-about-it-instead-2135308 |title=Charlie Brooker rules out direct sequel to 'San Junipero' but teases graphic novel about it instead |website=[[NME]] |last=Jones |first=Damian |date=7 September 2017 |accessdate=8 December 2017 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20171208070805/http://www.nme.com/news/tv/charlie-brooker-rules-out-direct-sequel-to-san-junipero-but-teases-a-graphic-novel-about-it-instead-2135308 |archive-date=8 December 2017 |url-status=live }}</ref> Brooker has suggested that the ''Bandersnatch'' character Colin Ritman (portrayed by [[Will Poulter]]) could potentially show up in future ''Black Mirror'' episodes, given that the character, in certain paths, seems to just disappear but has awareness of alternate timelines and realities.<ref name=\"thr s5\">{{cite news| url = https://www.hollywoodreporter.com/live-feed/black-mirrors-charlie-brooker-talks-season-5-1172112 | title = 'Black Mirror' Creator Charlie Brooker Shares Season 5 Update | first = Jackie | last = Strause | date = 2 January 2019 | accessdate = 2 January 2019 | work = [[The Hollywood Reporter]] | archive-url = https://web.archive.org/web/20190102182001/https://www.hollywoodreporter.com/live-feed/black-mirrors-charlie-brooker-talks-season-5-1172112 | archive-date = 2 January 2019 | url-status=live }}</ref>\n\nAround January 2020, Brooker and Jones announced their departure from House of Tomorrow, the show's production company with the [[Endemol Shine UK|Endemol Shine group]] which the two had led, during their negotiations with Netflix that had started mid-2019. ''[[Variety (magazine)|Variety]]'' reported that [[intellectual property]] issues were at the center of this change, with the series' rights held by Endemol.<ref>{{cite web | url = https://variety.com/2020/tv/news/black-mirror-charlie-brooker-annabel-jones-netflix-endemol-shine-group-1203478778/ | title = 'Black Mirror' Creators Quit Endemol Shine-Owned Label While Navigating IP Headaches With Netflix | first = Manori | last = Ravindran | date = 24 January 2020 | accessdate = 25 January 2020 | work = [[Variety (magazine)|Variety]] }}</ref> By February 2020 Brooker and Jones established Broke and Bones, a new production company with each having a 50% stake in it.<ref>{{cite web | url = https://deadline.com/2020/02/black-mirror-charlie-brooker-annabel-jones-launch-broke-and-bones-1202853906/ | title = 'Black Mirror' Creators Charlie Brooker & Annabel Jones Waste Little Time In Launching New Production Outfit | first = Jake | last = Kanter | date = 10 February 2020 | accessdate = 10 February 2020 | work = [[Deadline Hollywood]] }}</ref>\n\n== Reception ==\n\n=== Critical response ===\nOn [[Rotten Tomatoes]], series 1 received a 97% rating,<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.rottentomatoes.com/tv/black_mirror/s01/|title=Black Mirror: Season 1 |website=[[Rotten Tomatoes]]|accessdate=6 December 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190409024525/https://www.rottentomatoes.com/tv/black_mirror/s01|archive-date=9 April 2019|url-status=live}}</ref> series 2 received an 86% rating,<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.rottentomatoes.com/tv/black_mirror/s02|title=Black Mirror: Season 2 |website=[[Rotten Tomatoes]]|accessdate=6 December 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190409024523/https://www.rottentomatoes.com/tv/black_mirror/s02|archive-date=9 April 2019|url-status=live}}</ref> \"White Christmas\" received a 93% rating,<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.rottentomatoes.com/tv/black_mirror/17660|title=Black Mirror: White Christmas (2014 Christmas Special) |website=[[Rotten Tomatoes]]|accessdate=6 December 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190407104818/https://www.rottentomatoes.com/tv/black_mirror/17660|archive-date=7 April 2019|url-status=live}}</ref> series 3 received an 86% rating<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.rottentomatoes.com/tv/black_mirror/s03|title=Black Mirror: Season 3|website=[[Rotten Tomatoes]]|accessdate=6 December 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20181208205532/https://www.rottentomatoes.com/tv/black_mirror/s03/|archive-date=8 December 2018|url-status=live}}</ref> and a score of 82 on [[Metacritic]],<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.metacritic.com/tv/black-mirror/season-3|title=Black Mirror - Season 3 Reviews |website=[[Metacritic]]|accessdate=6 December 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20181216071628/https://www.metacritic.com/tv/black-mirror/season-3|archive-date=16 December 2018|url-status=live}}</ref> series 4 received an 84% rating on Rotten Tomatoes<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.rottentomatoes.com/tv/black_mirror/s04|title=Black Mirror: Season 4 |website=[[Rotten Tomatoes]]|accessdate=6 December 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190410102351/https://www.rottentomatoes.com/tv/black_mirror/s04|archive-date=10 April 2019|url-status=live}}</ref> and a score of 72 on Metacritic,<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.metacritic.com/tv/black-mirror/season-4|title=Black Mirror - Season 4 Reviews |website=[[Metacritic]]|accessdate=6 December 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20181107061750/https://www.metacritic.com/tv/black-mirror/season-4|archive-date=7 November 2018|url-status=live}}</ref> ''Bandersnatch'' holds a 72% rating on Rotten Tomatoes<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.rottentomatoes.com/tv/black_mirror/52530 |title=Black Mirror: Bandersnatch |accessdate=12 April 2019 |website=[[Rotten Tomatoes]] |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190328224829/https://www.rottentomatoes.com/tv/black_mirror/52530 |archive-date=28 March 2019 |url-status=live }}</ref> and a score of 61 on Metacritic,<ref>{{cite web | url = https://www.metacritic.com/tv/black-mirror-bandersnatch | title = Black Mirror: Bandersnatch | accessdate = 12 April 2019 | publisher = [[Metacritic]] | archive-url = https://web.archive.org/web/20190416101857/https://www.metacritic.com/tv/black-mirror-bandersnatch | archive-date = 16 April 2019 | url-status=live }}</ref> and series 5 holds a rating of 63% on Rotten Tomatoes<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.rottentomatoes.com/tv/black_mirror/s05|title=Black Mirror: Season 5 |website=[[Rotten Tomatoes]]|accessdate=5 June 2019}}</ref> and a score of 65 on Metacritic.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.metacritic.com/tv/black-mirror/season-5|title=Black Mirror: Season 5|website=[[Metacritic]]|accessdate=8 June 2019}}</ref>\n\nThe first series has been praised as being creative and shocking with twists-in-the-tale reminiscent of ''[[The Twilight Zone]]''.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.rottentomatoes.com/tv/black-mirror/s01/ |title=Black Mirror |website=Rotten Tomatoes |access-date=26 January 2015 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150208025557/http://www.rottentomatoes.com/tv/black-mirror/s01 |archive-date=8 February 2015 |url-status=live }}</ref><ref name=\"Tele1Hogan\">{{cite news |title=Black Mirror: The National Anthem, Channel 4, review |newspaper=The Daily Telegraph |first=Michael |last=Hogan |date=4 December 2011|title-link=The National Anthem (Black Mirror) }}</ref> Michael Hogan of ''[[The Daily Telegraph]]'' described the first episode, \"[[The National Anthem (Black Mirror)|The National Anthem]]\", as \"a shocking but ballsy, blackly comic study of the modern media\".<ref name=\"Tele1Hogan\" /> He continued: \"This was a dementedly brilliant idea. The satire was so audacious, it left me open-mouthed and squealing. Rather like that poor pig.\"<ref name=\"Tele1Hogan\" /> The series was taken up across much of the world, including Australia, Israel, Sweden, Spain, Poland, Hungary and China.<ref name=\"ChigTri1\">{{cite news |title='Black Mirror' sold to 21 territories: Satirical drama premiered on U.K.'s Channel 4 |url=http://articles.chicagotribune.com/2012-03-29/entertainment/sns-201203291204reedbusivarietynvr1118052051mar29_1_satirical-drama-territories-uk-s-channel |newspaper=Chicago Tribune |accessdate=17 March 2013 |first=Elsa |last=Keslassy |date=29 March 2012 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20131230234740/http://articles.chicagotribune.com/2012-03-29/entertainment/sns-201203291204reedbusivarietynvr1118052051mar29_1_satirical-drama-territories-uk-s-channel |archive-date=30 December 2013 |url-status=live }}</ref> The series has become popular and been well received in China, becoming one of the most discussed series in early 2012.<ref name=\"gz\">{{cite web |url=http://ent.163.com/12/0204/04/7PD1GBIV00032DGD.html |title=\u82f1\u5267\u300a\u9ed1\u955c\u300b\u88ab\u79f0\"\u795e\u5267\" \u53cd\u6620\u4eba\u6027\u5f31\u70b9\u5f15\u70ed\u8bae |website=Guangzhou Daily News |date=4 February 2012 |accessdate=8 August 2012 |language=zh |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120408071751/http://ent.163.com/12/0204/04/7PD1GBIV00032DGD.html |archive-date=8 April 2012 |url-status=dead }}</ref> User ratings on [[Douban]] reached 9.3,<ref name=\"chain\">{{cite web |url=http://tech.sina.com.cn/i/2012-04-07/04486923463_2.shtml |title=\u4e92\u8054\u7f51\u9119\u89c6\u98df\u7269\u94fe\u5927\u5168 |website=[[Southern Metropolis Daily]] |date=7 April 2012 |accessdate=8 August 2012 |language=zh |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120409210847/http://tech.sina.com.cn/i/2012-04-07/04486923463_2.shtml |archive-date=9 April 2012 |url-status=live }}</ref> higher than most popular American dramas.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://culture.ifeng.com/whrd/detail_2012_04/05/13671813_0.shtml |title=\u8ff7\u4f60\u82f1\u5267\u5f3a\u52bf\u5165\u4fb5 \u5c0f\u4e2a\u5934\u5267\u96c6\u53d7\u5927\u6bd4\u4f8b\u89c2\u4f17\u6b22\u8fce |website=[[Southern Weekly]] |date=5 April 2012 |accessdate=8 August 2012 |language=zh |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20130320225409/http://culture.ifeng.com/whrd/detail_2012_04/05/13671813_0.shtml |archive-date=20 March 2013 |url-status=live }}</ref> Many viewers and critics praised the depth of the series.<ref name=\"gz\" /><ref name=\"chain\" /><ref name=\"bjnews\" /> A reporter from ''The Beijing News'' thought the programme was \"an [[apocalypse]] of modern world\", \"desperate but profound\".<ref name=\"bjnews\">{{cite web |url=http://epaper.bjnews.com.cn/html/2012-02/24/content_319498.htm?div=-1 |title=\u300a\u9ed1\u955c\u300b Black Mirror |website=Beijing News |date=24 February 2012 |accessdate=8 August 2012 |language=zh |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20141218112519/http://epaper.bjnews.com.cn/html/2012-02/24/content_319498.htm?div=-1 |archive-date=18 December 2014 |url-status=live }}</ref> Another article from the same newspaper thought each story criticised television from different aspects.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.bjnews.com.cn/feature/2012/02/17/182968.html |title=\u300a\u9ed1\u955c\u300b \u7528\u7535\u89c6\u5267\u8bbd\u523a\u7535\u89c6\u5267 |website=Beijing News |date=17 February 2012 |accessdate=8 August 2012 |language=zh |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20121018005630/http://www.bjnews.com.cn/feature/2012/02/17/182968.html |archive-date=18 October 2012 |url-status=live }}</ref> Xu Wen at ''[[The Epoch Times]]'' thought the stories reveal modernity's moral turpitude.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.epochtimes.com/gb/12/2/16/n3514116.htm |title=\u300a\u9ed1\u955c\u300b\u5bf9\u73b0\u65f6\u7684\u97ad\u631e\u4e0e\u601d\u8003 |author=Xu Wen |website=The Epoch Times |date=16 February 2012 |accessdate=8 August 2012 |language=zh |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20130320225404/http://www.epochtimes.com/gb/12/2/16/n3514116.htm |archive-date=20 March 2013 |url-status=live }}</ref>\n\nIn its second series, ''Black Mirror'' continued to receive praise. In his review of the episode \"[[Be Right Back]]\", Sameer Rahim of ''The Telegraph'' wrote, \"The show touched on important ideas&nbsp;\u2013 the false way we sometimes present ourselves online, and our growing addiction to virtual lives&nbsp;\u2013 but it was also a touching exploration of grief. To my mind it's the best thing Brooker has done.\"<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/culture/tvandradio/tv-and-radio-reviews/9863062/Black-Mirror-Be-Right-Back-Channel-4-review.html |title=Black Mirror: Be Right Back, Channel 4, review |last=Rahim |first=Sameer |date=11 February 2013 |website=Telegraph |access-date=19 January 2019 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180912022340/https://www.telegraph.co.uk/culture/tvandradio/tv-and-radio-reviews/9863062/Black-Mirror-Be-Right-Back-Channel-4-review.html |archive-date=12 September 2018 |url-status=live }}</ref> Jane Simon of  ''[[The Daily Mirror]]'' newspaper website said the second episode of the second series, \"[[White Bear (Black Mirror)|White Bear]]\", lacked the \"instant emotional tug\" of the series opener, \"Be Right Back\".<ref name=\"Mirror1\">{{cite news |title=Charlie Brooker's second Black Mirror drama 'White Bear' is another work of dark and twisted genius |url=https://www.mirror.co.uk/tv/tv-previews/black-mirror-channel-4-video-1714613 |newspaper=The Daily Mirror |publisher=MGN Ltd. |accessdate=17 March 2013 |first=Jane |last=Simon |date=18 February 2013 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20130316091755/http://www.mirror.co.uk/tv/tv-previews/black-mirror-channel-4-video-1714613 |archive-date=16 March 2013 |url-status=live }}</ref> She continued: a third of the way through the second episode, she had lost hope of its concluding well, \"the acting was unbelievable, the script was riddled with horror-film cliches, the violence was a bit over the top\", but that by the end, \"I turned out to be absolutely dead wrong on every single count.\" She ended the piece with: \"It's another work of dark and twisted genius from Mr Brooker.\"  The second series is popular in China. Wen Bai at ''[[Information Times]]'' thought the second series was still \"cannily made\", and \"near perfection\".<ref>{{cite web|url=http://informationtimes.dayoo.com/html/2013-03/11/content_2175973.htm |title=\u7eed\u96c6\u4e5f\u53ef\u5982\u6b64\u7f8e\u597d |website=Information Times |date=11 March 2013 |accessdate=17 March 2013 |author=\u6587\u767d |language=zh |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140201203355/http://informationtimes.dayoo.com/html/2013-03/11/content_2175973.htm |archivedate=1 February 2014 |df=dmy-all }}</ref>\n\nIn December 2014, [[Stephen King]] noted his admiration for the series.<ref>{{cite tweet |last=King|first=Stephen|author-link=Stephen King|user=StephenKing|number=541660684720021504|date=7 December 2014 |title=Loved BLACK MIRROR. Terrifying, funny, intelligent. It's like THE TWILIGHT ZONE, only rated R.||access-date=26 February 2017}}</ref><ref name=premds>{{cite web |title=Black Mirror: Charlie Brooker, Jon Hamm on the dark side of Yuletide |url=http://www.digitalspy.co.uk/tv/interviews/a616435/black-mirror-charlie-brooker-jon-hamm-on-the-dark-side-of-yuletide.html |accessdate=14 December 2014 |website=Digital Spy |date=14 December 2014 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20141214172129/http://www.digitalspy.co.uk/tv/interviews/a616435/black-mirror-charlie-brooker-jon-hamm-on-the-dark-side-of-yuletide.html |archive-date=14 December 2014 |url-status=live }}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.denofgeek.com/tv/black-mirror/33368/black-mirror-interview-charlie-brooker-jon-hamm-rafe-spall |title=Black Mirror interview: Charlie Brooker, Jon Hamm, Rafe Spall |website=Den of Geek |access-date=15 March 2016 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160107103939/http://www.denofgeek.com/tv/black-mirror/33368/black-mirror-interview-charlie-brooker-jon-hamm-rafe-spall |archive-date=7 January 2016 |url-status=live }}</ref> The series' Christmas special that year, \"[[White Christmas (Black Mirror)|White Christmas]]\", received critical acclaim. Ben Beaumont-Thomas of ''[[The Guardian]]'' praised the comic satire of the episode and noted that \"sentimentality is offset with wicked wit, and Brooker's brio and imagination paper over any gaps in logic.\"<ref>{{cite news |first=Ben |last=Beaumont-Thomas |url=https://www.theguardian.com/media/2014/dec/12/black-mirror-charlie-brooker-rafe-spall-jon-hamm |title=Black Mirror: White Christmas review&nbsp;\u2013 sentimentality offset with wicked wit |newspaper=[[The Guardian]] |date=12 December 2014 |accessdate=17 December 2014 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150808040919/http://www.theguardian.com/media/2014/dec/12/black-mirror-charlie-brooker-rafe-spall-jon-hamm |archive-date=8 August 2015 |url-status=live }}</ref> ''The Daily Telegraph'' reviewer Mark Monahan gave the episode 4/5 stars, noting that the drama was \"thrilling stuff: escapist entertainment with a very real-world sting in its tail\". Monahan equated the episode with the stronger of the previous ''Black Mirror'' episodes, stating that \"it exaggerated present-day technology and obsessions to subtle but infernal effect, a nightmare-before-Christmas reminder that to revere our digital gizmos is to become their pathetic slave.\"<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/culture/tvandradio/tv-and-radio-reviews/11295878/black-mirror-christmas-special-review-the-nightmares-before-christmas.html |title=Black Mirror: White Christmas, review: 'Be careful what you wish for...' |first=Mark |last=Monahan |newspaper=[[The Daily Telegraph]] |date=17 December 2014 |accessdate=17 December 2014 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20141216233722/http://www.telegraph.co.uk/culture/tvandradio/tv-and-radio-reviews/11295878/black-mirror-christmas-special-review-the-nightmares-before-christmas.html |archive-date=16 December 2014 |url-status=live }}</ref> In 2019, ''Black Mirror'' was ranked 23rd on ''The Guardian'''s list of the 100 best TV shows of the 21st century.<ref>{{cite web |title= The 100 best TV shows of the 21st century |url=https://www.theguardian.com/tv-and-radio/2019/sep/16/100-best-tv-shows-of-the-21st-century |website=The Guardian |accessdate=23 September 2019}}</ref>\n\nJournalists have reported that some of the concepts in ''Black Mirror'' have come true, in fashion, within the real world and have called the series a [[Magic 8-Ball]] for the future.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.thedailybeast.com/black-mirror-is-tvs-magic-8-ball |title='Black Mirror' Is TV's Magic 8-Ball |first=G. Clay |last=Whitaker |date=14 September 2015 |accessdate=15 December 2017 |website=[[The Daily Beast]] |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170820214301/http://www.thedailybeast.com/black-mirror-is-tvs-magic-8-ball |archive-date=20 August 2017 |url-status=live }}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.inverse.com/article/15540-how-many-episodes-of-black-mirror-have-already-come-true |title=The 7 'Black Mirror' Prophecies That Have Come True |first=Brock |last=Wilbur |date=13 May 2016 |accessdate=15 December 2017 |website=Inverse |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20171216144027/https://www.inverse.com/article/15540-how-many-episodes-of-black-mirror-have-already-come-true |archive-date=16 December 2017 |url-status=live }}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/bbcthree/item/5c0ce0ab-c88f-45be-b44d-59841e5f9e64 |title=Seven creepy Black Mirror predictions that actually came true |first=Catriona |last=White |date=14 December 2017 |accessdate=15 December 2017 |website=[[BBC Three]] |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20171223235107/http://www.bbc.co.uk/bbcthree/item/5c0ce0ab-c88f-45be-b44d-59841e5f9e64 |archive-date=23 December 2017 |url-status=live }}</ref> The first episode, \"[[The National Anthem (Black Mirror)|The National Anthem]]\", revolves around the British Prime Minister's being blackmailed into having sex with a pig; in September 2015, four years after the episode aired, allegations were published that [[David Cameron]], who at the time was British Prime Minister, had placed a \"private part\" into the mouth of a dead pig as part of a university initiation rite.<ref>{{cite news |title=Black Mirror creator Charlie Brooker denies he knew about #Hameron |newspaper=[[Metro (British newspaper)|Metro]] |date=21 September 2015 |first=Nicole |last=Morley |url=http://metro.co.uk/2015/09/21/black-mirror-creator-charlie-brooker-denies-he-knew-about-hameron-5400774/ |access-date=15 December 2017 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20171119225940/http://metro.co.uk/2015/09/21/black-mirror-creator-charlie-brooker-denies-he-knew-about-hameron-5400774/ |archive-date=19 November 2017 |url-status=live }}</ref> Brooker has called the event a \"coincidence, albeit a quite bizarre one\" and was perturbed when he first heard the allegations: \"I did genuinely for a moment wonder if reality was a simulation, whether it exists only to trick me\", he said in an interview.<ref name=\"piggate guardian\">{{cite web |url=https://www.theguardian.com/tv-and-radio/shortcuts/2015/sep/21/pigs-prime-minister-black-mirror-ashcroft-allegation-charlie-brooker |title=Charlie Brooker on Cameron and #piggate: 'I'd have been screaming it into traffic if I'd known' |website=[[The Guardian]] |last=Benedictus |first=Leo |date=21 September 2015 |accessdate=7 September 2017 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150923010128/http://www.theguardian.com/tv-and-radio/shortcuts/2015/sep/21/pigs-prime-minister-black-mirror-ashcroft-allegation-charlie-brooker |archive-date=23 September 2015 |url-status=live }}</ref> Several news reports compared [[Donald Trump presidential campaign, 2016|Donald Trump's 2016 presidential campaign]] to \"[[The Waldo Moment]]\", a 2013 episode in the second series;<ref name=\"WP-20150908\">{{cite news |last=Cillizza |first=Chris |authorlink=Chris Cillizza |title=Donald Trump's troll game of Jeb Bush: A+ |url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/news/the-fix/wp/2015/09/08/donald-trumps-troll-game-of-jeb-bush-a/ |date=8 September 2015 |newspaper=[[The Washington Post]] |accessdate=24 October 2015 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20151017031625/https://www.washingtonpost.com/news/the-fix/wp/2015/09/08/donald-trumps-troll-game-of-jeb-bush-a/ |archive-date=17 October 2015 |url-status=live }}</ref><ref name=\"DC-20150807\">{{cite web |last=O'Keefe |first=Meghan |title=Why You Must Watch 'Black Mirror': \"The Waldo Moment\" This Weekend |url=http://decider.com/2015/08/07/black-mirror-the-waldo-effect-2016-presidential-race/ |date=7 August 2015 |website=Decider |accessdate=24 October 2015 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20151011065627/http://decider.com/2015/08/07/black-mirror-the-waldo-effect-2016-presidential-race/ |archive-date=11 October 2015 |url-status=live }}</ref> later, in September 2016, Brooker also compared the Trump campaign to the episode and predicted Trump would win the 2016 election.<ref name=\"DB-20160913\">{{cite news |last=Yamato |first=Jen |title='Black Mirror' Creator Predicts Trump Will Be President: 'I Find It F*cking Terrifying' |url=http://www.thedailybeast.com/articles/2016/09/13/black-mirror-creator-predicts-trump-will-be-president-i-find-it-f-cking-terrifying.html |date=13 September 2016 |work=[[The Daily Beast]] |accessdate=8 October 2016 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20161009171420/http://www.thedailybeast.com/articles/2016/09/13/black-mirror-creator-predicts-trump-will-be-president-i-find-it-f-cking-terrifying.html |archive-date=9 October 2016 |url-status=live }}</ref><ref name=\"BMD-20160913\">{{cite web|last=Wampler |first=Scott |title=Black Mirror's Charlie Brooker Predicts Trump Will Win The Election |url=http://birthmoviesdeath.com/2016/09/13/black-mirrors-charlie-brooker-predicts-that-trump-will-win-the-election |date=13 September 2016 |website=BirthMoviesDeath.com |accessdate=8 October 2016 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20161010073127/http://birthmoviesdeath.com/2016/09/13/black-mirrors-charlie-brooker-predicts-that-trump-will-win-the-election |archive-date=10 October 2016 |url-status=live }}</ref> The third series episode \"[[Nosedive (Black Mirror)|Nosedive]]\" presented a social rating-based system that several found mirrored by China's proposed [[Social Credit System]].<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/world/asia_pacific/chinas-plan-to-organize-its-whole-society-around-big-data-a-rating-for-everyone/2016/10/20/1cd0dd9c-9516-11e6-ae9d-0030ac1899cd_story.html |title=China's plan to organize its society relies on 'big data' to rate everyone |website=[[The Washington Post]] |last=Denyer |first=Simon |date=22 October 2016 |accessdate=10 October 2017 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20171010060617/https://www.washingtonpost.com/world/asia_pacific/chinas-plan-to-organize-its-whole-society-around-big-data-a-rating-for-everyone/2016/10/20/1cd0dd9c-9516-11e6-ae9d-0030ac1899cd_story.html |archive-date=10 October 2017 |url-status=live }}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.avclub.com/at-least-one-black-mirror-episode-is-already-coming-tru-1821315524 |title=At least one Black Mirror episode is already coming true in China |first=William |last=Hughes |date=15 December 2017 |accessdate=15 December 2017 |website=[[The A.V. Club]] |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20171215062920/https://www.avclub.com/at-least-one-black-mirror-episode-is-already-coming-tru-1821315524 |archive-date=15 December 2017 |url-status=live }}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/on-demand/2017/12/15/black-mirror-coming-true-china-rating-affects-home-transport/ |title=Black Mirror is coming true in China, where your 'rating' affects your home, transport and social circle |first=Alice |last=Vincent |date=15 December 2017 |accessdate=15 December 2017 |website=[[The Daily Telegraph]] |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20171215111451/http://www.telegraph.co.uk/on-demand/2017/12/15/black-mirror-coming-true-china-rating-affects-home-transport/ |archive-date=15 December 2017 |url-status=live }}</ref> Brooker has been surprised to see how some of these events had come to pass. \"It was quite trippy, though. I'm kind of getting used to it, because it seems like it's quite often that there are things that are in the stories that come true.\"<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.thedailybeast.com/black-mirror-creator-charlie-brooker-on-chinas-social-credit-system-and-the-rise-of-trump |title='Black Mirror' Creator Charlie Brooker on China's 'Social Credit' System and the Rise of Trump |first=Marlow |last=Stern |date=27 October 2017 |accessdate=15 December 2017 |website=[[The Daily Beast]] |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170908214223/http://www.thedailybeast.com/black-mirror-creator-charlie-brooker-on-chinas-social-credit-system-and-the-rise-of-trump |archive-date=8 September 2017 |url-status=live }}</ref> Ten days after the release of series 4 episode \"[[Crocodile (Black Mirror)|Crocodile]]\" \u2013 which included a self-driving pizza delivery truck as a major plot device \u2013 [[Toyota]] and [[Pizza Hut]] announced the e-Palette, a driverless delivery vehicle, at the 2018 [[Consumer Electronics Show]]. The conceptual vehicle drew numerous comparisons with its fictional counterpart,<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.thrillist.com/entertainment/nation/black-mirror-season-4-crocodile-episode-pizza-hut-delivery-truck|title=The 'Black Mirror' Killer Pizza Truck Is Real Now, Thanks to Pizza Hut|last=Fitz-Gerald|first=Sean|date=2018-01-09|work=Thrillist|access-date=2018-08-08|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180808073237/https://www.thrillist.com/entertainment/nation/black-mirror-season-4-crocodile-episode-pizza-hut-delivery-truck|archive-date=8 August 2018|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.highsnobiety.com/p/pizza-hut-black-mirror-truck/|title=Pizza Hut Goes 'Black Mirror' With Self-Driving Pizza Truck|date=2018-08-07|work=Highsnobiety|access-date=2018-08-08|language=en-US|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180808104340/https://www.highsnobiety.com/p/pizza-hut-black-mirror-truck/|archive-date=8 August 2018|url-status=live}}</ref> and the official Twitter account for ''Black Mirror'' commented on the announcement, saying, \"We know how this goes.\"<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://twitter.com/blackmirror/status/950506825035780096|title=Black Mirror on Twitter|work=Twitter|access-date=2018-08-08|language=en|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180215125811/https://twitter.com/blackmirror/status/950506825035780096|archive-date=15 February 2018|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\n=== Accolades ===\n{{Main|List of awards and nominations received by Black Mirror}}\nIn November 2012, ''Black Mirror'' won [[International Emmy Award for best TV movie or miniseries|Best TV Movie/Miniseries]] at the [[International Academy of Television Arts and Sciences|International Emmy Awards]].<ref name=\"BBC 2012\">{{cite news |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/entertainment-arts-20406749 |publisher=BBC News |title=Black Mirror and Pratchett film win International Emmys |date=20 November 2012 |access-date=21 July 2018 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20181011092848/https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/entertainment-arts-20406749 |archive-date=11 October 2018 |url-status=live }}</ref> Bryce Dallas Howard received a [[Screen Actors Guild Award for Outstanding Performance by a Female Actor in a Miniseries or Television Movie|Screen Actors Guild Award]] nomination for her performance in the episode \"[[Nosedive (Black Mirror)|Nosedive]]\".<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.ew.com/article/2016/12/14/2017-sag-awards-nominations |title=SAG Awards nominations 2017: See the full list |first=Joey |last=Nolfi |website=Entertainment Weekly |date=14 December 2016 |access-date=15 December 2016 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170111005833/http://www.ew.com/article/2016/12/14/2017-sag-awards-nominations |archive-date=11 January 2017 |url-status=live }}</ref> At the [[69th Primetime Emmy Awards]], ''Black Mirror'' received three nominations with two wins, including [[Primetime Emmy Award for Outstanding Television Movie|Outstanding Television Movie]] for \"[[San Junipero]]\".<ref name=\":0\">{{cite web |url=http://metro.co.uk/2017/06/24/charlie-brooker-says-black-mirror-season-4-will-be-the-most-out-there-yet-as-he-teases-new-details-6731644/ |title=Charlie Brooker teases Black Mirror season 4 will be the most 'out there' yet |last=Starkey |first=Adam |date=24 June 2017 |website=Metro |access-date=17 July 2017 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170729161318/http://metro.co.uk/2017/06/24/charlie-brooker-says-black-mirror-season-4-will-be-the-most-out-there-yet-as-he-teases-new-details-6731644/ |archive-date=29 July 2017 |url-status=live }}</ref><ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.huffingtonpost.com/entry/black-mirrors-san-junipero-nominated-for-two-emmys-and-were-crying_us_59679cdbe4b0a8d46d12eae7 |title=Black Mirror's 'San Junipero' Nominated For Two Emmys And We're Crying |last=Amatulli |first=Jenna |date=13 July 2017 |work=Huffington Post |access-date=17 July 2017 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170716115927/http://www.huffingtonpost.com/entry/black-mirrors-san-junipero-nominated-for-two-emmys-and-were-crying_us_59679cdbe4b0a8d46d12eae7 |archive-date=16 July 2017 |url-status=live }}</ref> \"[[USS Callister]]\" received three Emmy Awards, including Outstanding Television Movie, and four Emmy nominations in 2018.<ref name=\"USS Callister Black Mirror\">{{cite web|url=https://www.emmys.com/shows/uss-callister-black-mirror|title=USS Callister (Black Mirror)|publisher=[[Academy of Television Arts & Sciences]]|access-date=13 July 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180712221955/https://www.emmys.com/shows/uss-callister-black-mirror|archive-date=12 July 2018|url-status=live}}</ref><ref name=\"USS Callister Black Mirror\"/><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.emmys.com/shows/black-museum-black-mirror|title=Black Museum (Black Mirror)|publisher=[[Academy of Television Arts & Sciences]]|access-date=13 July 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180712224146/https://www.emmys.com/shows/black-museum-black-mirror|archive-date=12 July 2018|url-status=live}}</ref> ''Bandersnatch'' won two Emmys in 2019, including Outstanding Television Movie, making it the third consecutive win for ''Black Mirror'' in that category.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://pitchfork.com/news/emmys-2019-black-mirror-bandersnatch-wins-outstanding-tv-movie/|title=Emmys 2019: ''Black Mirror: Bandersnatch'' Wins Outstanding TV Movie|work=[[Pitchfork (website)|Pitchfork]]|last=Hussey|first=Allison|date=23 September 2019|accessdate=23 September 2019}}</ref>\n\n==Spin-off media==\n===Webisodes===\n{{external media\n|topic=Czarne Lusterko\n|video1=\"[https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=Y_igsGHD7Hg The Sum of Happiness]\"\n|video2=\"[https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=z1o1kvjTzG8 69.90]\"\n|video3=\"[https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=MFUUydRo-OQ 1%]\"\n|video4=\"[https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=LN_eEJFtQtE The Breakup]\"\n}}\nA series of webisodes ''Czarne Lusterko'' (Polish for ''Little Black Mirror'') was produced for Netflix Polska by Jacek Ambrosiewicz, in collaboration with Polish YouTubers. Released on 19 January 2018, the four shorts vary between eight and 21 minutes in length. \"69.90\" explores \"loneliness and gaming\" according to creators Huyen Pham and Marcin Nguyen, who discussed twenty different ideas for the episode before deciding upon an episode featuring a computer simulation which is indistinguishable from real life. \"The Breakup\" features Krzysztof Gonciarz and Kasia Mecinski; it used realism and ordinary technology, being filmed in part on a [[Panasonic Lumix DC-GH5]] to emulate [[vlog]] aesthetics. \"The Sum of Happiness\" was posted on Martin Stankiewicz's YouTube channel and focuses on a neurological implant and a relationship app, which have been featured before in ''Black Mirror''. \"1%\" is about a \"fallible\" and \"ruthless\" piece of [[obstetrics]] technology.<ref name=\"Lusterko\">{{cite web|url=https://i-d.vice.com/en_uk/article/43b3ep/the-polish-version-of-black-mirror-might-be-the-best-thing-on-the-internet|title=The Polish version of Black Mirror might be the best thing on the internet|work=[[Vice Media]]|last=Greenhill|first=Richard|date=2 April 2018|accessdate=1 July 2019|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190526093523/https://i-d.vice.com/en_uk/article/43b3ep/the-polish-version-of-black-mirror-might-be-the-best-thing-on-the-internet|archive-date=26 May 2019|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\n{{external media\n|topic=Stories From Our Future\n|video1=\"[https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=RqATb20dO34 Cure for Loneliness]\"\n|video2=\"[https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=gCwEJiQpaXc Getting to Know You]\"\n|video3=\"[https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=xdOC8WIXAkE The Healthy Alternative]\"\n}}\nA second series of webisodes, initially announced as ''Little Black Mirror'' but eventually renamed ''Stories From Our Future'', was directed for Netflix Am\u00e9rica Latina by American YouTuber [[Rudy Mancuso]].<ref name=\"Little Black Mirror\">{{cite web|url=https://io9.gizmodo.com/little-black-mirror-is-a-series-of-black-mirror-webisod-1835025432|title=Little Black Mirror Is a Series of Black Mirror Webisodes Coming to Netflix's Latin American YouTube Channel|work=[[io9]]|last=Muncy|first=Julie|date=26 May 2019|accessdate=26 May 2019|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190525202908/https://io9.gizmodo.com/little-black-mirror-is-a-series-of-black-mirror-webisod-1835025432|archive-date=25 May 2019|url-status=live}}</ref><ref name=\"Stories From Our FUture\">{{cite web|url=https://decider.com/2019/06/02/little-black-mirror-renamed-stories-from-our-future-by-netflix/|title='Little Black Mirror' Renamed 'Stories From Our Future' By Netflix|work=[[Decider (website)|Decider]]|last=Otterson|first=Joe|date=2 June 2019|accessdate=27 June 2019}}</ref> Initially planned for release on Netflix Am\u00e9rica Latina's YouTube channel, as part of promotion for the programme's fifth series, the original trailer for the project was removed by Netflix. The shorts were later released on 10 June 2019 on channels of individuals who feature in them.<ref name=\"DS SFOF\"/> \"Cure for Loneliness\" was released on Mancuso's channel; \"Getting to Know You\" was released on YouTuber [[Lele Pons]]' channel; \"The Healthy Alternative\" was released on vlogger [[Juanpa Zurita]]'s channel.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://heavy.com/entertainment/2019/06/watch-little-black-mirror-short-films-stories-from-our-future/|title=Watch 'Little Black Mirror' Short Films: Stories From Our Future|work=[[Heavy.com|Heavy]]|last=Dwilson|first=Stephanie Dube|date=12 June 2019|accessdate=1 July 2019}}</ref> Also featured in the series is Australian actor [[Maia Mitchell]].<ref name=\"DS SFOF\">{{cite web|url=https://www.digitalspy.com/tv/a27715097/black-mirror-spin-off-you-tube-little-stories-from-our-future/|title=Here's why you probably won't see Black Mirror's first spin-off|work=[[Digital Spy]]|last=Jeffery|first=Morgan|date=4 June 2019|accessdate=1 July 2019}}</ref>\n\n=== Literature ===\nIn June 2018, Brooker announced that he, along with Annabel Jones and [[Jason Arnopp]], have written an oral history companion to the series titled ''Inside Black Mirror''. The book features sections on each of the 19 episodes in the first four series, containing conversational interviews from cast and crew and images from the episodes and behind the scenes.<ref name=\"books cancelled\"/><ref>{{cite book|last=Brooker|first=Charlie|last2=Jones|first2=Annabel|date=1 November 2018|title=Inside Black Mirror|publisher=[[Penguin Random House]]|isbn=9781529102581}}</ref> The book was released in the UK on 1 November 2018 and in the US on 20 November 2018 from [[Penguin Random House]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.cosmopolitan.com/uk/entertainment/a23279428/inside-black-mirror-book/|title=If you're obsessed with Black Mirror, you need the new Inside Black Mirror book|work=[[Cosmopolitan (magazine)|Cosmopolitan]]|last=Baxter|first=Dusty|date=17 September 2018|accessdate=1 November 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20181127064705/https://www.cosmopolitan.com/uk/entertainment/a23279428/inside-black-mirror-book/|archive-date=27 November 2018|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.penguinrandomhouse.com/books/600315/inside-black-mirror-by-charlie-brooker-and-annabel-jones-with-jason-arnopp/9781984823489/|title=Inside Black Mirror by Charlie Brooker, Annabel Jones, Jason Arnopp {{!}} PenguinRandomHouse.com|website=PenguinRandomhouse.com|language=en-US|access-date=1 November 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180820234852/https://www.penguinrandomhouse.com/books/600315/inside-black-mirror-by-charlie-brooker-and-annabel-jones-with-jason-arnopp/9781984823489/|archive-date=20 August 2018|url-status=live}}</ref> ''[[Starburst (magazine)|Starburst]]'' rated the book ten out of ten stars, praising its \"wonderfully-comprehensive format\" and summarising it as \"blunt, brittle, often killingly funny and lavishly-illustrated\".<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.starburstmagazine.com/reviews/inside-black-mirror|title=Inside Black Mirror|work=[[Starburst (magazine)|Starburst]]|accessdate=17 July 2019}}</ref>\n\nIn June 2017, Brooker announced a series of novels based on ''Black Mirror'' that will offer \"new, original, darkly satirical stories that tap into our collective unease about the modern world\". Brooker will edit three volumes of novellas that will feature anthology short stories by different authors.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.thewrap.com/black-mirror-to-be-adapted-into-a-book-series/ |title='Black Mirror' to Be Adapted Into a Book Series |date=13 June 2017 |website=TheWrap |access-date=14 June 2017 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170613200406/http://www.thewrap.com/black-mirror-to-be-adapted-into-a-book-series/ |archive-date=13 June 2017 |url-status=live }}</ref><ref name=\":0\" /> The first instalment was scheduled to include stories written by [[Cory Doctorow]], [[Claire North]] and [[Sylvain Neuvel]].<ref>{{Cite book|title=Black Mirror Volume 1 |publisher=Amazon |id= {{ASIN|1785036742|country=uk}} }}</ref> Initially scheduled for release in 2018 and 2019,<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.theguardian.com/books/booksblog/2017/jun/14/charlie-brooker-black-mirror-spin-off-books-but-who-should-write-them |title=Charlie Brooker's Black Mirror to spin off into books&nbsp;\u2013 but who should write them? |last=Barnett |first=David |date=14 June 2017 |work=The Guardian |accessdate=28 September 2017 |issn=0261-3077 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170925095225/https://www.theguardian.com/books/booksblog/2017/jun/14/charlie-brooker-black-mirror-spin-off-books-but-who-should-write-them |archive-date=25 September 2017 |url-status=live }}</ref> the project was postponed indefinitely as Brooker and Jones could not dedicate enough time to it.<ref name=\"books cancelled\">{{cite web|url=http://www.digitalspy.com/tv/black-mirror/news/a869500/black-mirror-spin-off-novels-cancelled/|title=Charlie Brooker reveals why planned Black Mirror spin-offs novels have been shelved|work=[[Digital Spy]]|last=Jeffery|first=Morgan|date=29 October 2018|accessdate=1 November 2018}}</ref>\n\n===Board game===\n{{Main|Nosedive (board game)}}\nBased on the third series episode \"[[Nosedive (Black Mirror)|Nosedive]]\", the board game ''Nosedive'' was produced by [[Asmodee]]. Released on 25 November 2018, the game requires between three and six players and is designed to last for roughly 45 minutes.<ref>{{cite web | url = https://www.polygon.com/2018/11/15/18097545/black-mirror-nosedive-board-game-asmodee | title = Black Mirror's nightmarish social media episode is now a board game | first = Michael | last = McWhertor | date = 15 November 2018 | accessdate = 1 July 2019 | work = [[Polygon (website)|Polygon]] }}</ref>\n\n== References ==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n== Further reading ==\n* {{cite journal |url=https://www.newyorker.com/magazine/2015/01/05/button-pusher |title=Button-Pusher: The seductive dystopia of 'Black Mirror' |first=Emily |last=Nussbaum |date=January 2015 |journal=[[The New Yorker]] |accessdate=}}\n\n== External links ==\n{{sisterlinks|display=''Black Mirror''|d=Q558112|c=Category:Black Mirror|n=no|b=no|v=no|voy=no|wikt=no|s=no|species=no}}\n* [http://www.channel4.com/info/press/programme-information/black-mirror ''Black Mirror''] press release from [[Channel 4]]\n* [https://www.netflix.com/title/70264888 ''Black Mirror''] at [[Netflix]]\n* {{IMDb title|2085059}}\n\n{{Black Mirror|state=expanded}}\n{{Navboxes\n| title = [[List of awards and nominations received by Black Mirror|Awards for ''Black Mirror'']]\n| list =\n{{InternationalEmmyAward TV Movie or Miniseries}}\n{{EmmyAward TelevisionMovie}}\n{{Producers Guild of America Award for Best Long-Form Television}}\n}}\n{{Charlie Brooker}}\n{{Netflix original continuation series}}\n\n[[Category:Black Mirror| ]]\n[[Category:2010s British drama television series]]\n[[Category:2010s British satirical television series]]\n[[Category:2010s British science fiction television series]]\n[[Category:2011 British television series debuts]]\n[[Category:British anthology television series]]\n[[Category:British anthology web series]]\n[[Category:British science fiction television programmes]]\n[[Category:British television miniseries]]\n[[Category:Channel 4 television dramas]]\n[[Category:Dystopian television series]]\n[[Category:Dystopian web series]]\n[[Category:English-language television programs]]\n[[Category:Hard science fiction]]\n[[Category:International Emmy Award for Best TV Movie or Miniseries]]\n[[Category:Lesbian-related television programs]]\n[[Category:Netflix original programming]]\n[[Category:Primetime Emmy Award for Outstanding Made for Television Movie winners]]\n[[Category:Psychological thriller web series]]\n[[Category:Satirical web series]]\n[[Category:Science fiction anthology television series]]\n[[Category:Science fiction anthology web series]]\n[[Category:Science fiction web series]]\n[[Category:Television series by Endemol]]\n[[Category:Television series by Zeppotron]]\n[[Category:Television series created by Charlie Brooker]]\n[[Category:Television shows set in England]]\n[[Category:Television shows set in London]]\n[[Category:2010s black comedy television series]]\n[[Category:2020s black comedy television series]]\n", "text_old": "{{other uses}}\n{{short description|British science fiction anthology television series}}\n{{Use British English|date=February 2018}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=February 2018}}\n{{Infobox television\n |show_name            = Black Mirror\n |image                = BlackMirrorTitleCard.jpg\n |caption              =\n |show_name_2          =\n |genre                = {{Plainlist|\n* [[Science fiction]]\n* [[Satire]]\n* [[Psychological thriller]]\n* [[Dystopia]]\n* [[Anthology series|Anthology]]\n* [[Dramedy]]\n* [[Horror]]\n* [[Horror comedy]]\n* [[Black comedy]]\n* [[Romance]]\n* [[Mundane science fiction]]\n* [[Speculative fiction]]\n* [[Quality television]]\n* [[Psychological drama]]\n}}\n |creator              = [[Charlie Brooker]]\n |developer            =\n |writer               = {{Plainlist|\n* Charlie Brooker\n* [[Konnie Huq]]\n* [[Jesse Armstrong]]\n* [[Rashida Jones]]\n* [[Michael Schur]]\n* William Bridges\n}}\n |starring             =\n |voices               =\n |narrated             =\n |theme_music_composer =\n |opentheme            =\n |endtheme             =\n |composer             =\n |country              = United Kingdom\n |language             = English\n |num_series           = 5\n |num_episodes         = 22\n |list_episodes        = List of Black Mirror episodes\n |producer             =\n |executive_producer   = {{Plainlist|\n* [[Annabel Jones]]\n* Charlie Brooker\n}}\n |editor               =\n |location             =\n |cinematography       =\n |camera               =\n |runtime              = 41\u201389 minutes\n |company              = {{Plainlist|\n* Zeppotron (2011\u20132013)\n* [[Endemol UK|House of Tomorrow]] (2014\u2013present)\n}}\n |distributor          = [[Endemol Shine UK]]\n |network              = {{Plainlist|\n* [[Channel 4]] (2011\u20132014)\n* [[Netflix]] (2016\u2013present)\n}}\n |picture_format       = {{Plainlist|\n* [[High-definition television|HDTV]] [[1080i]] (2011\u20132014)\n* [[Ultra-high-definition television|4K UHD]] [[2160p]] (2016\u2013present)\n}}\n |audio_format         = [[Dolby Digital]] 2.0\n |first_run            =\n |first_aired          = {{Start date|df=yes|2011|12|4}}\n |last_aired           = {{End date|df=yes|present}}\n |preceded_by          =\n |followed_by          =\n |related              =\n |website              = https://www.netflix.com/gb/title/70264888\n |production_website   =\n}}\n\n'''''Black Mirror''''' is a British<!-- the series is produced in England and was originally broadcast on Channel 4, a British TV station --> [[dystopia]]n [[science fiction]] [[comedy-drama]] [[Anthology series|anthology]] television series created by [[Charlie Brooker]]. He and [[Annabel Jones]] are the programme's [[showrunner]]s. It examines modern society, particularly with regard to the unanticipated consequences of [[Post-industrial society|new technologies]]. Episodes are standalone, usually set in an [[alternative history|alternative present]] or the near future, often with a dark and satirical tone, although some are more experimental and lighter.\n\n''Black Mirror'' was inspired by older anthology series, such as ''[[The Twilight Zone]]'', which Brooker felt were able to deal with controversial, contemporary topics with less fear of censorship than other more realistic programmes. Brooker developed ''Black Mirror'' to highlight topics related to humanity's relationship with technology, creating stories that feature \"the way we live now&nbsp;\u2013 and the way we might be living in 10 minutes' time if we're clumsy.\"<ref name=\"guardian_a\"/>\n\nThe series premiered for two series on [[Channel 4]] in December 2011 and February 2013. After its addition to the catalogue in December 2014, [[Netflix]] purchased the programme in September 2015. It commissioned a series of 12 episodes later divided into the third and fourth series, each comprising six episodes; the former was released on 21 October 2016 and the latter on 29 December 2017. A standalone [[interactive film]] titled ''[[Black Mirror: Bandersnatch]]'' was released on 28 December 2018. A fifth series, comprising three episodes, was released on 5 June 2019.<ref name=\"S5ReleaseDate\" />\n\nThe series has garnered positive reception from critics, received many [[List of awards and nominations received by Black Mirror|awards and nominations]], and seen an increase in interest internationally, particularly in the United States after its addition to Netflix. The show has won eight [[Emmy Awards]] for \"[[San Junipero]]\", \"[[USS Callister]]\" and ''Bandersnatch'', including three consecutive wins in the [[Primetime Emmy Award for Outstanding Television Movie|Outstanding Television Movie]] category.\n\n== Episodes ==\n{{Main|List of Black Mirror episodes}}\nThe series was originally commissioned by [[Channel 4]] in the United Kingdom and premiered in December 2011. A second series ran during February 2013. In September 2015, [[Netflix]] purchased the programme, commissioning a series of 12 episodes later divided into two series of six episodes.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://media.netflix.com/en/press-releases/netflix-will-bring-viewers-twelve-new-episodes-of-the-critically-acclaimed-black-mirror-migration-1 |title=Netflix will bring viewers twelve new episodes of the critically-acclaimed Black Mirror |website=[[Netflix]] |date=24 September 2015 |access-date=8 November 2016 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180621194414/https://media.netflix.com/en/press-releases/netflix-will-bring-viewers-twelve-new-episodes-of-the-critically-acclaimed-black-mirror-migration-1 |archive-date=21 June 2018 |url-status=dead }}</ref> The first of these series was released on Netflix worldwide as the overall third series on 21 October 2016. The fourth series was released on 29 December 2017.<ref name=\"Series4Release\">{{cite web |url=https://variety.com/2017/tv/news/black-mirror-season-4-release-date-trailer-1202628880/ |title=Netflix Announces 'Black Mirror' Season 4 Release Date (Watch) |last=Turchiano |first=Danielle |website=Variety |date=6 December 2017 |accessdate=6 December 2017 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20171207013407/https://variety.com/2017/tv/news/black-mirror-season-4-release-date-trailer-1202628880/ |archive-date=7 December 2017 |url-status=live }}</ref> A fifth series consisting of three episodes was released on 5 June 2019.<ref name=\"S5ReleaseDate\" />\n{{:List of Black Mirror episodes}}\n\n== Production ==\n=== Conception and style ===\nCharlie Brooker had completed production of ''[[Dead Set]]'', a zombie-based drama series, and while working on ''[[Newswipe with Charlie Brooker|Newswipe]]'' and other programmes, had decided that he wanted to make another drama series, in an [[anthology series|anthology style]] like ''[[The Twilight Zone]]'', ''[[Tales of the Unexpected (TV series)|Tales of the Unexpected]]'', and ''[[Hammer House of Horror]]''.<ref name=\"denofgeek interview\">{{cite web |url=https://www.denofgeek.com/tv/21083/charlie-brooker-interview-black-mirror-videogames-gameswipe-and-a-touch-of-cloth |title=Charlie Brooker interview: Black Mirror, videogames, Gameswipe and A Touch Of Cloth |first=Ryan |last=Lamble |date=12 February 2012 |accessdate=7 December 2017 |website=[[Den of Geek]] |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20171208005054/http://www.denofgeek.com/tv/21083/charlie-brooker-interview-black-mirror-videogames-gameswipe-and-a-touch-of-cloth |archive-date=8 December 2017 |url-status=live }}</ref><ref name=\"guardian_a\">{{cite news |title=Charlie Brooker: the dark side of our gadget addiction |url=https://www.theguardian.com/technology/2011/dec/01/charlie-brooker-dark-side-gadget-addiction-black-mirror |accessdate=17 December 2011 |newspaper=The Guardian |date=1 December 2011 |location=London |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20131005141925/http://www.theguardian.com/technology/2011/dec/01/charlie-brooker-dark-side-gadget-addiction-black-mirror |archive-date=5 October 2013 |url-status=live }}</ref>  Brooker recognised that [[Rod Serling]] had written episodes of ''The Twilight Zone'' using contemporary issues, often controversial ones such as racism, but placed them in fictional settings so as to get around television censors at the time.<ref name=\"guardian_a\" /> Brooker realised he could do similar commentary on modern issues, specifically focusing on mankind's dependency on technology, something he encountered while producing the series ''[[How TV Ruined Your Life]]''.<ref name=\"guardian_a\" /> Brooker pulled the series' title from this approach:\n{{quote|If technology is a drug&nbsp;\u2013 and it does feel like a drug&nbsp;\u2013 then what, precisely, are the side effects? This area&nbsp;\u2013 between delight and discomfort&nbsp;\u2013 is where ''Black Mirror'', my new drama series, is set. The 'black mirror' of the title is the one you'll find on every wall, on every desk, in the palm of every hand: the cold, shiny screen of a [[Television|TV]], a monitor, a [[smartphone]].<ref name=\"guardian_a\" />}}\n\nBrooker wanted to keep the anthology approach, using new stories, settings, characters, and actors for each episode, as he felt this approach was a key element of enjoying series like ''The Twilight Zone''; he said, \"There was a signature tone to the stories, the same dark chocolate coating&nbsp;\u2013 but the filling was always a surprise.\"<ref name=\"guardian_a\" /> This approach would allow ''Black Mirror'' to contrast with current dramas and serials that had a standard recurring cast.<ref name=\"guardian_a\" /> According to Brooker, the production team considered giving the series a linking theme or presenter, but ultimately decided not to: \"There were discussions. Do we set them all in the same street? Do we have some characters who appear in each episode, a bit ''[[Three Colours trilogy|Three Colours: Blue/White/Red]]'' style? We did think about having a character who introduces them, ''[[Tales from the Crypt (TV series)|Tales from the Crypt]]'' style, or like Rod Serling or [[Alfred Hitchcock]] or [[Roald Dahl]], because most anthology shows did have that... but the more we thought about it, we thought it was a bit weird.\"<ref name=\"SFX_Magazine\">{{cite news |title=Charlie Brooker Talks The Twilight Zone And Technology |url=http://www.sfx.co.uk/2013/02/01/charlie-brooker-talks-the-twilight-zone-and-technology/ |accessdate=4 February 2013 |magazine=SFX |date=1 February 2013 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20130205075847/http://www.sfx.co.uk/2013/02/01/charlie-brooker-talks-the-twilight-zone-and-technology/ |archive-date=5 February 2013 |url-status=live }}</ref>\n\nWhile the production does not use linking elements, the series has included allusions and [[Easter egg (media)|Easter eggs]] from previous episodes into later ones. For example, \"[[Hated in the Nation]]\" in the third series calls back to the events of both the first series episode \"[[The National Anthem (Black Mirror)|The National Anthem]]\" and the second series episode \"[[White Bear (Black Mirror)|White Bear]]\",<ref name=\"hwr s4\" /> while the final episode of the fourth series \"[[Black Museum (Black Mirror)|Black Museum]]\" includes references to each prior episode of the series.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://variety.com/2017/tv/news/black-mirror-season-4-black-museum-colm-mccarthy-directing-interview-1202640505/ |title='Black Mirror' Director on 'Black Museum': 'I Think There's Something Quite Spiritual About It' |first=Danielle |last=Turchiano |date=29 December 2017 |accessdate=31 December 2017 |website=[[Variety (magazine)|Variety]] |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180111102248/http://variety.com/2017/tv/news/black-mirror-season-4-black-museum-colm-mccarthy-directing-interview-1202640505/ |archive-date=11 January 2018 |url-status=live }}</ref> Some of these are for the ease of reusing a name developed in a prior episode; for example, they created the fictional \"UKN\" broadcast network for handling news reports that drive stories,<ref name=\"thrillest s3 easter eggs\" /> while the pizza delivery company used in \"[[USS Callister]]\" was used again for a company running automated pizza trucks in \"[[Crocodile (Black Mirror)|Crocodile]]\".<ref name=\"ew s4 interview\">{{cite web |url=https://ew.com/tv/2018/01/02/black-mirror-season-4-interviews/ |title=Black Mirror season 4, your burning questions answered |first=James |last=Hibbard |date=2 January 2018 |accessdate=2 January 2018 |website=[[Entertainment Weekly]] |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180102200542/http://ew.com/tv/2018/01/02/black-mirror-season-4-interviews/ |archive-date=2 January 2018 |url-status=live }}</ref> Other Easter eggs were added as they knew viewers would be intensely dissecting the episodes, and the team provided these as gags. However, over time the use of Easter eggs became more purposeful, as to establish a [[canon (fiction)|canon]] of the \"dream universe\" that the episodes take place in.<ref name=\"hwr s4\">{{cite web |url=https://www.hollywoodreporter.com/live-feed/black-mirror-season-4-episodes-charlie-brooker-annabel-jones-interview-spoilers-1033807 |title='Black Mirror' Bosses on \"San Junipero\" Sequel and an Unpredictable Season 4 |first=Jackie |last=Strause |date=7 September 2017 |accessdate=14 December 2017 |website=[[The Hollywood Reporter]] |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20171215053422/https://www.hollywoodreporter.com/live-feed/black-mirror-season-4-episodes-charlie-brooker-annabel-jones-interview-spoilers-1033807 |archive-date=15 December 2017 |url-status=live }}</ref> Brooker noted that when they opted to reuse a cover of [[Irma Thomas]]' \"[[Anyone Who Knows What Love Is (Will Understand) |Anyone Who Knows What Love Is]]\", first introduced in \"[[Fifteen Million Merits]]\", for \"[[White Christmas (Black Mirror)|White Christmas]]\", as \"it does sort of nest the whole thing together in some kind of artistic universe\".<ref name=\"thrillest s3 easter eggs\">{{cite web |url=https://www.thrillist.com/entertainment/nation/black-mirror-netflix-season-3-charlie-brooker-interview |title='Black Mirror' Creator Charlie Brooker Explains Season 3 and Reveals Easter Eggs |first=Sean |last=Fitz-Gerald |date=23 October 2016 |accessdate=11 January 2018 |website=[[Thrillist]] |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20171230223739/https://www.thrillist.com/entertainment/nation/black-mirror-netflix-season-3-charlie-brooker-interview |archive-date=30 December 2017 |url-status=live }}</ref> In describing the nature of Easter eggs in the standalone film ''[[Black Mirror: Bandersnatch]]'', Brooker alluded to dialogue said by character Colin Ritman that spoke towards alternate realities, and suggested that their use of Easter eggs to previous episodes helps to connect all these stories, but not necessarily within the same reality or timeline. However, Brooker asserted that the Easter eggs in ''Black Mirror'' are only there \"as an extra bit of texture for fans of the show\", and not meant to fully construct an atlas of ''Black Mirror'' episodes that becomes essential for understanding any episode.<ref>{{cite news| url = https://www.hollywoodreporter.com/live-feed/bandersnatch-tuckersoft-black-mirror-universe-1172028 | title = How 'Bandersnatch' Fits Into the 'Black Mirror' Universe | first = Jackie | last = Strause | date = 31 December 2018 | accessdate = 2 January 2019 | work = [[The Hollywood Reporter]] | archive-url = https://web.archive.org/web/20190102053516/https://www.hollywoodreporter.com/live-feed/bandersnatch-tuckersoft-black-mirror-universe-1172028 | archive-date = 2 January 2019 | url-status=live }}</ref>\n\nGiles Harvey comments in a profile of Brooker for ''[[The New Yorker]]'' that each episode \"establishes the background of normality against which a decisive tweak will stand out all the more starkly\". Harvey notes that the series' diverse range of genres show that it is \"manifestly the work of someone who has clocked up many hours of screen time\". He further comments that Brooker is \"scrupulous\", as \"the believability of each episode depends on maintaining the complex internal logic of its dystopic world\". Brooker is involved during the filming and editing processes, pointing out any inconsistencies that arise, and is \"determined to make the devices and screens and interfaces used in 'Black Mirror' seem authentic\". As examples of Brooker's \"meticulous attention to detail\", Harvey reports that Brooker carefully considered whether a falling wine bottle would shatter in the nested virtual realities of \"[[Playtest (Black Mirror)|Playtest]]\", and whether it would rain in the eponymous location in \"[[San Junipero]]\". An instance of realistic technology is the email system in \"[[Be Right Back]]\", which contrasts with \"histrionic computers\" found in Hollywood; an email is sent to the main character with the heading \"Martha, people in your position bought the following\", containing various books on the topic of grief-counseling.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.newyorker.com/magazine/2016/11/28/the-speculative-dread-of-black-mirror |title=The Speculative Dread of \"Black Mirror\" |last=Harvey |first=Giles |website=[[The New Yorker]] |date=28 November 2016 |accessdate=16 December 2017 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20171222050640/https://www.newyorker.com/magazine/2016/11/28/the-speculative-dread-of-black-mirror |archive-date=22 December 2017 |url-status=live }}</ref> Knowing that fans of the series have dissected some of these details by watching the episodes frame-by-frame, Brooker and his team have included humorous jabs at these fans through printed messages on various props, such as a paragraph in a news article held up by a character directed to fans of the series on [[Reddit]] in \"[[Crocodile (Black Mirror) |Crocodile]]\".<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.thewrap.com/black-mirror-charlie-brooker-reddit-fans-easter-egg-crocodile/ |title='Black Mirror' Trolls Eagle-Eyed Reddit Users With Insane Season 4 Easter Egg |first=Jennifer |last=Maas |date=1 January 2018 |accessdate=2 January 2018 |website=[[The Wrap]] |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180102033759/https://www.thewrap.com/black-mirror-charlie-brooker-reddit-fans-easter-egg-crocodile/ |archive-date=2 January 2018 |url-status=live }}</ref>\n\n=== Series 1 ===\nThe series' inception was in 2010. Charlie Brooker and Annabel Jones served as executive producers; the two had begun to work together on ''[[Charlie Brooker's Screenwipe]]'', a television review programme which aired from 2006 to 2008. The first pitch, to the head of comedy at Channel 4, was for eight half-hour episodes written by different people. Technology was a lesser focus, and the worlds were larger and more detailed, which Jones said was not possible to execute properly in the short runtime. The series was then commissioned for three hour-long episodes. The first script was \"[[Fifteen Million Merits]]\", which was written by Brooker and his wife [[Konnie Huq]]. The second script was \"Inbound\", which episode was never produced; it was about war and contained concepts which were later repurposed for the series 3 episode \"[[Men Against Fire]]\". The following script pitched became \"[[The National Anthem (Black Mirror)|The National Anthem]]\", the first episode to air. The third episode is \"[[The Entire History of You]]\".<ref name=\"ibm\">{{cite book | title=  Inside Black Mirror | date = November 2018 | first1 = Charlie | last1 = Brooker | first2 = Annabel | last2 = Jones | first3 = Jason | last3 = Arnopp | isbn = 9781984823489 | publisher =  [[Crown Publishing Group]] | place = New York City }}</ref>{{rp|6\u201313}}\n\nThe programme was produced by Brooker's production company Zeppotron, for [[Endemol]]. Joel Collins served as production designer, with his company Painting Practice working on visual effects.<ref name=\"ibm\"/>{{rp|18}} An Endemol press release described the series as \"a hybrid of ''The Twilight Zone'' and ''Tales of the Unexpected'' which taps into our contemporary unease about our modern world\", with the stories having a \"techno-paranoia\" feel.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.endemoluk.com/news/black-mirror-a-new-drama-from-charlie-brooker |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110515185448/http://www.endemoluk.com/news/black-mirror-a-new-drama-from-charlie-brooker |url-status=dead |archive-date=15 May 2011 |title=Black Mirror&nbsp;\u2013 A new drama from Charlie Brooker |website=Endemol UK |date=11 May 2011 |accessdate=15 November 2011}}</ref> [[Channel 4]] described the first episode, \"The National Anthem\", as \"a twisted parable for the [[Twitter]] age\".<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.channel4.com/info/press/programme-information/black-mirror/allpi |title=Black Mirror |website=Channel 4 |date=7 November 2011 |accessdate=6 December 2011 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20111127030814/http://www.channel4.com/info/press/programme-information/black-mirror/allpi |archive-date=27 November 2011 |url-status=live }}</ref> ''Black Mirror'' series 1 had a limited DVD release for PAL / Region 2 on 27 February 2012.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.tuppencemagazine.co.uk/black-mirror-dvd.html |title=Black Mirror DVD |magazine=Tuppence Magazine |date=7 November 2011 |accessdate=18 December 2011 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120229014619/http://www.tuppencemagazine.co.uk/black-mirror-dvd.html |archivedate=29 February 2012 |df=dmy-all }}</ref>\n\nIn 2013, [[Robert Downey Jr.]] [[Option (filmmaking)|optioned]] the episode \"[[The Entire History of You]]\" (written by [[Jesse Armstrong]]) to potentially be made into a film by [[Warner Bros.]] and his own production company, [[Team Downey]].<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.theguardian.com/film/2013/feb/12/robert-downey-jr-black-mirror |title=Robert Downey Jr to turn episode of Charlie Brooker's Black Mirror into film |date=12 February 2013 |newspaper=[[The Guardian]] |first=Ben |last=Child |location=London |access-date=11 December 2016 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20151103220854/http://www.theguardian.com/film/2013/feb/12/robert-downey-jr-black-mirror |archive-date=3 November 2015 |url-status=live }}</ref> The series was available in the U.S. from November 2013 via [[DirecTV]], where episodes aired on [[Audience (TV network)|Audience]] and were also available online to subscribers.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://grantland.com/hollywood-prospectus/black-mirror-episode-1-the-national-anthem-pig-bang-theory/|title=Black Mirror Episode 1, 'The National Anthem': Pig Bang Theory|work=[[Grantland]]|last=Yoshida|first=Emily|date=14 November 2013|accessdate=20 March 2020}}</ref> It was made available in the U.S. on Netflix from late 2014 onwards.<ref name=\"Netflix vs 4\" />\n\nIn the early stages of ''Black Mirror'', Jones was keen to avoid casting comedy actors, as Brooker was previously a comedy writer, and they wanted the series to not feel like comedy.<ref name=\"ibm\"/>{{rp|16}} \"The National Anthem\" stars [[Rory Kinnear]] as Prime Minister Michael Callow, with [[Lindsay Duncan]] playing Home Secretary Alex Cairns. \"Fifteen Million Merits\" features [[Daniel Kaluuya]] as Bing, [[Jessica Brown Findlay]] as Abi and [[Rupert Everett]], [[Julia Davis]], [[Bashy|Ashley Thomas]] as Judges Hope, Charity, and Wraith. In \"The Entire History of You\", [[Toby Kebbell]] and [[Jodie Whittaker]] star as married couple Liam and Ffion.\n\nThe first series was popular and critically well received, although viewing figures decreased throughout the series. The series was expensive for Channel 4, as the anthology format meant there were no [[economies of scale]], but it was commissioned for a second series.<ref name=\"ibm\"/>{{rp|59}}\n\n=== Series 2 ===\nSeries 2 consists of three episodes. Brooker described it as \"more epic in scale, but more intimate in scope\". The episodes are more \"understated\" in their technologies. Brooker commented that the second series mirrors the first: the first series has topics of (in order) \"warped political satire\", \"dystopian hellscape\", and \"relationship torn apart by technology\", while the second series presents episodes of these forms in reverse.<ref name=\"ibm\"/>{{rp|60}} Each episode in the first series had a male protagonist, so Brooker deliberately wrote female protagonists for series 2 episodes \"[[Be Right Back]]\" and \"[[White Bear (Black Mirror)|White Bear]]\".<ref name=\"ibm\"/>{{rp|64}}\n\nA trailer for the second series was made by [[Moving Picture Company]] and featured three interspersed storylines: \"a dream sequence, the repetitive factory setting and the huge dust cloud that sweeps through the street at the ad's climactic end.\" Aired from 22 January 2013, the advertisement was shown on Channel 4 and in cinemas.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.digitalartsonline.co.uk/news/motion-graphics/mpc-creates-darkly-compelling-ads-for-charlie-brookers-black-mirror/ |title=MPC creates darkly compelling ads for Charlie Brooker's Black Mirror |website=Digital Arts |date=29 January 2013 |accessdate=16 December 2017 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20171222050737/https://www.digitalartsonline.co.uk/news/motion-graphics/mpc-creates-darkly-compelling-ads-for-charlie-brookers-black-mirror/ |archive-date=22 December 2017 |url-status=live }}</ref>\n\n\"Be Right Back\" stars [[Hayley Atwell]] as Martha and [[Domhnall Gleeson]] as Ash, both in human and robot form. In \"White Bear\", [[Lenora Crichlow]] plays Victoria Skillane and [[Michael Smiley]] and [[Tuppence Middleton]] play Baxter and Jem. \"[[The Waldo Moment]]\" features [[Daniel Rigby]] as Jamie Salter, [[Chloe Pirrie]] as Gwendolyn Harris and [[Jason Flemyng]] as Jack Napier.\n\n=== \"White Christmas\" ===\nAccording to Brooker, the series was still taking its budget from the comedy department of Channel 4, and there was discussion of whether it should fall under the drama department instead. Shane Allen, head of comedy for Channel 4 at the time, stated in 2018 that someone had been taken aback by the budget for ''Black Mirror'', which was well above the standard for a comedy, and became involved in the editorial process. A new head of comedy had been hired, who did not have a relationship with Brooker and Jones.<ref name=\"ibm\"/>{{rp|101\u2013103}}\n\nBrooker reported in 2018 that Channel 4 agreed on a third series of four episodes, but requested detailed synopses of the episodes in advance. Brooker came up with an episode \"Angel of the Morning\", which would later become a story in \"[[White Christmas (Black Mirror)|White Christmas]]\". He also conceived of an episode based on the earlier script \"Inbound\" which would have been similar to a later series 3 episode, \"Men Against Fire\". Another episode was named \"Crocodile\", which overlapped in parts with the series 4 episode of the same name. After a lengthy wait, Brooker and Jones were told that the ideas \"weren't very ''Black Mirror''\". Though Channel 4 may have suggested doing a one-off special, Jones said that \"we felt there wasn't any clarity from the channel\".<ref name=\"ibm\"/>{{rp|101\u2013103}}\n\nJones and Brooker worked on other projects for the next year, such as the comedy procedural ''[[A Touch of Cloth]]''. After bumping into a Channel 4 staff member, Brooker emailed the channel to ask about how to continue with ''Black Mirror''. Channel 4 had the budget for an hour-long Christmas special, but Jones and Brooker pushed for a 90-minute episode.<ref name=\"ibm\"/>{{rp|101\u2013103}}\n\n\"White Christmas\" was a portmanteau of three stories, inspired by works such as the 1983 science fiction film ''[[Twilight Zone: The Movie]]''.<ref name=\"ibm\"/>{{rp|101\u2013103}} It starred [[Jon Hamm]] as Matt and [[Rafe Spall]] as Joe throughout. Actors in the individual stories include: [[Rasmus Hardiker]] as Harry, [[Natalia Tena]] as Jennifer, [[Oona Chaplin]] as Greta, [[Janet Montgomery]] as Beth, and Ken Drury as Beth's father. The episode aired on 16 December 2014.\n\n=== Move to Netflix ===\nOn the day of the press screening for \"White Christmas\", Brooker and Jones had a meeting with Channel 4 executives, who told them that they wanted to continue the series but due to budget constraints, it would need to be a co-production. The pair had travelled to Los Angeles a few months prior to try to get co-production money but were unsuccessful. The channel also suggested that Brooker could write an episode of ''[[Electric Dreams (2017 TV series)|Electric Dreams]]'', a 2017 adaptation of short stories by [[Philip K. Dick]].<ref name=\"ibm\"/>{{rp|123\u2013124}}\n\nIn December 2014, the first two series of the programme were released on [[Netflix]] in the United States after they bought exclusive streaming rights, leading to increased attention for the programme.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://variety.com/2014/tv/news/netflix-run-brings-u-k-s-black-mirror-into-light-for-u-s-auds-1201380236/|title=Netflix Run Brings U.K.'s 'Black Mirror' Into Light for U.S. Auds|work=[[Variety (magazine)|Variety]]|last=Spangler|first=Todd|date=18 December 2014|accessdate=26 December 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20181227040808/https://variety.com/2014/tv/news/netflix-run-brings-u-k-s-black-mirror-into-light-for-u-s-auds-1201380236/|archive-date=27 December 2018|url-status=live}}</ref> In a bidding war between channels, which included several American networks, Netflix led with a commitment of two series of ten episodes each. Brooker and Jones reported in 2018 that although they and Netflix were both keen to have Channel 4 as equal partners, they could not get a meeting with Channel 4. They eventually got a meeting without discussion of a co-production with Netflix, where the channel suggested a renewal for three episodes. The channel later offered six episodes if full treatments could be given in advance, but Brooker and Jones were concerned due to past rejection of ideas. They had a limited time to reply to U.S. offers and chose to make a deal with Netflix.<ref name=\"ibm\"/>{{rp|125\u2013126}}\n\nIn September 2015, Netflix officially commissioned 12 episodes of ''Black Mirror''.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://variety.com/2015/digital/news/netflix-black-mirror-new-episodes-1201602037/ |title='Black Mirror' Lands at Netflix |first=Debra |last=Birnbaum |work=[[Variety (magazine)|Variety]] |date=25 September 2015 |accessdate=26 December 2018 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180612162641/https://variety.com/2015/digital/news/netflix-black-mirror-new-episodes-1201602037/ |archive-date=12 June 2018 |url-status=live }}</ref> In March 2016, it outbid Channel 4 for the rights to distributing the third series in the UK, with a bid of {{US$|40&nbsp;million}}.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.theguardian.com/media/2016/mar/29/netflix-channel-4-charlie-brooker-black-mirror |title=Netflix deals Channel 4 knockout blow over Charlie Brooker's Black Mirror |first=John |last=Plunkett |date=29 March 2016 |newspaper=The Guardian |access-date=11 December 2016 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20171230021155/https://www.theguardian.com/media/2016/mar/29/netflix-channel-4-charlie-brooker-black-mirror |archive-date=30 December 2017 |url-status=live }}</ref> Endemol released a statement saying that Channel 4 had \"had the opportunity to recommission [''Black Mirror''] since 2013 and passed on this and subsequent co-production offers put to them. [...] Further efforts were made to try to reach a settlement regarding a U.K. window for Channel 4, but these were also sadly to no avail\". In a press release, Channel 4 say that they \"offered to recommission ''Black Mirror''\". This marked the first time that an online streaming service had gained the rights to a series when the original network had wished to renew it.<ref name=\"Netflix vs 4\">{{cite web |url=https://www.hollywoodreporter.com/news/miptv-why-black-mirror-deal-881421 |title=MIPTV: Why the 'Black Mirror' Deal Marks a Turning Point for Netflix |website=[[The Hollywood Reporter]] |last=Ritman |first=Alex |last2=Roxborough |first2=Scott |date=7 April 2016 |accessdate=12 December 2017 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20171213013130/https://www.hollywoodreporter.com/news/miptv-why-black-mirror-deal-881421 |archive-date=13 December 2017 |url-status=live }}</ref>\n\n=== Series 3 ===\nIn developing the third series' stories, Brooker had looked back to the first two series and the Christmas special and recognised that all the stories were about characters becoming trapped in a situation that they could not escape from. Coupled with the anthology format that asked for viewers to get immersed within the stories to understand the nature of each, this created a sense of darkness and horror, which could make it difficult to watch successive episodes without becoming uncomfortable. With the third series, Brooker wanted to explore different formats, still having a few \"trap\" episodes but adding more conventional stories like a romance and police procedural, making the new series more digestible for the viewer.<ref>{{cite journal |url=https://www.wired.com/2016/10/black-mirror-traps/ |title=What Happens When Black Mirror Moves Beyond Traps? It Gets Even Better |first=Joesph |last=Bien-Kahn |date=21 October 2016 |accessdate=15 December 2017 |journal=[[Wired (magazine)|Wired]] |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20171216034602/https://www.wired.com/2016/10/black-mirror-traps/ |archive-date=16 December 2017 |url-status=live }}</ref> Producer Lucy Dyke commented that Netflix had an expectation that the series would become \"bigger and better\" and \"more international\", while production designer Joel Collins said that Netflix was happy to support ideas on the same scale or on a larger scale than previous episodes. The first episode that Brooker wrote for the series was \"[[San Junipero]]\", and it was an intentional departure from previous episodes as well as a \"deliberate raspberry-blow\" at fans who were concerned at the series' Americanisation.<ref name=\"ibm\"/>{{rp|126\u2013127}}\n\nThe titles of the six episodes that make up series 3 were announced in July 2016, along with the release date.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://nerdist.com/black-mirrors-new-episodes-will-hit-us-in-october/ |title=Black Mirror's New Episodes Will Hit Us In October |website=Nerdist|publisher=[[Nerdist Industries]] |last=Lutes |first=Alicia |date=27 July 2016 |accessdate=12 December 2017 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20171213010958/https://nerdist.com/black-mirrors-new-episodes-will-hit-us-in-october/ |archive-date=13 December 2017 |url-status=dead }}</ref> A trailer for the third series was released in October 2016.<ref name=trailer>{{cite web|title='Black Mirror' Season 3 Trailer: 'No One Is This Happy' |url=https://deadline.com/2016/10/black-mirror-season-3-trailer-netflix-bryce-dallas-howard-alice-eve-james-norton-1201832611/ |accessdate=7 October 2016 |website=Deadline |date=7 October 2016 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20161008153241/http://deadline.com/2016/10/black-mirror-season-3-trailer-netflix-bryce-dallas-howard-alice-eve-james-norton-1201832611/ |archive-date=8 October 2016 |url-status=live }}</ref> It was released on Netflix worldwide on 21 October 2016.<ref>{{cite journal |url=https://variety.com/2016/tv/news/black-mirror-netflix-premiere-date-gilmore-girls-the-ranch-1201824702/ |title=Netflix Original Series Premiere Dates: 'Black Mirror,' 'Gilmore Girls' and More to Drop in 2016 |first=Oriana |last=Schwindt |date=27 July 2016 |journal=Variety |access-date=11 December 2017 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20171213010751/https://variety.com/2016/tv/news/black-mirror-netflix-premiere-date-gilmore-girls-the-ranch-1201824702/ |archive-date=13 December 2017 |url-status=live }}</ref>\n\n\"[[Nosedive (Black Mirror)|Nosedive]]\" is an episode about social media written by [[Michael Schur]] and [[Rashida Jones]], and starring [[Bryce Dallas Howard]] as Lacie. \"[[Playtest (Black Mirror)|Playtest]]\" is a horror story starring [[Wyatt Russell]] as Cooper. \"[[Shut Up and Dance (Black Mirror)|Shut Up and Dance]]\" is about a blackmailed teenager, starring [[Alex Lawther]] as Kenny and [[Jerome Flynn]] as Hector, and written by Brooker and William Bridges. \"San Junipero\" is a science fiction love story starring [[Gugu Mbatha-Raw]] as Kelly and [[Mackenzie Davis]] as Yorkie. \"Men Against Fire\" is an episode about war, starring [[Malachi Kirby]] as Stripe. \"[[Hated in the Nation]]\" is a police procedural with [[Kelly Macdonald]] as Karin Parke and [[Faye Marsay]] as Blue Coulson.\n\n=== Series 4 ===\nAccording to Brooker, the fourth series has even more variety in the episodes than in previous series.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/on-demand/0/black-mirror-season-4-netflix-plus-charlie-brooker-hints-jodie/ |title=Black Mirror season 4: when is it on Netflix? Plus, Charlie Brooker hints about Jodie Foster's episode |newspaper=The Telegraph |date=20 February 2017 |access-date=3 April 2018 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180503102350/https://www.telegraph.co.uk/on-demand/0/black-mirror-season-4-netflix-plus-charlie-brooker-hints-jodie/ |archive-date=3 May 2018 |url-status=live }}</ref> Brooker says that there is \"some more hope\" in the series, crediting this to the fact that writing began in July 2016 and continued throughout the [[2016 United States presidential election]], and \"I genuinely thought, I don't know what state the world's going to be in by the time these [episodes] appear, and I don't know how much appetite there will be for nothing but bleak nihilism.\"<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.digitalspy.com/tv/black-mirror/news/a845347/black-mirror-season-4-charlie-brooker/ |title=Charlie Brooker: Black Mirror is more hopeful now because the world is more depressing |website=[[Digital Spy]] |last=Jeffery |first=Morgan |date=13 December 2017 |access-date=14 December 2017 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20171215055418/http://www.digitalspy.com/tv/black-mirror/news/a845347/black-mirror-season-4-charlie-brooker/ |archive-date=15 December 2017 |url-status=live }}</ref>\n\nIn May 2017, a [[Reddit]] post unofficially announced the names and directors of the six episodes in series 4 of ''Black Mirror''.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.independent.co.uk/arts-entertainment/tv/news/black-mirror-season-4-episode-titles-directors-charlie-brooker-netflix-jodie-foster-john-hillcoat-a7758786.html |title=Black Mirror season 4 episode titles and directors revealed |website=[[The Independent]] |last=Stolworthy |first=Jacob |date=27 May 2017 |accessdate=10 December 2017 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20171207154218/http://www.independent.co.uk/arts-entertainment/tv/news/black-mirror-season-4-episode-titles-directors-charlie-brooker-netflix-jodie-foster-john-hillcoat-a7758786.html |archive-date=7 December 2017 |url-status=live }}</ref> Filming for the fourth series concluded in June 2017.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.bleedingcool.com/2017/12/06/black-mirror-season-4-finally-gets-a-release-date/ |title=Black Mirror Season 4: Finally Gets a Release Date... in 2017 |last=Wickline |first=Dan |website=[[Bleeding Cool]] |date=6 December 2017 |accessdate=12 December 2017 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20171213012445/https://www.bleedingcool.com/2017/12/06/black-mirror-season-4-finally-gets-a-release-date/ |archive-date=13 December 2017 |url-status=live }}</ref> The first trailer for the series was released by Netflix on 25 August 2017, and contained the six episode titles.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.thewrap.com/black-mirror-season-4-teaser-trailer-episode-titles-directors-stars-drop-video/ |title='Black Mirror' Season 4: Teaser Trailer, Episode Titles, Directors and Stars Revealed (Video) |last=Donnelly |first=Matt |website=[[TheWrap]] |date=25 August 2017 |accessdate=10 December 2017 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20171210071818/https://www.thewrap.com/black-mirror-season-4-teaser-trailer-episode-titles-directors-stars-drop-video/ |archive-date=10 December 2017 |url-status=live }}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.independent.co.uk/arts-entertainment/tv/news/black-mirror-season-4-netflix-teaser-trailer-youtube-episode-titles-a7912416.html |title=Black Mirror season 4 Netflix trailer teases all six episodes and their titles |website=[[The Independent]] |last=Hooton |first=Christopher |date=25 August 2017 |accessdate=10 December 2017 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20171210074738/http://www.independent.co.uk/arts-entertainment/tv/news/black-mirror-season-4-netflix-teaser-trailer-youtube-episode-titles-a7912416.html |archive-date=10 December 2017 |url-status=live }}</ref> In September 2017, two photos from the fourth series were released.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.thewrap.com/black-mirror-season-4-photos/ |title=New 'Black Mirror' Season 4 Images Tease 'USS Callister's' Retro Goodness (Photos) |website=[[TheWrap]] |last=Velocci |first=Carli |date=7 September 2017 |accessdate=10 December 2017 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20171210123549/https://www.thewrap.com/black-mirror-season-4-photos/ |archive-date=10 December 2017 |url-status=live }}</ref> Beginning on 24 November 2017, Netflix published a series of posters and trailers for each episode in the fourth series of the program, referred to as the \"13 Days of ''Black Mirror''\",<ref name=\"THR cast\">{{cite web |url=https://www.hollywoodreporter.com/live-feed/black-mirror-season-4-guide-premiere-date-trailer-cast-episode-titles-1061669 |title='Black Mirror': All the Season 4 Details |website=[[The Hollywood Reporter]] |last=Strause |first=Jackie |date=27 November 2017 |accessdate=10 December 2017 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20171210072203/https://www.hollywoodreporter.com/live-feed/black-mirror-season-4-guide-premiere-date-trailer-cast-episode-titles-1061669 |archive-date=10 December 2017 |url-status=live }}</ref> concluding on 6 December 2017 with the announcement of the release date.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://decider.com/2017/12/06/black-mirror-season-4-trailer/ |title=Netflix Reveals 'Black Mirror' Season 4 Release Date In New Trailer |website=Decider.com |publisher=[[New York Post]] |last=White |first=Peter |date=6 December 2017 |accessdate=10 December 2017 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20171210072211/https://decider.com/2017/12/06/black-mirror-season-4-trailer/ |archive-date=10 December 2017 |url-status=live }}</ref> All six episodes were released to Netflix on 29 December 2017.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.theguardian.com/tv-and-radio/2017/dec/29/black-mirror-review-netflix-series-back-darker-charlie-brooker |title=Black Mirror review: the Netflix series is back&nbsp;\u2013 and darker than ever |first=Rebecca |last=Nicholson |date=29 December 2017 |accessdate=29 December 2017 |website=[[The Guardian]] |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20171229125055/https://www.theguardian.com/tv-and-radio/2017/dec/29/black-mirror-review-netflix-series-back-darker-charlie-brooker |archive-date=29 December 2017 |url-status=live }}</ref>\n\n\"[[USS Callister]]\" is a space epic starring [[Jesse Plemons]] as Robert Daly and [[Cristin Milioti]] as Nanette Cole. \"[[Arkangel (Black Mirror)|Arkangel]]\" is an episode about motherhood starring [[Rosemarie DeWitt]] as Marie and [[Brenna Harding]] as Sara. \"[[Crocodile (Black Mirror)|Crocodile]]\" is about the consequences of a [[hit-and-run]], starring [[Andrea Riseborough]] as Mia. \"[[Hang the DJ]]\" is a love story between Amy, played by [[Georgina Campbell]], and Frank, played by [[Joe Cole (actor)|Joe Cole]]. \"[[Metalhead (Black Mirror)|Metalhead]]\" is a black-and-white apocalypse episode starring [[Maxine Peake]] as Bella and directed by [[David Slade]]. \"[[Black Museum (Black Mirror)|Black Museum]]\" is an anthology of three stories, one of which was written by magician [[Penn Jillette]], starring [[Douglas Hodge]] as Rolo Haynes and [[Letitia Wright]] as Nish.\n\nThe first episode made for series 4 was \"Arkangel\", which was directed by [[Jodie Foster]] and filmed in Canada. The Netflix budget allowed them to set and film \"Crocodile\" in Iceland and make the special effects-intensive episode \"Metalhead\".<ref name=\"ibm\"/>{{rp|221}}\n\nAccording to ''[[Engadget]]'' and ''[[Gizmodo]]'', as a means of [[viral marketing]] Netflix sent private messages to users of the Turkish website [[Ek\u015fi S\u00f6zl\u00fck]]. The messages were sent from the account \"iamwaldo\" and read, \"We know what you're up to. Watch and see what we will do.\" Although the advertising was met with positive reception from some users, others were critical of distress that the messages may have caused.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.engadget.com/2017/12/29/maybe-private-black-mirror-messages-werent-a-good-idea-netfl/|title=Maybe private 'Black Mirror' messages weren't a good idea, Netflix|website=[[Engadget]]|last=Fingas|first=Jon|date=29 December 2017|accessdate=8 September 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180909000208/https://www.engadget.com/2017/12/29/maybe-private-black-mirror-messages-werent-a-good-idea-netfl/|archive-date=9 September 2018|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://gizmodo.com/netflix-freaks-out-users-with-creepy-black-mirror-marke-1821649915|title=Netflix Freaks Out Users with Creepy ''Black Mirror'' Marketing Stunt|website=[[Gizmodo]]|last=Jones|first=Rhett|date=29 December 2017|accessdate=8 September 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180909000444/https://gizmodo.com/netflix-freaks-out-users-with-creepy-black-mirror-marke-1821649915|archive-date=9 September 2018|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://metro.co.uk/2017/12/31/black-mirrors-strange-advert-in-the-middle-of-the-night-freaked-a-lot-of-turkish-netflix-viewers-out-it-is-not-cool-7193885/|title=Black Mirror's 'strange advert in the middle of the night' freaked a lot of Netflix viewers out: 'It is not cool'|website=[[Metro (British newspaper)|Metro]]|last=Gamp|first=Joe|date=31 December 2017|accessdate=8 September 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180909000428/https://metro.co.uk/2017/12/31/black-mirrors-strange-advert-in-the-middle-of-the-night-freaked-a-lot-of-turkish-netflix-viewers-out-it-is-not-cool-7193885/|archive-date=9 September 2018|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\n=== ''Bandersnatch'' ===\n{{main|Black Mirror: Bandersnatch}}\n\nThe first ''Black Mirror'' full-length film ''[[Black Mirror: Bandersnatch|Bandersnatch]]'' was released on Netflix on 28 December 2018, after being formally announced the day prior. Set in 1984, the film follows Stefan, portrayed by [[Fionn Whitehead]], a young programmer who begins to question reality as he adapts a sprawling fantasy novel into a video game and soon faces a mind-mangling challenge.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://deadline.com/2018/12/black-mirror-bandersnatch-trailer-netflix-film-release-date-1202526400/|title='Black Mirror: Bandersnatch' Trailer: Netflix Teases Event Film, Confirms Date|work=[[Deadline Hollywood]]|last=Tartaglione|first=Nancy|date=27 December 2018|accessdate=27 December 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20181227134141/https://deadline.com/2018/12/black-mirror-bandersnatch-trailer-netflix-film-release-date-1202526400/|archive-date=27 December 2018|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://tvline.com/2018/12/27/black-mirror-bandersnatch-movie-trailer-premiere-date-netflix-video/|title=Black Mirror: Bandersnatch Movie to Be Released on Friday \u2014 Watch Trailer|website=[[TVLine]]|last=Schwartz|first=Ryan|date=27 December 2018|accessdate=27 December 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20181227135951/https://tvline.com/2018/12/27/black-mirror-bandersnatch-movie-trailer-premiere-date-netflix-video/|archive-date=27 December 2018|url-status=live}}</ref> ''Bandersnatch'' is an [[interactive movie|interactive film]], prompting the viewer at times to select one of two choices on screen that affect how the work is shown; there are over one trillion potential paths to view the work and five distinct endings. The film also features [[Will Poulter]], [[Craig Parkinson]], [[Alice Lowe]], and [[Asim Chaudhry]].<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.hollywoodreporter.com/live-feed/black-mirror-film-bandersnatch-trailer-release-date-1165830|title=Netflix Drops Trailer, Date for 'Black Mirror' Stand-Alone Film|work=[[The Hollywood Reporter]]|last=Strause|first=Jackie|date=27 December 2018|accessdate=27 December 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20181227151926/https://www.hollywoodreporter.com/live-feed/black-mirror-film-bandersnatch-trailer-release-date-1165830|archive-date=27 December 2018|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\n=== Series 5 ===\nIn December 2017, when Brooker and executive producer Annabel Jones were asked about possibly creating a fifth series of ''Black Mirror'', they said, \"We would love to do it.\"<ref>{{cite web |url=http://metro.co.uk/2017/12/29/black-mirrors-charlie-brooker-teases-possibility-season-5-love-7191498/?ito=cbshare |title=Black Mirror's Charlie Brooker teases possibility of season 5: 'We would love to do it' |last=Starkey |first=Adam |date=29 December 2017 |website=Metro News |access-date= |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180109235546/http://metro.co.uk/2017/12/29/black-mirrors-charlie-brooker-teases-possibility-season-5-love-7191498/?ito=cbshare |archive-date=9 January 2018 |url-status=live }}</ref> Netflix announced the fifth series via social media on 5 March 2018, although they did not announce its release date or episode count.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://deadline.com/2018/03/black-mirror-renewed-for-season-5-by-netflix-1202308826/ |title='Black Mirror' Renewed For Season 5 By Netflix |last1=Andreeva |first1=Nellie |last2=Petski |first2=Denise |date=5 March 2018 |website=Deadline |access-date=5 March 2018 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180305190649/http://deadline.com/2018/03/black-mirror-renewed-for-season-5-by-netflix-1202308826/ |archive-date=5 March 2018 |url-status=live }}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=https://ew.com/tv/2018/03/05/black-mirror-season-5/ |title=''Black Mirror'' renewed for season 5 by Netflix |website=[[Entertainment Weekly]] |last=Hibberd |first=James |date=5 March 2018 |accessdate=5 March 2018 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180305224752/http://ew.com/tv/2018/03/05/black-mirror-season-5/ |archive-date=5 March 2018 |url-status=live }}</ref> On 20 March 2018, at the 2018 [[Royal Television Society]] Awards, Brooker confirmed that the fifth series had begun filming.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://screenrant.com/black-mirror-season-5-filming/ |title=Black Mirror Season 5 Has Already Begun Filming |last=Chapman |first=Tom |date=22 March 2018 |website=ScreenRant |access-date= |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180407182729/https://screenrant.com/black-mirror-season-5-filming/ |archive-date=7 April 2018 |url-status=live }}</ref> The complexity of ''Bandersnatch'', which Brooker had originally envisioned to be part of series 5, delayed remaining production of the fifth season, although Netflix still committed to release in 2019.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2018/12/28/arts/television/black-mirror-netflix-interactive.html |title='Black Mirror' Gives Power to the People |first=David |last=Streitfield |date=28 December 2018 |accessdate=28 December 2018 |work=[[The New York Times]] |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20181228101808/https://www.nytimes.com/2018/12/28/arts/television/black-mirror-netflix-interactive.html |archive-date=28 December 2018 |url-status=live }}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=https://arstechnica.com/gaming/2018/12/not-bander-snatched-black-mirror-confirms-fifth-season-plans/ |title=Not Bander-snatched: Black Mirror confirms fifth season plans |first=Sam |last=Makekovech |date=28 December 2018 |accessdate=28 December 2018 |website=[[Ars Technica]] |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20181228200230/https://arstechnica.com/gaming/2018/12/not-bander-snatched-black-mirror-confirms-fifth-season-plans/ |archive-date=28 December 2018 |url-status=live }}</ref><ref name=\"thr endings\">{{cite news|url=https://www.hollywoodreporter.com/live-feed/black-mirror-bandersnatch-charlie-brooker-talks-interactive-movie-1171496 |title='Black Mirror's' Interactive Film: How to Navigate 'Bandersnatch' |first=Jackie |last=Strause |date=29 December 2018 |accessdate=29 December 2018 |work=[[The Hollywood Reporter]] |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20181229192502/https://www.hollywoodreporter.com/live-feed/black-mirror-bandersnatch-charlie-brooker-talks-interactive-movie-1171496 |archive-date=29 December 2018 |url-status=live }}</ref><ref name=\"thr may2019\">{{cite news| url = https://www.hollywoodreporter.com/live-feed/black-mirror-team-complexity-bandersnatch-netflix-data-1213270 | title = 'Black Mirror' Duo on the Challenges of Netflix's First Interactive Movie \u2014 and Why They Would Do It Again | first = Jackie | last = Strause | date = 24 May 2019 | accessdate = 24 May 2019 | work = [[The Hollywood Reporter]] | archive-url = https://web.archive.org/web/20190524182742/https://www.hollywoodreporter.com/live-feed/black-mirror-team-complexity-bandersnatch-netflix-data-1213270 | archive-date = 24 May 2019 | url-status=live }}</ref> On 15 May 2019, a trailer for the fifth series was released, indicating it would comprise 3 episodes.<ref name=\"S5ReleaseDate\">{{cite news|url=https://www.hollywoodreporter.com/live-feed/black-mirror-season-5-cast-premiere-date-trailer-1210653 |title='Black Mirror' Reveals Cast, Premiere Date for Season 5 |first=Jackie |last=Strause |date=15 May 2019 |accessdate=15 May 2019 |work=[[The Hollywood Reporter]] |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190515125227/https://www.hollywoodreporter.com/live-feed/black-mirror-season-5-cast-premiere-date-trailer-1210653 |archive-date=15 May 2019 |url-status=live }}</ref> On 5 June 2019, all three series 5 episodes were released.\n\nThe fifth series cast includes [[Anthony Mackie]], [[Miley Cyrus]], [[Yahya Abdul-Mateen II]], [[Topher Grace]], [[Damson Idris]], [[Andrew Scott (actor)|Andrew Scott]], [[Nicole Beharie]], [[Pom Klementieff]], [[Angourie Rice]], [[Madison Davenport]], and [[Ludi Lin]].<ref name=\"S5Cast\">{{cite news|url=https://variety.com/2019/music/news/black-mirror-season-5-premiere-date-trailer-netflix-1203214490/ |title='Black Mirror' Drops Season 5 Trailer Starring Miley Cyrus; Release Date Announced |first=Danielle |last=Turchiano |date=15 May 2019 |accessdate=15 May 2019 |work=[[Variety (magazine)|Variety]] |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190515120800/https://variety.com/2019/music/news/black-mirror-season-5-premiere-date-trailer-netflix-1203214490/ |archive-date=15 May 2019 |url-status=live }}</ref>\n\n=== Future of the series ===\nIn October 2016, Brooker said that he had ideas of where sequels to both \"[[White Bear (Black Mirror)|White Bear]]\" and \"[[Be Right Back]]\" would go, but it was unlikely that either would be made.<ref name=recurring>{{cite news |url=https://www.independent.co.uk/arts-entertainment/tv/features/black-mirror-season-3-charlie-brooker-interview-release-date-joe-wright-nosedive-shut-up-and-dance-a7372841.html |title=Black Mirror's Charlie Brooker interview: 'I'm loathe to say this is the worst year ever because the next is coming' |date=21 October 2016 |newspaper=The Independent |accessdate=21 October 2016 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20161022025945/http://www.independent.co.uk/arts-entertainment/tv/features/black-mirror-season-3-charlie-brooker-interview-release-date-joe-wright-nosedive-shut-up-and-dance-a7372841.html |archive-date=22 October 2016 |url-status=live }}</ref> Brooker also stated that there were some characters in the series 3 episode \"[[Hated in the Nation]]\" who could potentially recur.<ref name=recurring /> Previously, actors have appeared in multiple ''Black Mirror'' episodes but for unrelated roles, such as [[Hannah John-Kamen]] (\"[[Fifteen Million Merits]]\" and \"[[Playtest (Black Mirror)|Playtest]]\"),<ref name=recurring /> [[Michaela Coel]] (\"[[Nosedive (Black Mirror)|Nosedive]]\" and \"[[USS Callister]]\"),<ref>{{cite web|url=https://nerdist.com/black-mirror-uss-callister-star-trek-trailer/|title=Black Mirror's \"U.S.S Callister\" Trailers Gives Us An Uneasy Star Trek Adventure|website=Nerdist|publisher=[[Nerdist Industries]]|last=Lutes|first=Alicia|date=5 December 2017|accessdate=10 December 2017|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20171210072002/https://nerdist.com/black-mirror-uss-callister-star-trek-trailer/|archive-date=10 December 2017|url-status=dead}}</ref> and [[Daniel Lapaine]] (\"[[The Entire History of You]]\" and \"[[Black Museum (Black Mirror)|Black Museum\"]]).<ref>{{cite web|url=http://heavy.com/entertainment/2017/12/black-museum-cast-characters-black-mirror/|title=Black Museum: Meet the Cast from the Black Mirror Episode|website=[[Heavy.com|Heavy]]|last=Dwilson|first=Stephanie Dube|date=29 December 2017|accessdate=31 December 2017|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20171231103500/http://heavy.com/entertainment/2017/12/black-museum-cast-characters-black-mirror/|archive-date=31 December 2017|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nWhen asked in interviews, Brooker has repeatedly stated that there are no plans for a sequel episode to \"San Junipero\". He told ''[[Los Angeles Times]]'' that they \"want to keep [Kelly and Yorkie] happy there\".<ref name=\"LATimes\">{{cite web |url=https://www.latimes.com/entertainment/envelope/la-en-st-0817-black-mirror-20170816-story.html |title='Black Mirror's' rare glimpse of technology as a means to joy earns an Emmy nod |website=[[Los Angeles Times]] |publisher=[[Tronc]] |last=Press |first=Joy |date=17 August 2017 |accessdate=13 September 2017 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170912125638/http://www.latimes.com/entertainment/envelope/la-en-st-0817-black-mirror-20170816-story.html |archive-date=12 September 2017 |url-status=live }}</ref> However, Brooker has said that the series \"may be referring to San Junipero again\" in [[Easter egg (media)|Easter eggs]], which the series has used before.<ref name=\"NME sequel\">{{cite web |url=https://www.nme.com/news/tv/charlie-brooker-black-mirror-san-junipero-sequel-2133848 |title=Charlie Brooker talks prospect of 'San Junipero' sequel episode on 'Black Mirror' |website=[[NME]] |last=Moore |first=Sam |date=3 September 2017 |access-date=12 December 2017 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180726040949/https://www.nme.com/news/tv/charlie-brooker-black-mirror-san-junipero-sequel-2133848 |archive-date=26 July 2018 |url-status=live }}</ref> Brooker has also raised the idea of doing a sequel to the episode in \"a completely different form\", such as a [[graphic novel]] or \"an experience\".<ref name=\"Hollywood interview\">{{cite web |url=https://www.hollywoodreporter.com/live-feed/black-mirror-season-4-episodes-charlie-brooker-annabel-jones-interview-spoilers-1033807 |title='Black Mirror' Bosses on \"San Junipero\" Sequel and an Unpredictable Season 4 |website=[[The Hollywood Reporter]] |last=Strause |first=Jackie |date=3 September 2017 |accessdate=13 September 2017 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170913234649/http://www.hollywoodreporter.com/live-feed/black-mirror-season-4-episodes-charlie-brooker-annabel-jones-interview-spoilers-1033807 |archive-date=13 September 2017 |url-status=live }}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.nme.com/news/tv/charlie-brooker-rules-out-direct-sequel-to-san-junipero-but-teases-a-graphic-novel-about-it-instead-2135308 |title=Charlie Brooker rules out direct sequel to 'San Junipero' but teases graphic novel about it instead |website=[[NME]] |last=Jones |first=Damian |date=7 September 2017 |accessdate=8 December 2017 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20171208070805/http://www.nme.com/news/tv/charlie-brooker-rules-out-direct-sequel-to-san-junipero-but-teases-a-graphic-novel-about-it-instead-2135308 |archive-date=8 December 2017 |url-status=live }}</ref> Brooker has suggested that the ''Bandersnatch'' character Colin Ritman (portrayed by [[Will Poulter]]) could potentially show up in future ''Black Mirror'' episodes, given that the character, in certain paths, seems to just disappear but has awareness of alternate timelines and realities.<ref name=\"thr s5\">{{cite news| url = https://www.hollywoodreporter.com/live-feed/black-mirrors-charlie-brooker-talks-season-5-1172112 | title = 'Black Mirror' Creator Charlie Brooker Shares Season 5 Update | first = Jackie | last = Strause | date = 2 January 2019 | accessdate = 2 January 2019 | work = [[The Hollywood Reporter]] | archive-url = https://web.archive.org/web/20190102182001/https://www.hollywoodreporter.com/live-feed/black-mirrors-charlie-brooker-talks-season-5-1172112 | archive-date = 2 January 2019 | url-status=live }}</ref>\n\nAround January 2020, Brooker and Jones announced their departure from House of Tomorrow, the show's production company with the [[Endemol Shine UK|Endemol Shine group]] which the two had led, during their negotiations with Netflix that had started mid-2019. ''[[Variety (magazine)|Variety]]'' reported that [[intellectual property]] issues were at the center of this change, with the series' rights held by Endemol.<ref>{{cite web | url = https://variety.com/2020/tv/news/black-mirror-charlie-brooker-annabel-jones-netflix-endemol-shine-group-1203478778/ | title = 'Black Mirror' Creators Quit Endemol Shine-Owned Label While Navigating IP Headaches With Netflix | first = Manori | last = Ravindran | date = 24 January 2020 | accessdate = 25 January 2020 | work = [[Variety (magazine)|Variety]] }}</ref> By February 2020 Brooker and Jones established Broke and Bones, a new production company with each having a 50% stake in it.<ref>{{cite web | url = https://deadline.com/2020/02/black-mirror-charlie-brooker-annabel-jones-launch-broke-and-bones-1202853906/ | title = 'Black Mirror' Creators Charlie Brooker & Annabel Jones Waste Little Time In Launching New Production Outfit | first = Jake | last = Kanter | date = 10 February 2020 | accessdate = 10 February 2020 | work = [[Deadline Hollywood]] }}</ref>\n\n== Reception ==\n\n=== Critical response ===\nOn [[Rotten Tomatoes]], series 1 received a 97% rating,<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.rottentomatoes.com/tv/black_mirror/s01/|title=Black Mirror: Season 1 |website=[[Rotten Tomatoes]]|accessdate=6 December 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190409024525/https://www.rottentomatoes.com/tv/black_mirror/s01|archive-date=9 April 2019|url-status=live}}</ref> series 2 received an 86% rating,<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.rottentomatoes.com/tv/black_mirror/s02|title=Black Mirror: Season 2 |website=[[Rotten Tomatoes]]|accessdate=6 December 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190409024523/https://www.rottentomatoes.com/tv/black_mirror/s02|archive-date=9 April 2019|url-status=live}}</ref> \"White Christmas\" received a 93% rating,<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.rottentomatoes.com/tv/black_mirror/17660|title=Black Mirror: White Christmas (2014 Christmas Special) |website=[[Rotten Tomatoes]]|accessdate=6 December 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190407104818/https://www.rottentomatoes.com/tv/black_mirror/17660|archive-date=7 April 2019|url-status=live}}</ref> series 3 received an 86% rating<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.rottentomatoes.com/tv/black_mirror/s03|title=Black Mirror: Season 3|website=[[Rotten Tomatoes]]|accessdate=6 December 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20181208205532/https://www.rottentomatoes.com/tv/black_mirror/s03/|archive-date=8 December 2018|url-status=live}}</ref> and a score of 82 on [[Metacritic]],<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.metacritic.com/tv/black-mirror/season-3|title=Black Mirror - Season 3 Reviews |website=[[Metacritic]]|accessdate=6 December 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20181216071628/https://www.metacritic.com/tv/black-mirror/season-3|archive-date=16 December 2018|url-status=live}}</ref> series 4 received an 84% rating on Rotten Tomatoes<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.rottentomatoes.com/tv/black_mirror/s04|title=Black Mirror: Season 4 |website=[[Rotten Tomatoes]]|accessdate=6 December 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190410102351/https://www.rottentomatoes.com/tv/black_mirror/s04|archive-date=10 April 2019|url-status=live}}</ref> and a score of 72 on Metacritic,<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.metacritic.com/tv/black-mirror/season-4|title=Black Mirror - Season 4 Reviews |website=[[Metacritic]]|accessdate=6 December 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20181107061750/https://www.metacritic.com/tv/black-mirror/season-4|archive-date=7 November 2018|url-status=live}}</ref> ''Bandersnatch'' holds a 72% rating on Rotten Tomatoes<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.rottentomatoes.com/tv/black_mirror/52530 |title=Black Mirror: Bandersnatch |accessdate=12 April 2019 |website=[[Rotten Tomatoes]] |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190328224829/https://www.rottentomatoes.com/tv/black_mirror/52530 |archive-date=28 March 2019 |url-status=live }}</ref> and a score of 61 on Metacritic,<ref>{{cite web | url = https://www.metacritic.com/tv/black-mirror-bandersnatch | title = Black Mirror: Bandersnatch | accessdate = 12 April 2019 | publisher = [[Metacritic]] | archive-url = https://web.archive.org/web/20190416101857/https://www.metacritic.com/tv/black-mirror-bandersnatch | archive-date = 16 April 2019 | url-status=live }}</ref> and series 5 holds a rating of 63% on Rotten Tomatoes<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.rottentomatoes.com/tv/black_mirror/s05|title=Black Mirror: Season 5 |website=[[Rotten Tomatoes]]|accessdate=5 June 2019}}</ref> and a score of 65 on Metacritic.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.metacritic.com/tv/black-mirror/season-5|title=Black Mirror: Season 5|website=[[Metacritic]]|accessdate=8 June 2019}}</ref>\n\nThe first series has been praised as being creative and shocking with twists-in-the-tale reminiscent of ''[[The Twilight Zone]]''.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.rottentomatoes.com/tv/black-mirror/s01/ |title=Black Mirror |website=Rotten Tomatoes |access-date=26 January 2015 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150208025557/http://www.rottentomatoes.com/tv/black-mirror/s01 |archive-date=8 February 2015 |url-status=live }}</ref><ref name=\"Tele1Hogan\">{{cite news |title=Black Mirror: The National Anthem, Channel 4, review |newspaper=The Daily Telegraph |first=Michael |last=Hogan |date=4 December 2011|title-link=The National Anthem (Black Mirror) }}</ref> Michael Hogan of ''[[The Daily Telegraph]]'' described the first episode, \"[[The National Anthem (Black Mirror)|The National Anthem]]\", as \"a shocking but ballsy, blackly comic study of the modern media\".<ref name=\"Tele1Hogan\" /> He continued: \"This was a dementedly brilliant idea. The satire was so audacious, it left me open-mouthed and squealing. Rather like that poor pig.\"<ref name=\"Tele1Hogan\" /> The series was taken up across much of the world, including Australia, Israel, Sweden, Spain, Poland, Hungary and China.<ref name=\"ChigTri1\">{{cite news |title='Black Mirror' sold to 21 territories: Satirical drama premiered on U.K.'s Channel 4 |url=http://articles.chicagotribune.com/2012-03-29/entertainment/sns-201203291204reedbusivarietynvr1118052051mar29_1_satirical-drama-territories-uk-s-channel |newspaper=Chicago Tribune |accessdate=17 March 2013 |first=Elsa |last=Keslassy |date=29 March 2012 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20131230234740/http://articles.chicagotribune.com/2012-03-29/entertainment/sns-201203291204reedbusivarietynvr1118052051mar29_1_satirical-drama-territories-uk-s-channel |archive-date=30 December 2013 |url-status=live }}</ref> The series has become popular and been well received in China, becoming one of the most discussed series in early 2012.<ref name=\"gz\">{{cite web |url=http://ent.163.com/12/0204/04/7PD1GBIV00032DGD.html |title=\u82f1\u5267\u300a\u9ed1\u955c\u300b\u88ab\u79f0\"\u795e\u5267\" \u53cd\u6620\u4eba\u6027\u5f31\u70b9\u5f15\u70ed\u8bae |website=Guangzhou Daily News |date=4 February 2012 |accessdate=8 August 2012 |language=zh |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120408071751/http://ent.163.com/12/0204/04/7PD1GBIV00032DGD.html |archive-date=8 April 2012 |url-status=dead }}</ref> User ratings on [[Douban]] reached 9.3,<ref name=\"chain\">{{cite web |url=http://tech.sina.com.cn/i/2012-04-07/04486923463_2.shtml |title=\u4e92\u8054\u7f51\u9119\u89c6\u98df\u7269\u94fe\u5927\u5168 |website=[[Southern Metropolis Daily]] |date=7 April 2012 |accessdate=8 August 2012 |language=zh |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120409210847/http://tech.sina.com.cn/i/2012-04-07/04486923463_2.shtml |archive-date=9 April 2012 |url-status=live }}</ref> higher than most popular American dramas.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://culture.ifeng.com/whrd/detail_2012_04/05/13671813_0.shtml |title=\u8ff7\u4f60\u82f1\u5267\u5f3a\u52bf\u5165\u4fb5 \u5c0f\u4e2a\u5934\u5267\u96c6\u53d7\u5927\u6bd4\u4f8b\u89c2\u4f17\u6b22\u8fce |website=[[Southern Weekly]] |date=5 April 2012 |accessdate=8 August 2012 |language=zh |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20130320225409/http://culture.ifeng.com/whrd/detail_2012_04/05/13671813_0.shtml |archive-date=20 March 2013 |url-status=live }}</ref> Many viewers and critics praised the depth of the series.<ref name=\"gz\" /><ref name=\"chain\" /><ref name=\"bjnews\" /> A reporter from ''The Beijing News'' thought the programme was \"an [[apocalypse]] of modern world\", \"desperate but profound\".<ref name=\"bjnews\">{{cite web |url=http://epaper.bjnews.com.cn/html/2012-02/24/content_319498.htm?div=-1 |title=\u300a\u9ed1\u955c\u300b Black Mirror |website=Beijing News |date=24 February 2012 |accessdate=8 August 2012 |language=zh |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20141218112519/http://epaper.bjnews.com.cn/html/2012-02/24/content_319498.htm?div=-1 |archive-date=18 December 2014 |url-status=live }}</ref> Another article from the same newspaper thought each story criticised television from different aspects.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.bjnews.com.cn/feature/2012/02/17/182968.html |title=\u300a\u9ed1\u955c\u300b \u7528\u7535\u89c6\u5267\u8bbd\u523a\u7535\u89c6\u5267 |website=Beijing News |date=17 February 2012 |accessdate=8 August 2012 |language=zh |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20121018005630/http://www.bjnews.com.cn/feature/2012/02/17/182968.html |archive-date=18 October 2012 |url-status=live }}</ref> Xu Wen at ''[[The Epoch Times]]'' thought the stories reveal modernity's moral turpitude.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.epochtimes.com/gb/12/2/16/n3514116.htm |title=\u300a\u9ed1\u955c\u300b\u5bf9\u73b0\u65f6\u7684\u97ad\u631e\u4e0e\u601d\u8003 |author=Xu Wen |website=The Epoch Times |date=16 February 2012 |accessdate=8 August 2012 |language=zh |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20130320225404/http://www.epochtimes.com/gb/12/2/16/n3514116.htm |archive-date=20 March 2013 |url-status=live }}</ref>\n\nIn its second series, ''Black Mirror'' continued to receive praise. In his review of the episode \"[[Be Right Back]]\", Sameer Rahim of ''The Telegraph'' wrote, \"The show touched on important ideas&nbsp;\u2013 the false way we sometimes present ourselves online, and our growing addiction to virtual lives&nbsp;\u2013 but it was also a touching exploration of grief. To my mind it's the best thing Brooker has done.\"<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/culture/tvandradio/tv-and-radio-reviews/9863062/Black-Mirror-Be-Right-Back-Channel-4-review.html |title=Black Mirror: Be Right Back, Channel 4, review |last=Rahim |first=Sameer |date=11 February 2013 |website=Telegraph |access-date=19 January 2019 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180912022340/https://www.telegraph.co.uk/culture/tvandradio/tv-and-radio-reviews/9863062/Black-Mirror-Be-Right-Back-Channel-4-review.html |archive-date=12 September 2018 |url-status=live }}</ref> Jane Simon of  ''[[The Daily Mirror]]'' newspaper website said the second episode of the second series, \"[[White Bear (Black Mirror)|White Bear]]\", lacked the \"instant emotional tug\" of the series opener, \"Be Right Back\".<ref name=\"Mirror1\">{{cite news |title=Charlie Brooker's second Black Mirror drama 'White Bear' is another work of dark and twisted genius |url=https://www.mirror.co.uk/tv/tv-previews/black-mirror-channel-4-video-1714613 |newspaper=The Daily Mirror |publisher=MGN Ltd. |accessdate=17 March 2013 |first=Jane |last=Simon |date=18 February 2013 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20130316091755/http://www.mirror.co.uk/tv/tv-previews/black-mirror-channel-4-video-1714613 |archive-date=16 March 2013 |url-status=live }}</ref> She continued: a third of the way through the second episode, she had lost hope of its concluding well, \"the acting was unbelievable, the script was riddled with horror-film cliches, the violence was a bit over the top\", but that by the end, \"I turned out to be absolutely dead wrong on every single count.\" She ended the piece with: \"It's another work of dark and twisted genius from Mr Brooker.\"  The second series is popular in China. Wen Bai at ''[[Information Times]]'' thought the second series was still \"cannily made\", and \"near perfection\".<ref>{{cite web|url=http://informationtimes.dayoo.com/html/2013-03/11/content_2175973.htm |title=\u7eed\u96c6\u4e5f\u53ef\u5982\u6b64\u7f8e\u597d |website=Information Times |date=11 March 2013 |accessdate=17 March 2013 |author=\u6587\u767d |language=zh |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140201203355/http://informationtimes.dayoo.com/html/2013-03/11/content_2175973.htm |archivedate=1 February 2014 |df=dmy-all }}</ref>\n\nIn December 2014, [[Stephen King]] noted his admiration for the series.<ref>{{cite tweet |last=King|first=Stephen|author-link=Stephen King|user=StephenKing|number=541660684720021504|date=7 December 2014 |title=Loved BLACK MIRROR. Terrifying, funny, intelligent. It's like THE TWILIGHT ZONE, only rated R.||access-date=26 February 2017}}</ref><ref name=premds>{{cite web |title=Black Mirror: Charlie Brooker, Jon Hamm on the dark side of Yuletide |url=http://www.digitalspy.co.uk/tv/interviews/a616435/black-mirror-charlie-brooker-jon-hamm-on-the-dark-side-of-yuletide.html |accessdate=14 December 2014 |website=Digital Spy |date=14 December 2014 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20141214172129/http://www.digitalspy.co.uk/tv/interviews/a616435/black-mirror-charlie-brooker-jon-hamm-on-the-dark-side-of-yuletide.html |archive-date=14 December 2014 |url-status=live }}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.denofgeek.com/tv/black-mirror/33368/black-mirror-interview-charlie-brooker-jon-hamm-rafe-spall |title=Black Mirror interview: Charlie Brooker, Jon Hamm, Rafe Spall |website=Den of Geek |access-date=15 March 2016 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160107103939/http://www.denofgeek.com/tv/black-mirror/33368/black-mirror-interview-charlie-brooker-jon-hamm-rafe-spall |archive-date=7 January 2016 |url-status=live }}</ref> The series' Christmas special that year, \"[[White Christmas (Black Mirror)|White Christmas]]\", received critical acclaim. Ben Beaumont-Thomas of ''[[The Guardian]]'' praised the comic satire of the episode and noted that \"sentimentality is offset with wicked wit, and Brooker's brio and imagination paper over any gaps in logic.\"<ref>{{cite news |first=Ben |last=Beaumont-Thomas |url=https://www.theguardian.com/media/2014/dec/12/black-mirror-charlie-brooker-rafe-spall-jon-hamm |title=Black Mirror: White Christmas review&nbsp;\u2013 sentimentality offset with wicked wit |newspaper=[[The Guardian]] |date=12 December 2014 |accessdate=17 December 2014 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150808040919/http://www.theguardian.com/media/2014/dec/12/black-mirror-charlie-brooker-rafe-spall-jon-hamm |archive-date=8 August 2015 |url-status=live }}</ref> ''The Daily Telegraph'' reviewer Mark Monahan gave the episode 4/5 stars, noting that the drama was \"thrilling stuff: escapist entertainment with a very real-world sting in its tail\". Monahan equated the episode with the stronger of the previous ''Black Mirror'' episodes, stating that \"it exaggerated present-day technology and obsessions to subtle but infernal effect, a nightmare-before-Christmas reminder that to revere our digital gizmos is to become their pathetic slave.\"<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/culture/tvandradio/tv-and-radio-reviews/11295878/black-mirror-christmas-special-review-the-nightmares-before-christmas.html |title=Black Mirror: White Christmas, review: 'Be careful what you wish for...' |first=Mark |last=Monahan |newspaper=[[The Daily Telegraph]] |date=17 December 2014 |accessdate=17 December 2014 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20141216233722/http://www.telegraph.co.uk/culture/tvandradio/tv-and-radio-reviews/11295878/black-mirror-christmas-special-review-the-nightmares-before-christmas.html |archive-date=16 December 2014 |url-status=live }}</ref> In 2019, ''Black Mirror'' was ranked 23rd on ''The Guardian'''s list of the 100 best TV shows of the 21st century.<ref>{{cite web |title= The 100 best TV shows of the 21st century |url=https://www.theguardian.com/tv-and-radio/2019/sep/16/100-best-tv-shows-of-the-21st-century |website=The Guardian |accessdate=23 September 2019}}</ref>\n\nJournalists have reported that some of the concepts in ''Black Mirror'' have come true, in fashion, within the real world and have called the series a [[Magic 8-Ball]] for the future.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.thedailybeast.com/black-mirror-is-tvs-magic-8-ball |title='Black Mirror' Is TV's Magic 8-Ball |first=G. Clay |last=Whitaker |date=14 September 2015 |accessdate=15 December 2017 |website=[[The Daily Beast]] |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170820214301/http://www.thedailybeast.com/black-mirror-is-tvs-magic-8-ball |archive-date=20 August 2017 |url-status=live }}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.inverse.com/article/15540-how-many-episodes-of-black-mirror-have-already-come-true |title=The 7 'Black Mirror' Prophecies That Have Come True |first=Brock |last=Wilbur |date=13 May 2016 |accessdate=15 December 2017 |website=Inverse |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20171216144027/https://www.inverse.com/article/15540-how-many-episodes-of-black-mirror-have-already-come-true |archive-date=16 December 2017 |url-status=live }}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/bbcthree/item/5c0ce0ab-c88f-45be-b44d-59841e5f9e64 |title=Seven creepy Black Mirror predictions that actually came true |first=Catriona |last=White |date=14 December 2017 |accessdate=15 December 2017 |website=[[BBC Three]] |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20171223235107/http://www.bbc.co.uk/bbcthree/item/5c0ce0ab-c88f-45be-b44d-59841e5f9e64 |archive-date=23 December 2017 |url-status=live }}</ref> The first episode, \"[[The National Anthem (Black Mirror)|The National Anthem]]\", revolves around the British Prime Minister's being blackmailed into having sex with a pig; in September 2015, four years after the episode aired, allegations were published that [[David Cameron]], who at the time was British Prime Minister, had placed a \"private part\" into the mouth of a dead pig as part of a university initiation rite.<ref>{{cite news |title=Black Mirror creator Charlie Brooker denies he knew about #Hameron |newspaper=[[Metro (British newspaper)|Metro]] |date=21 September 2015 |first=Nicole |last=Morley |url=http://metro.co.uk/2015/09/21/black-mirror-creator-charlie-brooker-denies-he-knew-about-hameron-5400774/ |access-date=15 December 2017 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20171119225940/http://metro.co.uk/2015/09/21/black-mirror-creator-charlie-brooker-denies-he-knew-about-hameron-5400774/ |archive-date=19 November 2017 |url-status=live }}</ref> Brooker has called the event a \"coincidence, albeit a quite bizarre one\" and was perturbed when he first heard the allegations: \"I did genuinely for a moment wonder if reality was a simulation, whether it exists only to trick me\", he said in an interview.<ref name=\"piggate guardian\">{{cite web |url=https://www.theguardian.com/tv-and-radio/shortcuts/2015/sep/21/pigs-prime-minister-black-mirror-ashcroft-allegation-charlie-brooker |title=Charlie Brooker on Cameron and #piggate: 'I'd have been screaming it into traffic if I'd known' |website=[[The Guardian]] |last=Benedictus |first=Leo |date=21 September 2015 |accessdate=7 September 2017 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150923010128/http://www.theguardian.com/tv-and-radio/shortcuts/2015/sep/21/pigs-prime-minister-black-mirror-ashcroft-allegation-charlie-brooker |archive-date=23 September 2015 |url-status=live }}</ref> Several news reports compared [[Donald Trump presidential campaign, 2016|Donald Trump's 2016 presidential campaign]] to \"[[The Waldo Moment]]\", a 2013 episode in the second series;<ref name=\"WP-20150908\">{{cite news |last=Cillizza |first=Chris |authorlink=Chris Cillizza |title=Donald Trump's troll game of Jeb Bush: A+ |url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/news/the-fix/wp/2015/09/08/donald-trumps-troll-game-of-jeb-bush-a/ |date=8 September 2015 |newspaper=[[The Washington Post]] |accessdate=24 October 2015 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20151017031625/https://www.washingtonpost.com/news/the-fix/wp/2015/09/08/donald-trumps-troll-game-of-jeb-bush-a/ |archive-date=17 October 2015 |url-status=live }}</ref><ref name=\"DC-20150807\">{{cite web |last=O'Keefe |first=Meghan |title=Why You Must Watch 'Black Mirror': \"The Waldo Moment\" This Weekend |url=http://decider.com/2015/08/07/black-mirror-the-waldo-effect-2016-presidential-race/ |date=7 August 2015 |website=Decider |accessdate=24 October 2015 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20151011065627/http://decider.com/2015/08/07/black-mirror-the-waldo-effect-2016-presidential-race/ |archive-date=11 October 2015 |url-status=live }}</ref> later, in September 2016, Brooker also compared the Trump campaign to the episode and predicted Trump would win the 2016 election.<ref name=\"DB-20160913\">{{cite news |last=Yamato |first=Jen |title='Black Mirror' Creator Predicts Trump Will Be President: 'I Find It F*cking Terrifying' |url=http://www.thedailybeast.com/articles/2016/09/13/black-mirror-creator-predicts-trump-will-be-president-i-find-it-f-cking-terrifying.html |date=13 September 2016 |work=[[The Daily Beast]] |accessdate=8 October 2016 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20161009171420/http://www.thedailybeast.com/articles/2016/09/13/black-mirror-creator-predicts-trump-will-be-president-i-find-it-f-cking-terrifying.html |archive-date=9 October 2016 |url-status=live }}</ref><ref name=\"BMD-20160913\">{{cite web|last=Wampler |first=Scott |title=Black Mirror's Charlie Brooker Predicts Trump Will Win The Election |url=http://birthmoviesdeath.com/2016/09/13/black-mirrors-charlie-brooker-predicts-that-trump-will-win-the-election |date=13 September 2016 |website=BirthMoviesDeath.com |accessdate=8 October 2016 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20161010073127/http://birthmoviesdeath.com/2016/09/13/black-mirrors-charlie-brooker-predicts-that-trump-will-win-the-election |archive-date=10 October 2016 |url-status=live }}</ref> The third series episode \"[[Nosedive (Black Mirror)|Nosedive]]\" presented a social rating-based system that several found mirrored by China's proposed [[Social Credit System]].<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/world/asia_pacific/chinas-plan-to-organize-its-whole-society-around-big-data-a-rating-for-everyone/2016/10/20/1cd0dd9c-9516-11e6-ae9d-0030ac1899cd_story.html |title=China's plan to organize its society relies on 'big data' to rate everyone |website=[[The Washington Post]] |last=Denyer |first=Simon |date=22 October 2016 |accessdate=10 October 2017 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20171010060617/https://www.washingtonpost.com/world/asia_pacific/chinas-plan-to-organize-its-whole-society-around-big-data-a-rating-for-everyone/2016/10/20/1cd0dd9c-9516-11e6-ae9d-0030ac1899cd_story.html |archive-date=10 October 2017 |url-status=live }}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.avclub.com/at-least-one-black-mirror-episode-is-already-coming-tru-1821315524 |title=At least one Black Mirror episode is already coming true in China |first=William |last=Hughes |date=15 December 2017 |accessdate=15 December 2017 |website=[[The A.V. Club]] |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20171215062920/https://www.avclub.com/at-least-one-black-mirror-episode-is-already-coming-tru-1821315524 |archive-date=15 December 2017 |url-status=live }}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/on-demand/2017/12/15/black-mirror-coming-true-china-rating-affects-home-transport/ |title=Black Mirror is coming true in China, where your 'rating' affects your home, transport and social circle |first=Alice |last=Vincent |date=15 December 2017 |accessdate=15 December 2017 |website=[[The Daily Telegraph]] |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20171215111451/http://www.telegraph.co.uk/on-demand/2017/12/15/black-mirror-coming-true-china-rating-affects-home-transport/ |archive-date=15 December 2017 |url-status=live }}</ref> Brooker has been surprised to see how some of these events had come to pass. \"It was quite trippy, though. I'm kind of getting used to it, because it seems like it's quite often that there are things that are in the stories that come true.\"<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.thedailybeast.com/black-mirror-creator-charlie-brooker-on-chinas-social-credit-system-and-the-rise-of-trump |title='Black Mirror' Creator Charlie Brooker on China's 'Social Credit' System and the Rise of Trump |first=Marlow |last=Stern |date=27 October 2017 |accessdate=15 December 2017 |website=[[The Daily Beast]] |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170908214223/http://www.thedailybeast.com/black-mirror-creator-charlie-brooker-on-chinas-social-credit-system-and-the-rise-of-trump |archive-date=8 September 2017 |url-status=live }}</ref> Ten days after the release of series 4 episode \"[[Crocodile (Black Mirror)|Crocodile]]\" \u2013 which included a self-driving pizza delivery truck as a major plot device \u2013 [[Toyota]] and [[Pizza Hut]] announced the e-Palette, a driverless delivery vehicle, at the 2018 [[Consumer Electronics Show]]. The conceptual vehicle drew numerous comparisons with its fictional counterpart,<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.thrillist.com/entertainment/nation/black-mirror-season-4-crocodile-episode-pizza-hut-delivery-truck|title=The 'Black Mirror' Killer Pizza Truck Is Real Now, Thanks to Pizza Hut|last=Fitz-Gerald|first=Sean|date=2018-01-09|work=Thrillist|access-date=2018-08-08|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180808073237/https://www.thrillist.com/entertainment/nation/black-mirror-season-4-crocodile-episode-pizza-hut-delivery-truck|archive-date=8 August 2018|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.highsnobiety.com/p/pizza-hut-black-mirror-truck/|title=Pizza Hut Goes 'Black Mirror' With Self-Driving Pizza Truck|date=2018-08-07|work=Highsnobiety|access-date=2018-08-08|language=en-US|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180808104340/https://www.highsnobiety.com/p/pizza-hut-black-mirror-truck/|archive-date=8 August 2018|url-status=live}}</ref> and the official Twitter account for ''Black Mirror'' commented on the announcement, saying, \"We know how this goes.\"<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://twitter.com/blackmirror/status/950506825035780096|title=Black Mirror on Twitter|work=Twitter|access-date=2018-08-08|language=en|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180215125811/https://twitter.com/blackmirror/status/950506825035780096|archive-date=15 February 2018|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\n=== Accolades ===\n{{Main|List of awards and nominations received by Black Mirror}}\nIn November 2012, ''Black Mirror'' won [[International Emmy Award for best TV movie or miniseries|Best TV Movie/Miniseries]] at the [[International Academy of Television Arts and Sciences|International Emmy Awards]].<ref name=\"BBC 2012\">{{cite news |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/entertainment-arts-20406749 |publisher=BBC News |title=Black Mirror and Pratchett film win International Emmys |date=20 November 2012 |access-date=21 July 2018 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20181011092848/https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/entertainment-arts-20406749 |archive-date=11 October 2018 |url-status=live }}</ref> Bryce Dallas Howard received a [[Screen Actors Guild Award for Outstanding Performance by a Female Actor in a Miniseries or Television Movie|Screen Actors Guild Award]] nomination for her performance in the episode \"[[Nosedive (Black Mirror)|Nosedive]]\".<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.ew.com/article/2016/12/14/2017-sag-awards-nominations |title=SAG Awards nominations 2017: See the full list |first=Joey |last=Nolfi |website=Entertainment Weekly |date=14 December 2016 |access-date=15 December 2016 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170111005833/http://www.ew.com/article/2016/12/14/2017-sag-awards-nominations |archive-date=11 January 2017 |url-status=live }}</ref> At the [[69th Primetime Emmy Awards]], ''Black Mirror'' received three nominations with two wins, including [[Primetime Emmy Award for Outstanding Television Movie|Outstanding Television Movie]] for \"[[San Junipero]]\".<ref name=\":0\">{{cite web |url=http://metro.co.uk/2017/06/24/charlie-brooker-says-black-mirror-season-4-will-be-the-most-out-there-yet-as-he-teases-new-details-6731644/ |title=Charlie Brooker teases Black Mirror season 4 will be the most 'out there' yet |last=Starkey |first=Adam |date=24 June 2017 |website=Metro |access-date=17 July 2017 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170729161318/http://metro.co.uk/2017/06/24/charlie-brooker-says-black-mirror-season-4-will-be-the-most-out-there-yet-as-he-teases-new-details-6731644/ |archive-date=29 July 2017 |url-status=live }}</ref><ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.huffingtonpost.com/entry/black-mirrors-san-junipero-nominated-for-two-emmys-and-were-crying_us_59679cdbe4b0a8d46d12eae7 |title=Black Mirror's 'San Junipero' Nominated For Two Emmys And We're Crying |last=Amatulli |first=Jenna |date=13 July 2017 |work=Huffington Post |access-date=17 July 2017 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170716115927/http://www.huffingtonpost.com/entry/black-mirrors-san-junipero-nominated-for-two-emmys-and-were-crying_us_59679cdbe4b0a8d46d12eae7 |archive-date=16 July 2017 |url-status=live }}</ref> \"[[USS Callister]]\" received three Emmy Awards, including Outstanding Television Movie, and four Emmy nominations in 2018.<ref name=\"USS Callister Black Mirror\">{{cite web|url=https://www.emmys.com/shows/uss-callister-black-mirror|title=USS Callister (Black Mirror)|publisher=[[Academy of Television Arts & Sciences]]|access-date=13 July 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180712221955/https://www.emmys.com/shows/uss-callister-black-mirror|archive-date=12 July 2018|url-status=live}}</ref><ref name=\"USS Callister Black Mirror\"/><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.emmys.com/shows/black-museum-black-mirror|title=Black Museum (Black Mirror)|publisher=[[Academy of Television Arts & Sciences]]|access-date=13 July 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180712224146/https://www.emmys.com/shows/black-museum-black-mirror|archive-date=12 July 2018|url-status=live}}</ref> ''Bandersnatch'' won two Emmys in 2019, including Outstanding Television Movie, making it the third consecutive win for ''Black Mirror'' in that category.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://pitchfork.com/news/emmys-2019-black-mirror-bandersnatch-wins-outstanding-tv-movie/|title=Emmys 2019: ''Black Mirror: Bandersnatch'' Wins Outstanding TV Movie|work=[[Pitchfork (website)|Pitchfork]]|last=Hussey|first=Allison|date=23 September 2019|accessdate=23 September 2019}}</ref>\n\n==Spin-off media==\n===Webisodes===\n{{external media\n|topic=Czarne Lusterko\n|video1=\"[https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=Y_igsGHD7Hg The Sum of Happiness]\"\n|video2=\"[https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=z1o1kvjTzG8 69.90]\"\n|video3=\"[https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=MFUUydRo-OQ 1%]\"\n|video4=\"[https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=LN_eEJFtQtE The Breakup]\"\n}}\nA series of webisodes ''Czarne Lusterko'' (Polish for ''Little Black Mirror'') was produced for Netflix Polska by Jacek Ambrosiewicz, in collaboration with Polish YouTubers. Released on 19 January 2018, the four shorts vary between eight and 21 minutes in length. \"69.90\" explores \"loneliness and gaming\" according to creators Huyen Pham and Marcin Nguyen, who discussed twenty different ideas for the episode before deciding upon an episode featuring a computer simulation which is indistinguishable from real life. \"The Breakup\" features Krzysztof Gonciarz and Kasia Mecinski; it used realism and ordinary technology, being filmed in part on a [[Panasonic Lumix DC-GH5]] to emulate [[vlog]] aesthetics. \"The Sum of Happiness\" was posted on Martin Stankiewicz's YouTube channel and focuses on a neurological implant and a relationship app, which have been featured before in ''Black Mirror''. \"1%\" is about a \"fallible\" and \"ruthless\" piece of [[obstetrics]] technology.<ref name=\"Lusterko\">{{cite web|url=https://i-d.vice.com/en_uk/article/43b3ep/the-polish-version-of-black-mirror-might-be-the-best-thing-on-the-internet|title=The Polish version of Black Mirror might be the best thing on the internet|work=[[Vice Media]]|last=Greenhill|first=Richard|date=2 April 2018|accessdate=1 July 2019|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190526093523/https://i-d.vice.com/en_uk/article/43b3ep/the-polish-version-of-black-mirror-might-be-the-best-thing-on-the-internet|archive-date=26 May 2019|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\n{{external media\n|topic=Stories From Our Future\n|video1=\"[https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=RqATb20dO34 Cure for Loneliness]\"\n|video2=\"[https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=gCwEJiQpaXc Getting to Know You]\"\n|video3=\"[https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=xdOC8WIXAkE The Healthy Alternative]\"\n}}\nA second series of webisodes, initially announced as ''Little Black Mirror'' but eventually renamed ''Stories From Our Future'', was directed for Netflix Am\u00e9rica Latina by American YouTuber [[Rudy Mancuso]].<ref name=\"Little Black Mirror\">{{cite web|url=https://io9.gizmodo.com/little-black-mirror-is-a-series-of-black-mirror-webisod-1835025432|title=Little Black Mirror Is a Series of Black Mirror Webisodes Coming to Netflix's Latin American YouTube Channel|work=[[io9]]|last=Muncy|first=Julie|date=26 May 2019|accessdate=26 May 2019|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190525202908/https://io9.gizmodo.com/little-black-mirror-is-a-series-of-black-mirror-webisod-1835025432|archive-date=25 May 2019|url-status=live}}</ref><ref name=\"Stories From Our FUture\">{{cite web|url=https://decider.com/2019/06/02/little-black-mirror-renamed-stories-from-our-future-by-netflix/|title='Little Black Mirror' Renamed 'Stories From Our Future' By Netflix|work=[[Decider (website)|Decider]]|last=Otterson|first=Joe|date=2 June 2019|accessdate=27 June 2019}}</ref> Initially planned for release on Netflix Am\u00e9rica Latina's YouTube channel, as part of promotion for the programme's fifth series, the original trailer for the project was removed by Netflix. The shorts were later released on 10 June 2019 on channels of individuals who feature in them.<ref name=\"DS SFOF\"/> \"Cure for Loneliness\" was released on Mancuso's channel; \"Getting to Know You\" was released on YouTuber [[Lele Pons]]' channel; \"The Healthy Alternative\" was released on vlogger [[Juanpa Zurita]]'s channel.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://heavy.com/entertainment/2019/06/watch-little-black-mirror-short-films-stories-from-our-future/|title=Watch 'Little Black Mirror' Short Films: Stories From Our Future|work=[[Heavy.com|Heavy]]|last=Dwilson|first=Stephanie Dube|date=12 June 2019|accessdate=1 July 2019}}</ref> Also featured in the series is Australian actor [[Maia Mitchell]].<ref name=\"DS SFOF\">{{cite web|url=https://www.digitalspy.com/tv/a27715097/black-mirror-spin-off-you-tube-little-stories-from-our-future/|title=Here's why you probably won't see Black Mirror's first spin-off|work=[[Digital Spy]]|last=Jeffery|first=Morgan|date=4 June 2019|accessdate=1 July 2019}}</ref>\n\n=== Literature ===\nIn June 2018, Brooker announced that he, along with Annabel Jones and [[Jason Arnopp]], have written an oral history companion to the series titled ''Inside Black Mirror''. The book features sections on each of the 19 episodes in the first four series, containing conversational interviews from cast and crew and images from the episodes and behind the scenes.<ref name=\"books cancelled\"/><ref>{{cite book|last=Brooker|first=Charlie|last2=Jones|first2=Annabel|date=1 November 2018|title=Inside Black Mirror|publisher=[[Penguin Random House]]|isbn=9781529102581}}</ref> The book was released in the UK on 1 November 2018 and in the US on 20 November 2018 from [[Penguin Random House]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.cosmopolitan.com/uk/entertainment/a23279428/inside-black-mirror-book/|title=If you're obsessed with Black Mirror, you need the new Inside Black Mirror book|work=[[Cosmopolitan (magazine)|Cosmopolitan]]|last=Baxter|first=Dusty|date=17 September 2018|accessdate=1 November 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20181127064705/https://www.cosmopolitan.com/uk/entertainment/a23279428/inside-black-mirror-book/|archive-date=27 November 2018|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.penguinrandomhouse.com/books/600315/inside-black-mirror-by-charlie-brooker-and-annabel-jones-with-jason-arnopp/9781984823489/|title=Inside Black Mirror by Charlie Brooker, Annabel Jones, Jason Arnopp {{!}} PenguinRandomHouse.com|website=PenguinRandomhouse.com|language=en-US|access-date=1 November 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180820234852/https://www.penguinrandomhouse.com/books/600315/inside-black-mirror-by-charlie-brooker-and-annabel-jones-with-jason-arnopp/9781984823489/|archive-date=20 August 2018|url-status=live}}</ref> ''[[Starburst (magazine)|Starburst]]'' rated the book ten out of ten stars, praising its \"wonderfully-comprehensive format\" and summarising it as \"blunt, brittle, often killingly funny and lavishly-illustrated\".<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.starburstmagazine.com/reviews/inside-black-mirror|title=Inside Black Mirror|work=[[Starburst (magazine)|Starburst]]|accessdate=17 July 2019}}</ref>\n\nIn June 2017, Brooker announced a series of novels based on ''Black Mirror'' that will offer \"new, original, darkly satirical stories that tap into our collective unease about the modern world\". Brooker will edit three volumes of novellas that will feature anthology short stories by different authors.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.thewrap.com/black-mirror-to-be-adapted-into-a-book-series/ |title='Black Mirror' to Be Adapted Into a Book Series |date=13 June 2017 |website=TheWrap |access-date=14 June 2017 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170613200406/http://www.thewrap.com/black-mirror-to-be-adapted-into-a-book-series/ |archive-date=13 June 2017 |url-status=live }}</ref><ref name=\":0\" /> The first instalment was scheduled to include stories written by [[Cory Doctorow]], [[Claire North]] and [[Sylvain Neuvel]].<ref>{{Cite book|title=Black Mirror Volume 1 |publisher=Amazon |id= {{ASIN|1785036742|country=uk}} }}</ref> Initially scheduled for release in 2018 and 2019,<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.theguardian.com/books/booksblog/2017/jun/14/charlie-brooker-black-mirror-spin-off-books-but-who-should-write-them |title=Charlie Brooker's Black Mirror to spin off into books&nbsp;\u2013 but who should write them? |last=Barnett |first=David |date=14 June 2017 |work=The Guardian |accessdate=28 September 2017 |issn=0261-3077 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170925095225/https://www.theguardian.com/books/booksblog/2017/jun/14/charlie-brooker-black-mirror-spin-off-books-but-who-should-write-them |archive-date=25 September 2017 |url-status=live }}</ref> the project was postponed indefinitely as Brooker and Jones could not dedicate enough time to it.<ref name=\"books cancelled\">{{cite web|url=http://www.digitalspy.com/tv/black-mirror/news/a869500/black-mirror-spin-off-novels-cancelled/|title=Charlie Brooker reveals why planned Black Mirror spin-offs novels have been shelved|work=[[Digital Spy]]|last=Jeffery|first=Morgan|date=29 October 2018|accessdate=1 November 2018}}</ref>\n\n===Board game===\n{{Main|Nosedive (board game)}}\nBased on the third series episode \"[[Nosedive (Black Mirror)|Nosedive]]\", the board game ''Nosedive'' was produced by [[Asmodee]]. Released on 25 November 2018, the game requires between three and six players and is designed to last for roughly 45 minutes.<ref>{{cite web | url = https://www.polygon.com/2018/11/15/18097545/black-mirror-nosedive-board-game-asmodee | title = Black Mirror's nightmarish social media episode is now a board game | first = Michael | last = McWhertor | date = 15 November 2018 | accessdate = 1 July 2019 | work = [[Polygon (website)|Polygon]] }}</ref>\n\n== References ==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n== Further reading ==\n* {{cite journal |url=https://www.newyorker.com/magazine/2015/01/05/button-pusher |title=Button-Pusher: The seductive dystopia of 'Black Mirror' |first=Emily |last=Nussbaum |date=January 2015 |journal=[[The New Yorker]] |accessdate=}}\n\n== External links ==\n{{sisterlinks|display=''Black Mirror''|d=Q558112|c=Category:Black Mirror|n=no|b=no|v=no|voy=no|wikt=no|s=no|species=no